{"sessions":[{"intendedAudience":"This presentation is targeted towards developers and architects who use messaging within their systems. Participants will get an overview of how ActiveMQ and Kafka work under the covers, and how tradeoffs within these products affects application designs. No experience with messaging is assumed. Some code in slides.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jakub Korab","bio":"Jakub Korab is an independent consultant specialising in open source messaging and integration, helping companies to apply Apache ActiveMQ and Apache Kafka. His experience spans everything from architecture to troubleshooting across a number of industries that have included transportation, banking, law enforcement, gambling, logistics, utilities and space exploration. In 2016 he will complete his 100th messaging engagement.","sessionId":"9a5a84def65d4c3880e0154c0adf50e5"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"9a5a84def65d4c3880e0154c0adf50e5","abstract":"Messaging systems underpin architectures ranging from stream processing, through to event sourcing and communication between loosely-coupled microservices. To most developers the technology is not core to the business they work in, and is often disregarded as “just a pipe” for message distribution. Without understanding their capabilities and underlying design decisions, we tell ourselves myths how these systems “should” work and are frustrated in production by behaviours coming from design trade-offs.\n\nIn this session you will learn how to think about messaging as we compare and contrast the approaches taken by two similar but fundamentally different messaging platforms – Apache ActiveMQ and Apache Kafka. We will discuss how their underlying philosophies impact message distribution, reliability, scalability, and performance.\n\nAlong the way we will dip into how IOPS, latency and bandwidth affect throughput, why messaging systems do not play nicely with containers, and the unicorn of once-and-only-once delivery in distributed systems.","published":"true","title":"The Myth of the Magical Messaging Fabric","slug":"the_myth_of_the_magical_messagin"},{"intendedAudience":"Tilhørere bør ha erfaring med smidige prosjekter og kunnskap om rammene og kompromissene som inngår i arkitekturavgjørelser. Løsningsarkitekter og seniorutviklere vil få størst utbytte av presentasjonen.","keywords":["distributedsystems, scalability, agile architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Kristoffer Dyrkorn","bio":"Kristoffer Dyrkorn er teknolog i BEKK. De siste 15 årene har Kristoffer jobbet som utvikler, prosjektleder, løsningsarkitekt og rådgiver på ulike prosjekter i Norge. Han har i løpet av den tiden vært borti mange forskjellige teknologier og løst en god del mystiske problemer. Kristoffer har dyp kompetanse på skalerbarhet og løpende arkitekturutforming og har holdt workshops og presentasjoner om brukervennlighet og arkitektur på konferanser i Norge, Europa og USA.","sessionId":"9cd53aacae26476ca86bacc9fa76457d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"9cd53aacae26476ca86bacc9fa76457d","abstract":"Presentasjonen går igjennom erfaringer vi har fått underveis i arbeidet med å lage en løsning for å samle inn data om vegtrafikken i Norge. Systemet gir ut høykvalitets informasjon i nær sanntid og er basert på en uvanlig kombinasjon av sensorer, embedded devices, protokoller og programvare.\n\nGjennom dette arbeidet har vi fått erfaring i å bygge et distribuert system med en arkitektur i stadig endring. Presentasjonen vil ta for seg noen av problemene vi har hatt underveis og samtidig illustrere hvordan vi mener man bør gå fram for å lage løsninger som er mottakelige for forandringer.  \n\nPresentasjonen vil vise at det er mange paralleller mellom det å oppnå smidighet i arkitekturer og det å oppnå god skalerbarhet.","published":"true","title":"Smidig arkitektur handler egentlig om skalerbarhet","slug":"smidig_arkitektur_handler_egentl"},{"intendedAudience":"Foredraget krever ingen tidligere erfaring med DDD, men det er fordelaktig om du har kjennskap til de utfordringene prinsippene derfra prøver å løse, enten det er store monolitter som en ønsker å modularisere eller om du sliter med en flokk mikrotjenester som får gjeting av katter til å virke enkelt. Foredraget vil være relevant for både utviklere, arkitekter og produkteiere.","keywords":["architecture","ddd","microservices"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Trond Hjorteland","bio":"Trond er en kodende arkitekt fra konsulentselskapet Scienta og har lang erfaring med store, komplekse og forretningskritiske applikasjoner, primært mellomvare- og backendsystemer. Han har spesialkompetanse innen tjenesteorientering, domene-drevet design og hendelsesdrevet arkitektur.","sessionId":"748a8b39b7a849d0b8ee890b3c144629"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"748a8b39b7a849d0b8ee890b3c144629","abstract":"Hvor relevant er domene-drevet design (DDD) 13 år etter Eric Evans’ velkjente blå bok kom ut for første gang? Boken og miljøet den vokste ut av var preget av hvordan større virksomheter bygget sine IT-systemer tidlig på 2000-tallet, dominert av de to store og altomfattende plattformene J2EE og .NET, så da er det naturlig å spørre seg hvordan den da kan passe inn i en verden preget av mikrotjenester, smidige metodikker og en myriade av teknologier og plattformer. På mange måter passer sentrale DDD-konsepter som “bounded context”, “core domain”, “ubiquitous language”, “distillation” og “aggregates” enda bedre inn i en slik verden enn i de store monolittene vi slet med den gang. Denne velfylte verktøykassen inneholder teknikker for hvordan vi som teknikere kan komme mye tettere på forretningen for å bedre forstå deres visjoner og behov; prinsipper for hvordan vi bedre kan designe vedlikeholdbare løsninger som er direkte koblet til de individuelle domene i bedriften; og maler for hvordan vi kan bygge autonome komponenter på en smidig måte.","published":"true","title":"Mikrotjenester uten domenedrevet design er risikosport!","slug":"mikrotjenester_uten_domenedrevet"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette foredraget sikter seg inn på et bredt publikum! Jobber du med IoT/mikrokontrollere, kan dette foredraget by på kunnskap og utfordringer du selv kan komme til å støte på. Ingen forkunnskaper er nødvendig.","keywords":["internet of things","node-red","microcontrollers"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nikhil André Luthra","bio":"Utvikler som jobber i Bouvet Norge, hvor jeg startet et internt maker-/hackerspace med gadgets og elektronikk som 3D-printere, mikrokontrollere, verktøy og morsomme dingser. Har arrangert flere kurs innen 3D-printing, modellering og lodding. Holder foredrag om IoT og fremtidsteknologi for kunder og på eksterne arrangementer.\n\nJeg organiserer også Internet of Things Oslo meetup, hvor folk som er interessert i IoT kan presentere og følge med på prosjekter som blir kjørt rundt omkring i landet.","sessionId":"82a17f32a5de4750b187b75f4dd69583"},{"name":"Martin Gravråk","bio":"Martin  har jobbet som systemutvikler i 10 år, og har bygget systemer for alt fra bank og forsikring til olje og jernbane.  Elsker konseptet med internet of things, og mener at hvis noe ikke har wifi så er det ikke verdt å eie. Dette har ført til at det meste i hjemmet inkludert tannbørste,  belysning, baderomsvekt, seng,  og kjøleskap er koblet på nett.\n\nDet forrige IOT prosjekt var en hjemmelaget robot-arm som ble presentert på NDC i 2015, nå har vi tatt steget videre til et kommersielt IOT prosjekt og Javazone.","sessionId":"82a17f32a5de4750b187b75f4dd69583"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"82a17f32a5de4750b187b75f4dd69583","abstract":"Våre oppdragsgivere får ikke alltid den leveransen de forventer – i positiv forstand. Så da de ba oss om 'design til en musematte og en plakat' måtte det bli noe helt annet. Nærmere bestemt en IoT-installasjon som sekunderer et helt kundesenter i hvor gjerrige de greier å være.\n\nI dette foredraget vil du høre om hvordan to programvareutviklere hoppet inn i sitt første kommersielle IoT-prosjekt for en kunde. Hva skjer når du bruker kjente metodikker for programvare i et hardware prosjekt? Hva gjør du når du har veldig dårlig tid til å levere et fysisk produkt? Litervis med vann og elektronikk i samme installasjon kan også by på skumle scenarier.\n\nVi dro inn flere teknologier i dette prosjektet, blant annet:\n- Node-red\n- Raspberry Pi\n- ESP8266\n- Highcharts\n- Firebase\n\nVi går gjennom problemene, utfordringene, gledene og aha-opplevelsene vi støtte på, og disse er godt dokumentert med bilder og video!","published":"true","title":"Erfaringer fra et kommersielt IoT Prosjekt hos Viasat","slug":"erfaringer_fra_et_kommersielt_io"},{"intendedAudience":"the participant will enjoy the session more if they have some basic experience of running Kafka and can relate to our mistakes.","keywords":["kafka","bigdata","experiencereports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Audun Fauchald Strand","bio":"Audun har jobbet som utvikler og arkitekt i 10 år. Han liker store kompliserte systemer, diskusjoner, og ting som google lager.","sessionId":"1435fb0dd762435c9a27617eee86dc97"},{"name":"Henning Spjelkavik","bio":"Henning Spjelkavik har i det siste jobbet med både arkitektur, ytelse og skalering på FINN.no, i tillegg til å vedlikeholde én av Norges ledende karttjenester. Hans favorittverktøy er wireshark, bash og en liten leatherman.","sessionId":"1435fb0dd762435c9a27617eee86dc97"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"1435fb0dd762435c9a27617eee86dc97","abstract":"Topic: Operations (and development) - how we set up Kafka without really understand our own requirements or how to configure Kafka to fullfill them\n\n**\n\nKafka was introduced as part of a proof of concept for collecting 20 million click events a day. Other teams started using Kafka for different purposes, but our configuration was still as if it was a prototype. This lead to scaling problems, stability problems, and lost messages. We'll tell you what we did, and how we solved it. Enjoy our mistakes and learn!\n\n**\n\n4 years of using Kafka without really understanding the documentation, has taught us a lot. Join this session, and learn from our suboptimal solutions!\n\nAt FINN.no, Norway's biggest online classifieds site, we have been using Kafka since version 0.7 in 2012. Kafka was introduced as part of a proof of concept for collecting click events from our web front end, which had approximately 40 million page views a day. The Kafka cluster became popular, and more and more teams started using it, with our default settings. Still we did not have anyone dedicated to running and configuring Kafka - it was a best effort, and usually the latest person touching the defaults won. As the traffic, number of use cases, and topics grew, we got some scaling problems, stability problems, lost messages and a general feeling among developers that \"our kafka cluster was unstable\".\n\nIn the end we had to put some effort into find out what we ran, which properties we really needed, and get control over the configuration, our library code and how our clients used Kafka. Since August we haven't had a complaint, nor downtime on our Kafka cluster.\n\nAs the Germans say \"Schadenfreude ist die schönste Freude\".\n\nMajor points:\n- Making our own client library, trying to \"simplify\" our developers' life\n- Using a single cluster, with a single configuration, for vastly different purposes (click event streams and credit card payment)\n- Single Zookeeper connection over a load balancer\n- 8 Zookeeper nodes and 8 Kafka nodes - on the same 8 servers\n- Running Kafka on nodes that already were nearly out of memory\n- Arbitrary number of replicas\n- Arbitrary number of partitions, default 128\n- Auto create of topics\n- Unclean leader election for topics requiring strict reliability\n- No schema repository\n- Layered schemas; single IDL for thrift, java artifacts for mapping\n- \"What is client rebalance - this has to be a bug\"\n- Not understanding of how auto commits work\n\nSlides in English, presentation in Norwegian","published":"true","title":"101 ways of configuring Kafka - badly  ; Hva FINN.no har lært av å kjøre Kafka","slug":"101_ways_of_configuring_kafka__b"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is intended for people with an interest in performance, especially in the context of applications that run on top of the JVM. There is not much prior knowledge required although it is beneficial to have a very basic understanding of the JVM and the available tooling (e.g. Java Flight Recorder). I intend to show some code snippets on my slides and maybe do a benchmark live demo (but no live coding).","keywords":["performance"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Daniel Mitterdorfer","bio":"Daniel Mitterdorfer is a software engineer at Elastic working on Elasticsearch. He is interested in CPU architecture, performance in general and concurrency on the JVM.","sessionId":"dfba124acbe7423fb2cc5ddef0e3e64a"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"dfba124acbe7423fb2cc5ddef0e3e64a","abstract":"There are lots of pitfalls when creating a benchmark, yet many people just write a simple driver script, run it and use the resulting numbers without any further verification. This can result in bad decisions.\n\nIn this talk, we describe how we approached this problem when creating a macrobenchmarking framework for the popular search engine Elasticsearch. Based on this example, we share our experience, show you concrete techniques to spot accidental bottlenecks and other common problems in benchmarks in order to get accurate benchmark results.","published":"true","title":"Benchmarking Elasticsearch","slug":"benchmarking_elasticsearch"},{"intendedAudience":"This session is for experienced developers, architects and technical leaders. The talk does contains no code, but addresses the complexity at a design level with regards to services and databases.","keywords":["microservices","domain driven design","organization structure"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sebastian Verheughe","bio":"Chief Enterprise Architect @ FINN.no, previously worked at Telenor for 7 years with last responsibility for the service architecture (middleware) for mobile services. Worked with development and architecture professionally for 16 years. Introduced NOSQL graph databases into Telenor some years ago, and in general believes in finding the right tool for the right problem is the correct strategy in any organization. Still codes once in a while...","sessionId":"f357f3922e71480fa4de4c8c0055844b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"f357f3922e71480fa4de4c8c0055844b","abstract":"Experience talk about how architecture and organization come together to address the challenges we face at FINN.no. How we believe decentralised ownership and decision making can help improve development speed and product quality over time. Where we still see complexity in FINN after we started using micro services. And how we try to use the inverse Conway manoeuvre together with DDD to extract the strategic parts of our legacy code. The talk will also address how we currently address data flows across services, and how we are moving in the direction of using events and data streams.","published":"true","title":"Strategic Design by Architecture and Organisation @ FINN.no","slug":"strategic_design_by_architecture"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers writing code that touches crypto, e.g. client-side cookies, encrypted storage of files, masked strings sent to the client UI, WS-Security etc.\nSome code in slides / live-coding in demos","keywords":["security","cryptography","hacking"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Erlend Oftedal","bio":"Erlend has worked as a developer and security tester for over 10 years. He has built open source security tools, and spoken at national and international developer and security conferences.","sessionId":"2b2f042d0f0f48979fd90ae9b249fc8b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"2b2f042d0f0f48979fd90ae9b249fc8b","abstract":"We using an increasing amount of crypto in our code to protect our assets. However we can easily go wrong if we don't know how to use it correctly. In this talk we will look at what can go wrong when crypto is used the wrong way. We will NOT dive into the algorithms themselves, but look at what the different primitives give us and what happens when our expectations are wrong.","published":"true","title":"Broken crypto is broken","slug":"broken_crypto_is_broken"},{"intendedAudience":"Anybody developing concurrent programs for the JVM. Code in slides.","keywords":["javase","concurrency","jvm"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Rafael Winterhalter","bio":"Rafael works as a software consultant in Oslo, Norway. He is a proponent of static typing and a JVM enthusiast with particular interest in code instrumentation, concurrency and functional programming. Rafael blogs about software development, regularly presents at conferences and was pronounced a JavaOne Rock Star. When coding outside of his work place, he contributes to a wide range of open source projects and often works on Byte Buddy, a library for simple runtime code generation for the Java virtual machine. For his work, Rafael received a Duke's Choice award and was elected a Java Champion.","sessionId":"6e971893406947d99cf6ddd049ff0575"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"6e971893406947d99cf6ddd049ff0575","abstract":"At first glance, writing concurrent programs in Java seems like a straight-forward task. But the devil is in the detail. Fortunately, these details are strictly regulated by the Java memory model which, roughly speaking, decides what values a program can observe for a field at any given time. Without respecting the memory model, a Java program might behave erratic and yield bugs that only occure on some hardware platforms. This presentation summarizes the guarantees that are given by Java's memory model and teaches how to properly use volatile and final fields or synchronized code blocks. Instead of discussing the model in terms of memory model formalisms, this presentation builds on easy-to follow Java code examples.","published":"true","title":"The Java memory model made easy","slug":"the_java_memory_model_made_easy"},{"intendedAudience":"Beginner \nForedraget er for alle som vil lære litt om maskinlæring. Det vil bli vist kode i presentasjonen, og du kan jaggu kjøre eksemplene selv også ved å klone vårt GitHub repo.","keywords":["maskinlæring"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Aleksander Bai","bio":"Aleksander Bai er seniorforsker hos Norsk Regnesentral. Han har mange års erfaring som både gründer og  IT-konsulent hos store og små aktører, før han fikk sansen for anvendt forskning. Aleksander er en stor tilhenger av open source og maskinlæring, og jobber for tiden med en doktorgrad hvor maskinlæring er sentralt.","sessionId":"75de0b2507fb4f8d8ad7031d94e079ad"},{"name":"Heidi Mork","bio":"Heidi Mork er også seniorforsker hos Norsk Regnesentral. Hun har en doktorgrad i matematikk om noe uforståelige greier, og har tidligere jobbet mange år som utvikler i et konsulentfirma. Heidi er interessert i det meste som har med programmering å gjøre, og liker å lære nye ting, som for eksempel maskinlæring.","sessionId":"75de0b2507fb4f8d8ad7031d94e079ad"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"75de0b2507fb4f8d8ad7031d94e079ad","abstract":"Lyst til å lære om maskinlæring? Interessert i hva du kan bruke det til i ditt prosjekt? \nI dette foredraget går vi gjennom grunnleggende maskinlæringsmetoder. Vi forklarer historien bak maskinlæring og teorien for de ulike metodene. Vi viser deg hvilke Java-biblioteker som kan gjøre jobben for deg, og ikke minst hva du kan bruke maskinlæring til i prosjektet ditt.\nFor å lage eksempler til de ulike maskinlæringsmetodene har vi tatt utgangspunkt i data om presentasjoner og foredragsholdere på tidligere års JavaZone. Vi analyserer og kategoriserer dataene for å finne nye og ukjente sammenhenger. Hvilke selskaper holder de mest avanserte presentasjonene og hvilke grupper foredragsholdere bruker flest superlativer i beskrivelsen av seg selv?\nTil slutt presenter vi det optimale JavaZone-abstractet som er generert helt automatisk fra tidligere abstracts.","published":"true","title":"Maskinlæring skriver din neste presentasjon!","slug":"maskinlring_skriver_din_neste_pr"},{"intendedAudience":"The target audience is experienced Java developers willing to get a detailed overview on how does the security sandbox model of the Java platform work and what are the future directions for extension of that model in new version of the platform.","keywords":["javase","security","openjdk"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Martin Toshev","bio":"Martin is a Java enthusiast and one of the leads of the Bulgarian Java Users group (BG JUG). He is a certified Java professional (SCJP6) and a certified IBM cloud computing solution advisor. His areas of interest include the wide range of Java-related technologies (such as Servlets, JSP, JAXB, JAXP, JMS, JMX, JAX-RS, JAX-WS, Hibernate, Spring Framework, Liferay Portal and Eclipse RCP), cloud computing technologies, cloud-based software architectures, enterprise application integration, relational and NoSQL databases. You can reach him for any Java and FOSS-related topics (especially Eclipse and the OpenJDK). Martin is a regular speaker at Java conferences and one of the organizers behind the jPrime conference in Bulgaria (http://jprime.io/).\n\nRecent talks:\nSpring RabbitMQ (VoxxedDays 2016, Istanbul Turkey)\nSecurity Architecture of the Java Platform (jDays 2016, Gothenburg, Sweden)\nSecurity Architecture of the Java Platform (VoxxedDays 2016, Zurich, Switzerland)\nSpring RabbitMQ (JavaScop 2015, Skopie, Macedonia)\nSecurity Architecture of the Java Platform (JavaDay 2015, Kiev, Ukraine)","sessionId":"fc1bc2a67f7a4c0a8defd842a0ee740d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"fc1bc2a67f7a4c0a8defd842a0ee740d","abstract":"The session provides an overview of the security architecture of the Java platform in terms of its evolution throughout the versions of the JDK up to JDK 9 and beyond. The utilities that fullfill the security portfolio of the JDK will be discussed briefly along with several guidelines in designing and implementing secure applications by following security best practices.","published":"true","title":"Evolution of the Java Security Architecture","slug":"evolution_of_the_java_security_a"},{"intendedAudience":"This session will be structured around a robust and easily-applied core method, but with most focus on the less-discussed and small-thing-but-large-impact gotchas which we've caught (and failed to catch) over the last two years.  We want to have live demos too time and infrastructure allowing.\n\nThe end result should be both educational and entertaining.","keywords":["nonfunctional","testing","microservices"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Andrew Harmel-Law","bio":"Experienced both across the software development lifecycle and in many sectors, Andrew loves leading teams and building large-scale software solutions. He understands that people, tooling, architecture and process all have key roles to play in achieving this. \n\nTo learn, Andrew tries to share both his experiences and his code as widely as possible. He is Capgemini UK's OSS advocate and recently led the creation of an internal Software Craftsmanship Course to help others adopt XP programming practices. He also set up the Capgemini Engineering Blog. This sharing comes not only from his formal consulting engagements - he also mentors undergraduates, posts blogs, speaks and contributes to open source projects and forums.","sessionId":"fa3757309f0c41ea926dd4fa80adadc2"},{"name":"Kevin Rudland","bio":"An experienced Senior Software Engineer with Capgemini, having worked on projects across a variety of problem domains and industries. Kevin loves solving big complex problems for clients and strives to find simple elegant solutions. Kevin is passionate about helping junior developers and helps run a variety of Software engineering courses across Capgemini on subjects such as OO, TDD and pair programming.","sessionId":"fa3757309f0c41ea926dd4fa80adadc2"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"fa3757309f0c41ea926dd4fa80adadc2","abstract":"We've been working on and incrementally deploying and upgrading a growing set of Microservices for two years now.  They support the website for a UK household-name company, and as such, through testing of every release is vital.\n\nOver this time we've spent more and more time on our performance testing. In this session we'll describe our current approach, illustrated with lashings of war stories:\n\n  * plan - driving all your tests from your requirements, and your greatest fears\n  * setup - the importance of being as prod-like as possible, especially when you're not Netflix. Oh, and repeatability\n  * perform - where request mix, load profile, duration, network flakiness and failure in its myriad forms are key\n  * record - measurement, percentiles, and analysis\n  * summarise - pulling out the headlines\n  * investigation - when things went a bit weird and you have no idea why\n  * improve - not just perf. but also visibility and diagnose-ability\n  * automate - because CI/CD pipelines aren't just for functional tests\n\nAs an added bonus we've done all this with free tools so you'll get some demos and will then be able to go away and try things out for yourselves.","published":"true","title":"Distributed Architecture and Design: A Scientific Approach","slug":"distributed_architecture_and_des"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere med kjennskap til java-syntaks eller funksjonell programmering. Code in slides and live coding.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Axel Wathne","bio":"Begynte å lære Java for 16 år siden og jobber i Webstep","sessionId":"eee6d440b9de44879941e243cd5d8dde"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"eee6d440b9de44879941e243cd5d8dde","abstract":"Immutables er et bibliotek for generering av klasser med rik standardfunksjonalitet, både foranderlige og uforanderlige. Javaslang er en erstatning for de innebygde datastrukturene i java.util som tar sikte på renere kode enn Stream-APIet  og utstrakt bruk av uforanderlige datastrukturer og funksjonell programmering. De er begge i versjon 2 nå, betyr det at det er på tide å vurdere å ta dem i bruk?","published":"true","title":"En ny følelse av Java med Immutables og Javaslang","slug":"en_ny_flelse_av_java_med_immutab"},{"intendedAudience":"Beginners to experts should each be available to take away something from the talk. The audience will get a glimpse into Java-based game development, WORA API design principles, special considerations when doing cross-platform development, and how to manage a popular OSS project. The audience needs to be familiar with basic Java. Code in slides and some very minor live coding.","keywords":["game development, cross-platform, war stories"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mario Zechner","bio":"Machine learner and middle management in an R&D company in a previous life, now enjoying writing Ahead-of-Time compilers and the tooling around them to get Java onto iOS. Night-time game (middleware) developer and benevolent OSS project dictator at libGDX. Author of best selling book \"Beginning Android Games\".","sessionId":"c3e0a3bf2fb7406fb7dac13772ac3559"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"c3e0a3bf2fb7406fb7dac13772ac3559","abstract":"Duke’s Choice Award winner libGDX is an open source cross-platform game development framework enabling its users to target Windows, Linux, Mac OS X, Android, iOS, BlackBerry, Windows Phone 10, and WebGL-enabled browsers with a single codebase. libGDX is used extensively around the world by everyone from indie developers to large studios, demonstrating the validity of Java for game development. This session provides an introduction to libGDX, including a detailed look under the covers and an exploration of the lessons learned during its development. It includes topics such as API design, platform fragmentation, cross-platform build systems, and performance considerations. It also covers aspects of OSS development such as community building and team management.","published":"true","title":"It’s All Fun and Games: Cross-Platform Game Development with Java and libGDX","slug":"its_all_fun_and_games_crossplatf"},{"intendedAudience":"Systemeiere, prosjektledere, utviklere\nIngen kode","keywords":["yteslsestest","komplekse systemer"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Vegar Engen","bio":"Vegar gikk ut fra NTNU i 2014 med en sivilingeniørutdannelse innen datateknologi. Etter endt studie har Vegar jobbet som konsulent for Visma Consulting og har jobbet med ytelsestest på NAV og UDI de siste 2 årene.","sessionId":"2e727e4c2a3c467d81c546f99a0adf44"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"2e727e4c2a3c467d81c546f99a0adf44","abstract":"Under utvikling av store komplekse systemer er det ofte stor usikkerhet rundt hvor godt applikasjonen yter. Hvilke tiltak kan gjøres før koden går i prod for å sikre at kapasiteten på servere er tilstrekkelig, uten at det blir overkapasitet. Lyntalen vil gi et overblikk over hvordan dette gjøres i NAV.","published":"true","title":"Hvordan sikre høy ytelse i komplekse systemer?","slug":"hvordan_sikre_hy_ytelse_i_komple"},{"intendedAudience":"Every Java web developer should attend this session in order to learn how to create self defending web applications with Java. Code will be shown in slides as well as in the live demo (IDE).","keywords":["security","web","self defending"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Dominik Schadow","bio":"Dominik Schadow has more than 10 years of experience in Java development and is working as a senior consultant at bridgingIT in Stuttgart (Germany). He is specialized on Java enterprise application architecture and development with Spring and JEE and a strong advocate on the secure development of Java based web applications. He is a regular speaker about various Java security topics at different conferences, author of a German book about the development of secure Java web applications and has written many articles in German IT magazines. In his spare time, he is the lead of the JCrypTool open source project, an extensible cryptography e-learning application.","sessionId":"f118dab1a2a643469d7ee81e67f30e63"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"f118dab1a2a643469d7ee81e67f30e63","abstract":"One important mitigation to prevent attacks on web applications is secure development. But one layer of security is not enough. So why not develop an application that protects and defends itself? Developers know best what needs to be protected and how to identify unusual behavior. That’s ‘Application Intrusion Detection’. In addition to the subsequent analysis of an attack, it enables the application to detect an ongoing attack itself. And to respond to an attack automatically and in real time with appropriate defense measures – before an attacker gains control of the application. This session will show you how to create more secure Java web applications by adding self-defending capabilities by utilizing ‘Application Intrusion Detection’.","published":"true","title":"The Web Application Strikes Back","slug":"the_web_application_strikes_back"},{"intendedAudience":"Anybody wanting to gather data from any source they can think of.\nCode in slides","keywords":["logging","loganalysis"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Philipp Krenn","bio":"Philipp is a Developer Advocate at Elastic, spreading the love and knowledge of full-text search, analytics, and real-time data. He is a frequent speaker at conferences and meetups about all things search & analytics, databases, cloud computing, and devops. Philipp lives in Vienna where he enjoys experimenting with software, organizing meetups, and sports.","sessionId":"d67e422d028e4a4894d6115eab5bd01a"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"d67e422d028e4a4894d6115eab5bd01a","abstract":"The Elastic Stack is widely used to collect logs with Logstash, analyze and search the data with Elasticsearch, and visualize what is happening in your system with Kibana. Now there is a new platform for shipping many types of operational data: Beats. It can be used to collect, parse, and ship any type of data.\nThis talk provides an overview of the Beats platform and dives into gathering system metrics, tapping your wire data, and using real-time file analytics.","published":"true","title":"Collect all the things with Beats","slug":"collect_all_the_things_with_beat"},{"intendedAudience":"> Who should attend this session?\nDevelopers, data scientists, everyone who has basic SQL skills\n\n> How will the participants benefit from attending?\n90% of the participants will learn things they've never heard before, but which they could use immediately in their projects.\n\n> Explicitly state what your audience needs to know\nBasic SQL skills are required. If participants have never worked with SQL, they might be pretty lost.\n\n> To indicate the amount of code in your talk we recommend you use the following phrases\nCode in slides","keywords":["sql","nosql","big data"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lukas Eder","bio":"Lukas Eder is the founder and CEO of Data Geekery GmbH, located in Zurich, Switzerland. With his company he has been selling database products and services around Java and SQL since 2013. Ever since his Master’s studies at EPFL in 2006, he has been fascinated by the interaction of Java and SQL. Most of this experience he has obtained in the Swiss E-Banking field through various variants (JDBC, Hibernate, mostly with Oracle). As a Java Champion, he is happy to share this knowledge at various conferences, JUGs, in-house presentations and on his blog. Here’s his conference and JUG talk schedule for the most recent time: http://www.jooq.org/news.","sessionId":"f8e6cd12799245da9856a942fafec50c"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"f8e6cd12799245da9856a942fafec50c","abstract":"SQL is the winning language of Big Data. Whether you’re running a classic relational database, a column store (“NewSQL”), or a non-relational storage system (“NoSQL”), a powerful, declarative, SQL-based query language makes the difference. The SQL standard has evolved drastically in the past decades, and so have its commercial and open source implementations.\n\nIn this fast-paced talk, we’re going to look at very peculiar and interesting data problems and how we can solve them with SQL. We’ll explore common table expressions, hierarchical SQL, table-valued functions, lateral joins, row value expressions, window functions, and advanced data types, such as XML and JSON. And we’ll look at Oracle’s mysterious MODEL and MATCH_RECOGNIZE clauses, devices whose mystery is only exceeded by their power. Most importantly, however, we’re going to learn that everyone can write advanced SQL. Once you learn the basics in these tricks, you’re going to love SQL even more.","published":"true","title":"10 SQL Tricks that You Didn't Think Were Possible","slug":"10_sql_tricks_that_you_didnt_thi"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is for developers and architects who have a basic understanding of functional programming and design patterns described by the Gang of Four.","keywords":["reactive","functionalprogramming","reactive systems"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jan Carsten Lohmüller","bio":"Jan Carsten is a software developer, coffee enthusiast and bearded man. Since doing his studies at university of Bonn and university of Hamburg he has been actively working in the software industry, utilizing various technologies. He has been involved in both start-ups as well as established global organizations and research. Jan is currently working in the software consultancy business with emphasis on C#, Java, architecture and security, functional programming and software craftsmanship.","sessionId":"57fbba4ffe6d42c19cb4754a8e018df2"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"57fbba4ffe6d42c19cb4754a8e018df2","abstract":"Reactive Programming is described as the next big thing of a programming paradigm.\nThe most common thoughts you will read about Reactive Programming is that it makes use of immutable streams and the propagation of change. At first when you hear propagation of change you might think about the observer pattern which will be delimited from what we think of Reactive Programming.\nWith the help of small examples, modifying arrays, we will get to know lambda expressions, filter expressions and map/reduce. Adding the concept of observables we inspect the subscription to a stream of events which turns the observer pattern the other way around and omits the usage of callbacks.\nOf course there is already a manifesto, as for all fresh programming paradigms, you can sign. The manifesto states four principles of Reactive Programming at which we will take a closer look: Reactive systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message driven.\nAfter this overview on Reactive Programming we ask the following questions:\n* Is Reactive Programming new after all?\n* How do you test reactive systems?\n* Who has control over a reactive system when everything is based on change?","published":"true","title":"I have a stream - Insights in Reactive Programming","slug":"i_have_a_stream__insights_in_rea"},{"intendedAudience":"Litt kjennskap til Angular2 . Er nyskjerrig på redux, men erfaring med redux er ikke nødvendig. Code in slides.","keywords":["angular2","frontend","redux"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Steffen Hageland","bio":"Utvikler i BEKK. Jobber i hovedsak på relativt frontend-tunge applikasjoner - hvor de fleste er skrevet i Angular. Men har også jobbet med andre rammeverk som f.eks. React. Har den siste tiden bygget kompetanse på angular2, og sett på hvordan man kan migrere eksisterende angular-applikasjoner over til den nye plattformen.","sessionId":"446fdcca37f64ea0bacffd5ed26f6210"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"446fdcca37f64ea0bacffd5ed26f6210","abstract":"Redux er et rammeverk som skal ta hånd om tilstanden til applikasjonen for deg. Ved å flytte tilstanden ut av komponentene kan du lettere lage små komponenter som er lette å gjenbruke. Debuggeren til Redux lar deg også ta en tidsreise gjennom de ulike tilstandene applikasjonen har vært i - og på den måten gjøre deg lett for deg som utvikler å forstå hvordan du endte opp i en bestemt tilstand.\n\nI denne lyntalen vil vi se på hvordan vi kan bruke Redux sammen med Angular2 og hvordan det kan være med på å gjøre dine angular-applikasjoner bedre.","published":"true","title":"Redux + Angular2 = sant","slug":"redux__angular2__sant"},{"intendedAudience":"The presentation is suitable for all Java developers. Attendees should preferably have some experience with debugging. \nThe presentation will be based on live debugging.","keywords":["tools","debugging","craftsmanship"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Martin Skarsaune","bio":"Martin is a passionate software developer working for Kantega AS. His primary interest is the core Java platform and tools.","sessionId":"6c1a2dacb95c4ad09ff0afae7db715cc"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"6c1a2dacb95c4ad09ff0afae7db715cc","abstract":"If you really want to find out what goes on inside your Java application, then the debugger is your best choice. \nAre you aware of all the things modern debuggers can do?\nWith recent Java language advances such as lambdas, and rapid improvements by the IDE vendors it is a good time to revisit Java debugging.   \nWe will go through some common use cases and solve them using debugging features and strategies in IntelliJ IDEA and Eclipse:\nSmart breakpoints and stepping, lambdas, monitoring classes and instances, concurrency, etc.\nSo come along for some debugger magic!","published":"true","title":"Java Debugging Tricks","slug":"java_debugging_tricks"},{"intendedAudience":"Android-utviklere som ønsker å lage robuste applikasjoner. Noe erfaring med automatisert testing er en fordel. Code in slides.","keywords":["android","testing"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sindre Nordbø","bio":"Systemutvikler og medlem av mobil-faggruppen i BEKK. Lagde sin første Android-app i 2010.\n\nHvis jeg ikke programmerer er jeg sannsynligvis på en fotballstadion som syngende Rosenborg-supporter.","sessionId":"508a4eedbe2846dea63d6068fe769701"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"508a4eedbe2846dea63d6068fe769701","abstract":"Espresso er et testrammeverk for å enkelt skrive UI-tester for Android-applikasjoner uten for mye boilerplate. Jeg gir en kjapp intro til hvordan du også kan komme i gang med å skrive automatiserte tester for å forhindre uventet oppførsel for brukere av appen din.","published":"true","title":"UI-testing på Android med Espresso","slug":"uitesting_p_android_med_espresso"},{"intendedAudience":"developers, architects and ops people looking to find pragmatic solutions and inspiration for adopting continuous delivery in a setting where this is difficult.\n\nbasic knowledge of infrastructure, network components and java application server deployment logistics is a benefit, but not required. The presentation will contain small parts of code in slides.","keywords":["devops","continuousdelivery","softskills"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Terje Løken","bio":"Former C++ developer and chief architect, now unit manager for the Digital & Mobile unit @ Storebrand. I like to figure out how things work, and implement changes rather than talk about them.\n\nI also have a fondness for pragmatic solutions, grassroots activism and incremental change. I consider patience, good timing and judgement equally important as technical mastery when evolving an architecture.","sessionId":"e1a8a52791144069b74aa7a49155ee15"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"e1a8a52791144069b74aa7a49155ee15","abstract":"The literature and blogosphere around continuous delivery is littered with shining examples describing DevOps teams, container technologies, cloud platforms and green-field implementations. At Storebrand, our challenge was slightly different: We had an existing legacy of monolithic applications, cumbersome platforms, third-party operations teams, ITIL-heavy change processes and heavily orchestrated releases. We wanted something better, but could not throw away what we had and start again. Nor did we have any budgets or executive sponsors.\n\nThis talk will relay the story of how we moved into the world of continuous delivery one step at a time, without large rewrites or interruptions of ongoing projects. It will be a story of how ideal solutions seldom match the real-life requirements of an existing architecture, and how these can be overcome if you apply creativity, opportunism and a little bit of patience. We will also demonstrate how a loosely coupled and simplistic architecture can provide more flexibility than relying too much on a single tool or technology.","published":"true","title":"Continuous Delivery in a 250-year old company","slug":"continuous_delivery_in_a_250year"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk in intended for an audience interested in understanding how their application works. As with any other performance related-talk this will be a deep dive in the JVM internals, however there is no prerequisite knowledge required to understand the content. No live coding, only code on slides.","keywords":["jit compiler","performance","deoptimization"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ivan Krylov","bio":"Ivan Krylov is a lead developer at Azul Systems, working on Zing JVM, co-author of the JEP-285 and implementor of the ObjectLayout prototype. Ivan has been in JVM development since 2005. Previous experience includes the Hotspot Runtime development and the JIT compiler work for the HSA/OpenCL stack.","sessionId":"18b0937ccb3f431f9e797aa25fc0dd14"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"18b0937ccb3f431f9e797aa25fc0dd14","abstract":"The just-in-time compilers Java Virtual Machines make sure that the java code you wrote runs as fast as possible and that the various checks implicitly imposed by the standard do not compromise the performance. Many optimizations are speculative and profile driven. What happens to the code when the assumption becomes incorrect? This talk will cover the lifecycle of a program execution in a JVM, talk specifically about the speculative optimizations and how the JIT compiler “may get it wrong”.","published":"true","title":"Continuous Java program transformations","slug":"continuous_java_program_transfor"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for developers  who prefer static types checking, compiler errors and don't feel good at dynamic languages world. I'll show that there is a way to bring more sanity to Javascript development by introducing Typescript which feels incredibly familiar to Java devs. There will be lot of code samples and some simle live coding.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Michał Ostruszka","bio":"Seasoned full-stack developer, in love with building things for web since beginning of his developer career. Coding in Scala, JS/Typescript and Clojure(Script) together with awesome crew at SoftwareMill, learning new things every day. Speaker and active member of local Java/JVM and Javascript groups, conference speaker at Confitura, Geecon, Agile by Example, 4Developers. Founder of Łódź meet.js developers meetups. Privately husband, father of two and amateur runner.","sessionId":"51b3da2370d44f1b8fa09d3368262669"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"51b3da2370d44f1b8fa09d3368262669","abstract":"We all at least heard of this language called Javascript, created in mythical 10 days with it's famous  bad and good parts. It usually feels weird and uneasy to seasoned Java/JVM developers if one has to deal with it: no compiler safety-net, no types checking, prototypal inheritance, unexpected runtime errors etc. Truth is these days Javascript is everywhere and it really pays off to be able to work on this platform. But what to do if you  feel really uncomfortable with the language itself? Meet Typescript and feel at home: compiler, types, class-based inheritance, interfaces, generics and other goodies. I'll show and try to convince you that writing client stuff as well as solid backends in Typescript can feel familiar to Java/JVM developers, be productive and fun.","published":"true","title":"Typescript - now you have no more excuses.","slug":"typescript__now_you_have_no_more"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som er interessert i automatisert testing og kodekvalitet.\nIngen kode.","keywords":["kodekvalitet","automatisert testing","utdanning"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Per Lauvås","bio":"Tidligere utvikler (2004-2013). Hovedsakelig Java.\nEr nå ansvarlig for programmeringsprogrammet ved Westerdals Oslo ACT, og underviser Java, database og prosjektmetodikk.\nEr for tiden veldig interessert i programmeringsdidaktikk og kunnskapsdeling.","sessionId":"8967a8e405284c4387eb86c3a326b3ca"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"8967a8e405284c4387eb86c3a326b3ca","abstract":"Akademia forsyner industrien med noen unge, håpefulle hvert år. Noen av dem kommer fra Westerdals Oslo ACT. Ved Westerdals innførte vi en endring for et par år siden. Fra å tidligere undervise automatisert testing krever vi nå automatiserte tester til java-koden studentene leverer. Testingen har blitt en naturlig del av vurderingsgrunnlaget.\n\nHvis vi gir samme oppgave til to grupper studenter, men kun den ene gruppen har krav til testedekning. Hvilke utslag gir det? Det vet vi, for vi har det nødvendige kodegrunnlaget, og vi har analysert koden via SonarQube. Du vet også snart dette, hvis du møter opp på denne lyntalen.","published":"true","title":"Juniorene kommer!","slug":"juniorene_kommer"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som vil bli bedre på estimater, og alle som vil forstå litt om hvorfor vi så ofte tar feil.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Håvard Wigtil","bio":"Håvard jobber som programvareutvikler i Kantega AS, der han overrasker seg selv ved å treffe på sine egne estimater. Han har også bommet på estimater siden 90-tallet, selv med et halvt årsstudie i psykologi.","sessionId":"f98e61ae3ef2411eac9c42d1bd2a090b"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"f98e61ae3ef2411eac9c42d1bd2a090b","abstract":"Estimering ER vanskelig. Selv om du sverger til  #noestimates estimerer du alltid noe uansett, og da er det jo bedre om de er litt mer riktige.\n\nNoe av det som gjør det vanskelig er hvordan vi lurer oss selv, men med litt innsikt i hvordan hodene våre virker trenger du ikke å være så lettlurt lengre.\n\nKom for å få litt innsikt i ditt eget hode og hvordan du kan slutte å lure deg selv, basert på David Kahnemans prisbelønnede bok \"Thinking, fast and slow\".","published":"true","title":"\"Estimating, fast and slow\"","slug":"estimating_fast_and_slow"},{"intendedAudience":"Code in slides!\nThe audience will need to have to past experience with building concurrent apps in Java.","keywords":["concurrency","performance","design"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nitsan Wakart","bio":"A blogger and a coder with a pedantic passion for performance. My work has spanned army intelligence systems, dot.com era startups, financial institutions and innovative product companies. The Lead Performance Eng. for Azul Systems by day (working on Zing, best JVM ever :-)), main contributor to lock free data structures library JCTools by night.","sessionId":"7d5ece3d48364391bb32d81411f6637f"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"7d5ece3d48364391bb32d81411f6637f","abstract":"Exploring novel message passing data structures outside the JDK and what they offer in terms of usage patterns, performance and possibilities. We'll be looking at:\n* JCTools queues: placing limitations on producer/consumer counts\n* Disruptor: building a pipeline of workers on top of a pre-allocated buffer\n* Aeron IPC: offheap, cross platform (Java/Native), binary message passing\n* JCTools Proxy Channels: Proxy calls to other threads using custom-generated queues","published":"true","title":"Beyond Qs: Novel Concurrent Message Passing Techniques","slug":"beyond_qs_novel_concurrent_messa"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette er presentasjonen for de fleste utviklere som har med frontend å gjøre. Dersom man ikke er oppdatert får man oppfordring til modernisering, dersom man er erfaren og fremoverlent kan man få oppfordring til å tenke seg ekstra godt om. Det inneholder litt kode, men man trenger ikke å forholde seg til det.","keywords":["javascript","frontend","architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mikael Brevik","bio":"Mikael har hatt en fascinasjon av JavaScript i store deler av sitt voksne liv og er i dag fagleder for frontend i BEKK Trondheim. Han er og en ivrig Open Source-utvikler, Meetup Organizer for BartJS i Trondheim og er i gang med Norges foreløpig eneste månedlige JavaScript Podcast.","sessionId":"ec597cac0032409ea7538d8afb99330f"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"ec597cac0032409ea7538d8afb99330f","abstract":"Det er lite tvil om at det har skjedd mye i frontend-verden de siste 10 årene. Særlig er dette merkbart i JavaScript. Etter at vi har bevegd oss fra tynne til tykke klienter, har vi gått igjennom en transformering som har betydd høy innovasjon, stor grad av utforsking og iterativt arbeid. Det har virket for mange som det er umulig å følge med i frontend-verden og vanskelig å vite hvilke valg man skal ta.\n\nDenne presentasjonen skal prøve å overbevise deg om at JavaScript-frykt ikke er en ting de fleste burde bekymre seg over. På samme måte som vi har smidig og utforskende arbeid på produkter, har vi det og på utvikling av økosystem og teknologier, og man kan fint få gevinsten av det uten å måtte ofre mye.\n\nVi vil gå igjennom historie og utviklingen av språket, utviklingen av økosystem og fellesskapet for å skjønne hvordan ting henger sammen og for å se at det ikke nødvendigvis er slik at alle må være med på all utvikling som foregår. Vi vil også se hvordan et moderne prosjekt ser ut i 2016 og hvorfor det ikke trenger å være så skremmende.","published":"true","title":"Frontend Anno 2016: Exploration and Iteration","slug":"frontend_anno_2016_exploration_a"},{"intendedAudience":"No code","keywords":["productivity","hardware","opensource"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Joar Aurdal","bio":"Joar er en entusiastisk utvikler med 15 års erfaring fra komplekse  javabaserte prosjekter i offentlig og privat sektor. Han har gjennom hele sin karriere hatt et sterkt engasjement for hvordan utviklingen gjøres i prosjektene han har deltatt i, både med tanke på teknologier, verktøy og prosesser.","sessionId":"3c9fec10fb454617b3aa0ef399a20fe5"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"3c9fec10fb454617b3aa0ef399a20fe5","abstract":"Det er viktig å ha riktig redskap når en jobb skal utføres.  Likevel selges det stort sett bare tastatur som baserer seg på et over 100 år gammelt design. Et design som var tilpasset skrivemaskiner, og ikke utvikling av programvare i et moderne IDE. \n\nJeg vil gå gjennom hva jeg mener er galt med vanlige tastatur, og vise til alternative  tastatur og tastaturoppsett for utviklere.","published":"true","title":"Alternative tastatur og tastaturoppsett for utviklere","slug":"alternative_tastatur_og_tastatur"},{"intendedAudience":"Intermediate, Slides + Live Coding","keywords":["javase","programminglanguages"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Richard Warburton","bio":"Richard is an empirical technologist and solver of deep-dive technical problems and works independently as a Software Engineer and Trainer. Recently he has written a book on Java 8 Lambdas for O’Reilly and helps developers learn via http://iteratrlearning.com and http://www.pluralsight.com/author/richard-warburton. He’s worked as a developer in diverse areas including Statistical Analytics, Static Analysis, Compilers and Network Protocols. He is a leader in the London Java Community. Richard is also a well known conference speaker, having talked at Devoxx, JavaOne, QCon SF, JFokus, Devoxx UK, Geecon, Oredev, JAX London, JEEConf and Codemotion. He obtained a PhD in Computer Science from The University of Warwick.","sessionId":"3f14115ed88242319d8e0d9def9d9328"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"3f14115ed88242319d8e0d9def9d9328","abstract":"Generics are one of the most complex features of Java. They are often poorly understood and lead to confusing errors. Unfortunately, it won’t get easier. Java 10, release planned for 2018, extends Generics. It’s now time to understand generics or risk being left behind.\n\nWe start by stepping back into the halcyon days of 2004 and explain why generics were introduced in the first place back. We also explain why Java’s implementation is unique compared to similar features in other programming languages.\n\nThen we travel to the present to explaining how to make effective use of Generics. We then explore various entertaining code examples and puzzlers of how Generics are used today.\n\nFinally, this talk sheds light on the planned changes in Java 10 with practical code examples and related ideas from other programming languages. If you ever wanted to understand the buzz around higher kinded types or declaration site variance now is your chance!","published":"true","title":"Generics: Past, Present and Future","slug":"generics_past_present_and_future"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is intended for developers, however, there is no requirements to watching the talk.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Rolf Erik Lekang","bio":"Developer at Itera, works mostly with JavaScript. Enjoying life with good books and great coffee. Also tries to capture great moments with my camera.","sessionId":"1a2a144e1cd44200b633dbf13ff3776e"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"1a2a144e1cd44200b633dbf13ff3776e","abstract":"We learn and evolve as projects goes on, so does our codestyle and what we view as best practices. It is fairly common to use linters to enforce a certain code style within a project. The problem arises when we want to add a new rule, but the codebase already breaks this in thousands places from before. How do you tackle that? Especially when there is that deadline coming up. This talk proposes a way to use you version control system to help decide which lint errors should be taken into account or not and that way making it possible to gradually evolve your linter rules.","published":"true","title":"Enforcing codestyle changes over time","slug":"enforcing_codestyle_changes_over"},{"intendedAudience":"Denne lyntalen er for for deg som er inspirert til å hjelpe, men synes open source er litt stort og skummelt.","keywords":["open source","pull request"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jørgen Aaberg","bio":"Jørgen jobber som konsulent for Iterate. Spesielt interessert i JavaScript og Lean Startup. Ellers glad i løping og en god kopp kaffe.","sessionId":"63acf395f64a43eca90beea410101640"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"63acf395f64a43eca90beea410101640","abstract":"\"Feel free to submit a pull request\". Noen vil kalle det en invitasjon, men for mange er det vanskelig og skummelt. Denne lyntalen vil gi en rask introduksjon til hvor enkelt, ufarlig, og givende kan være å gi tilbake til miljøet.","published":"true","title":"Din første pull request","slug":"din_frste_pull_request"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere. No code.","keywords":["devops","docker","experiencereports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mads Mobæk","bio":"Mads har en bred interesse for alle aspekter av digitale løsninger, fra strategi til konsept og til hovedtyngden som han har på teknologi. Til daglig jobber han med problemstillinger rundt digitalisering hos BEKK og BEKKs kunder.","sessionId":"44040aa53462410ba3f2aa2b455cad7c"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"44040aa53462410ba3f2aa2b455cad7c","abstract":"Er byggserveren din full av håndskreven konfigurasjon, manuelt installerte plugins og så høy kompleksitet at bare et fåtall kan administrere den? Hør erfaringene rundt å få Jenkins og slaver til å kjøre på Docker med all konfigurasjon under kildekontroll, hvordan vi åpner opp for alle, spawner nye slaver uten anstrengelse og lar byggserveren redeploye seg selv!","published":"true","title":"Selvbyggende byggserver med Docker på SpareBank 1","slug":"selvbyggende_byggserver_med_dock"},{"intendedAudience":"Utvecklare, no code.","keywords":["experiencereports","docker","developmentpractice"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Stian Conradsen","bio":"Utvikler med stor interesse for koding, automatisering og forenkling. Er også opptatt av å bruke ressursene riktig og at man løser det faktiske problemet. \nJobber i dag for SpareBank 1 hvor jeg med på å bygge en distribuert arkitektur og bygge opp team. \nHoldt foredraget Breaking the Monolith @ SpareBank 1 på JavaZone i fjor.","sessionId":"6867a91bff04499880d0b1e8d5898014"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"6867a91bff04499880d0b1e8d5898014","abstract":"Hvordan utvikler man lokalt på et komplisert distribuert system uten å være avhengig av manuelt konfigurerte testmiljøer.\n\nLa frontend-utviklere kode frontend uten å måtte bygge backend-kode. \n\nVær fleksibel på hvilke deler av det distribuerte systemet som kjøres lokalt og hvilke som kjører på delte miljøer.\n\nMed en lokal DNS server er det mulig å bruke systemet på flere forskjellige måter - uten å ta noe opp og ned.\nI talken ser vi nærmere på hvordan noen enkle Docker image konvensastioner og HAProxy kan realisere og sette opp en komplisert infrastruktur lokalt og på utviklerens arbeidsstasjon.","published":"true","title":"“Jeg vil bare lage internett!”. Hvordan bruker vi Docker i utviklingsmiljøet hos SpareBank 1 for å kjøre komplisert infrastruktur.","slug":"jeg_vil_bare_lage_internett_hvor"},{"intendedAudience":"The target audience is developers who are interested in improving their coding craft and looking to reason more clearly about their coding style and design. There will be code in slides using Java and a few other JVM languages.","keywords":["paradigms","programming style","patterns"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Kevlin Henney","bio":"Kevlin is an independent consultant, trainer and writer based in the UK. His development interests are in patterns, programming, practice and process. He has been a columnist for various magazines and web sites and is co-author of A Pattern Language for Distributed Computing and On Patterns and Pattern Languages, two volumes in the Pattern-Oriented Software Architecture series. He is also editor of the 97 Things Every Programmer Should Know.","sessionId":"0341b50d36fa471d9c7a0a20a7f447f3"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"0341b50d36fa471d9c7a0a20a7f447f3","abstract":"It is very easy to get stuck in one way of doing things. This is as true of programming as it is of life. Although a programming paradigm represents a set of stylistic choices, it is much more than this: a programming paradigm also represents a way of thinking. Having only way to think about problems is too limiting. A programming paradigm represents a set of patterns of problem framing and solving and contains the ingredients of software architecture. As Émile Auguste Chartier noted, there is nothing more dangerous than an idea when you have only one idea.\n\nPerhaps even more problematic than being stuck with a narrow view of paradigms, is being stuck with a dysfunctional view of each paradigm. For instance, many developers working in languages and frameworks that support object orientation lack a strong idea of the principles of interaction, data abstraction and granularity that support an effective view of OO, and instead surround themselves with manager objects, singletons and DTOs.\n\nThis session explores the strengths and weaknesses of different programming styles, patterns and paradigms in Java and other JVM languages.","published":"true","title":"Paradigms Lost, Paradigms Regained: Programming with Objects and Functions and More","slug":"paradigms_lost_paradigms_regaine"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for a developer with some experience, who has to come up with better ways to solve technical problems. Middle level and up.\nThe whole talk is live coding","keywords":["cleancode","java8","java9"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nikita Salnikov-Tarnovski","bio":"Nikita is the co-founder of Plumbr, the JVM performance monitoring product, where he now contributes as core developer. Besides his daily technical tasks of solving various problems, he is an active blogger, 3 times JavaOne RockStar and frequent conference speaker  (JavaOne, Devoxx, GeeCON, TopConf, JFokus, GeekOut, Joker, JPoint, Jazoon, JEEConf etc).","sessionId":"cf7f80dbb76f47f089abbf58739951ea"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"cf7f80dbb76f47f089abbf58739951ea","abstract":"Although the JVM takes care of cleaning up memory for you, it is still your responsibility to clean other types of resources after usage, such as file handlers, open streams, native resources etc. Usually the first cleaning method that comes to mind is the finalization mechanism. But as it often happens, the first thought is a wrong one.\n\nIn this talk I will review several methods of cleaning up unused resources: autoclosables, “wrap your lambda”, finalisers, reference queues and Cleaner classes. I will demonstrate how to use all of them and will talk about the pros and cons of each of them.","published":"true","title":"You use it, you clean it","slug":"you_use_it_you_clean_it"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers new to RxJava or having very little experience, but willing to experiment with it. No slides, only live coding.","keywords":["rxjava","reactive","functionalprogramming"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Tomasz Nurkiewicz","bio":"Spent half of his life on programming, for the last decade professionally in Java land. Loves back-end, tolerates JavaScript. Passionate about alternative JVM languages. Disappointed with the quality of software written these days (so often by himself!), hates long methods and hidden side effects. Interested in charting, data analysis and reporting. Believes that computers were invented so that developers can automate boring and repetitive tasks. Also their own.\n\nOn a daily basis works in financial sector. Involved in open-source, DZone’s Most Valuable Blogger, used to be very active on StackOverflow. Author, trainer, conference speaker, technical reviewer, runner. Claims that code not tested automatically is not a feature but just a rumour. Currently writing a book \"Reactive Programming with RxJava\" for O'Reilly.","sessionId":"351787c1e99241118a91344a1e82abef"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"351787c1e99241118a91344a1e82abef","abstract":"If you ever approached RxJava before you might come to a conclusion that this library solves problems most of us don't have. Reactively composing streams of data, virtual time, marble diagrams and event-driven programming - where most of our code is pretty much just transferring data from database to presentation layer.\n\nDuring this live coding session for Rx beginners and intermediates there will not be a single slide, we start with empty IDE to step-by-step implement key constructs in RxJava. Most importantly we will discover how this high-level abstraction can help in existing projects. When to use RxJava, what problems does it solve and when using it is an excess of form over substance.\n\nWe will learn how to build highly reliable and concurrent applications, improve throughput and resource utilization without hurting readability and avoiding  complexity.","published":"true","title":"RxJava in legacy projects","slug":"rxjava_in_legacy_projects"},{"intendedAudience":"For utviklere. Kode i slider","keywords":["jwt","intro"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Øyvind Tangen","bio":"Øyvind er ansatt som utvikler i BEKKs teknologiavdeling og jobber til daglig som konsulent på prosjekt i bank- og forsikringsbransjen.\n\nHan er opptatt av mobilutvikling, personvern og å velge riktig verktøy for jobben som skal gjøres.","sessionId":"0123c8e261fe4d2da207ca3684ed58f9"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"0123c8e261fe4d2da207ca3684ed58f9","abstract":"Sikkerhet og autentisering er vanskelig å gjøre riktig, og i en moderne verden kanskje viktigere enn noensinne. JSON Web Tokens er en ny teknologi som enkelt lar deg sende informasjon mellom to parter på en sikker og tilstandsløs måte. Informasjonen sendes som en rekke påstander som kan inneholde all nødvendig informasjon  om en bruker, noe som blant annet eliminerer behovet for databaseoppslag.\n\nJeg har jobbet med JWTer på prosjekt en god periode. Kom og hør hvordan du kan komme i gang og hva jeg har lært.","published":"true","title":"En introduksjon til JWT","slug":"en_introduksjon_til_jwt"},{"intendedAudience":"No code\nNo coding experiance required","keywords":["biohacking","iot","nfc"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Tore Myklebust","bio":"Tore is a full-stack developer at BEKK and has a passion for all kinds of technology. He likes planning  and attending  events involving programming. Tore is co-hosting Pils & Programming Oslo, a meetup which is simply about hacking while enjoying a few beers.","sessionId":"175171f87d0e4ee79cdb816d76f56b01"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"175171f87d0e4ee79cdb816d76f56b01","abstract":"Have you ever wondered how you can modify your own body with technology? That is, enabling your own body to interact directly with the increasingly modern world? Today, everybody can be a cyborg – this talk will show you how. \n\nWe will take a closer look at biohacking and NFC implants, and demonstrate how easy and cheap it is to get started. We'll also explore some practical use cases for the technology, like authentication and information sharing, with a focus on security and privacy.","published":"true","title":"Biohacking, hack your body!","slug":"biohacking_hack_your_body"},{"intendedAudience":"Architects, DevOps and developers how are passionate about continuous deployments and zero downtime.","keywords":["continuous delivery","zero downtime","database changes"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sebastian Dehne","bio":"I am an enthusiastic programmer who is hopeless at accepting excellent advice from others and always has to discover things for himself first. For 20+ years I have been fascinated by computers and the stuff we can make them do. Especially distributed architectures and concurrent systems interest me the most. I am working as a consultant for Systek and am currently at the norwegian tax office (Skatteetaten), where we built awesome web- and backend applications to make the business of tax administration more efficient.","sessionId":"8653d0f0cd0f4592821f9d6d07cdf4cc"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"8653d0f0cd0f4592821f9d6d07cdf4cc","abstract":"The importance of being able to do small and frequent deployments is well understood by most of us. Being able to do those deployments during daytime, without downtime, can typically be solved by so called blue-green deployments. But what if you need to do database changes in addition? Join my talk if you are keen to learn how to manage day time deployments with database changes without causing any interruptions.","published":"true","title":"Zero downtime continuous deployment architecture","slug":"zero_downtime_continuous_deploym"},{"intendedAudience":"Passer for alle, enten man kjenner til C++ eller ei. For deg som er opptatt av at kode skal være lett å forholde seg til. Code in slides.","keywords":["languagefeatures","programminglanguages","softwarequality"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ole Bakstad","bio":"Ole er en faglig engasjert utvikler som interesserer seg for alt fra programmeringspråk til utviklingsprosesser og organisasjonskultur. Spesielt interessert i hvordan tekniske valg påvirker måten man jobber på, jobbhverdagen til de ansatte og evnen til å skape verdi over tid. Jobber i dag som konsulent i Knowit, men har bakgrunn fra embedded programmering og signalbehandling.","sessionId":"75f32173c6c644ae9a8d38d144398b1f"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"75f32173c6c644ae9a8d38d144398b1f","abstract":"Som tidligere C++-utvikler var jeg fornøyd da jeg så at Java hadde et final-keyword. Gleden var dog kortvarig da jeg fant ut hvor liten effekt final faktisk har når man jobber i en stor og gammel kodebase. C og C++ er kanskje kjent for segfaults, minnelekasjer og udefinert oppførsel, men noe har de gjort rett. I denne talken introduserer jeg C++ sitt keyword const, hvilket problem dette løser og hvorfor Java burde ha noe tilsvarende.","published":"true","title":"final? Gi meg const!","slug":"final_gi_meg_const"},{"intendedAudience":"For alle som er interessert i åpne data og ITS. Og for utviklere som ønsker å berike sine applikasjoner med åpne lokasjonsbestemte data. Litt kode i slides.","keywords":["åpnedata","its","api"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jørgen Abrahamsen","bio":"Jørgen er en erfaren, entusiastisk og engasjert programvareutvikler med en brennende lidenskap for kvalitet og brukbarhet i håndtverket han utfører til daglig. Å sette sammen åpne data for å lage nyttige applikasjoner har blitt en besettelse for ham.\n\nJørgen har jobbet med tilgjengeliggjøring og bruk av åpne data for flere virksomheter i offentlig sektor, blant annet Statens vegvesen.","sessionId":"52f9d2ad1d204f38a59c974575580c9d"},{"name":"Trond Smaavik","bio":"Trond er en spesialist på åpne data med spesiell kunnskap om intelligente transportsystemer (ITS) og ITS-data. Er det noe du vil vite om åpne datasett? Sjansene er gode for at han kan gi deg en datakilde eller vet hvem du bør ta kontakt med.\n\nTrond har jobbet med tilgjengeliggjøring og bruk av åpne data for flere virksomheter i offentlig sektor, blant annet Statens vegvesen.","sessionId":"52f9d2ad1d204f38a59c974575580c9d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"52f9d2ad1d204f38a59c974575580c9d","abstract":"ITS, intelligent transport systems, handler om å gjøre transport mer effektivt, sikkert og miljøvennlig. Data fra sensorer langs veien, kombinert med data fra biler og verden rundt, gjør det mulig for deg å bygge nye og spennende tjenester. Det finnes mange datasett med slik data fritt tilgjengelig for deg å bruke.\n\nStatens vegvesen er en av de største leverandørene av åpne lokasjonsbestemte ITS-data. Vi vil vise deg hvordan du gjennom APIer kan få tilgang til data om sanntids trafikkmeldinger, reisetid, bomstasjoner, fartsgrenser, webkameraer og mye mer.\n\nStatens vegvesen har nylig lansert en ny webbasert kartløsning. Vi vil også ta en kikk på denne løsningen, erfaringene og utfordringene fra å utvikle denne, og hvilke datasett som er brukt.","published":"true","title":"Åpne data i intelligente transportsystemer","slug":"pne_data_i_intelligente_transpor"},{"intendedAudience":"Attend this session if you dream about creating persuasive design sketches and maybe want to test out your ideas without any coding.  You're also welcome if you're simply looking to impress your co-workers with some Keynote ninja skills","keywords":["keynote","html5","webapp"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Thomas Lund Sigdestad","bio":"CTO and product architect @ Enonic. Father of two, husband of one. Dropped out of university master studies 16 years ago to start my own company, and never looked back!","sessionId":"79be89d3224a4ca18717a0d9d77e2f4c"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"79be89d3224a4ca18717a0d9d77e2f4c","abstract":"Keynote is awesome - no wonder Google Venture uses it for prototyping!\n\nFaced with the daunting task of designing a responsive Html5 authoring interface for an Open Source CMS, we had no designers on the team - just a CTO that knew Keynote.\n\nThis talk will show you how to create powerful and persuasive webapp  \"foilware\" with Keynote. How this can be used for basic user tests and finally as input to your developers. You should be able to pick up some ninja tricks on the way.\n\nIn the end we'll take you through the various stages of designing and implementing our own application - and finally check out the live result!","published":"true","title":"Building software with Keynote","slug":"building_software_with_keynote"},{"intendedAudience":"Intended for Devs and/or Ops, or anyone interested in how they can work together. Some Gherkin in sliders.","keywords":["devops","bdd"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Magnus Reftel","bio":"Currently at the Norwegian Tax Office in a DevOpsy role, previously at Spotify and ST-Ericsson. Coder since the '90s. Habitual automator. Cucumber fan.","sessionId":"0bd8f05639b444c989842700f2de0291"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"0bd8f05639b444c989842700f2de0291","abstract":"As one way of bringing the Ops closer to the Devs, we're using Cucumber to describe our systems from an operations perspective. Which application is dependent on which? How are they configured? How should they behave in network outages? It's all in the Gherkin.\n\nThis talk summarises what we've learned from doing this, and helps you get started too.","published":"true","title":"Behaviour-Driven DevOps","slug":"behaviourdriven_devops"},{"intendedAudience":"Både utviklere som har havnet i \"testdatagjørma\", utviklere som synes at testdata skal håndteres i kode og testere/teknisk testere vil ha utbytte av foredraget. Foredraget vil starte med en introduksjon til Cucumber, slik at også de uten erfaring med rammeverket vil få utbytte.\n\nAlle kodeeksempler vil selvsagt være i Java.","keywords":["testing","bdd"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Torstein Strøm","bio":"Torstein er hands-on arkitekt, innvikler og medeier i Kantega AS, og har 15 års erfaring fra prosjekter fra 1 til 150 personer. Han forsøker å unngå samme feil mer enn to ganger, denne gangen er det testdata som skal til pers.","sessionId":"38fcfec3f7f3486eaa00ba241e717d96"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"38fcfec3f7f3486eaa00ba241e717d96","abstract":"GITT tilstrekkelig mye testdata\nOG la de modes godt en god periode\nNÅR testdataene så må endres litt\nSÅ er det ingen som tør å gjøre det\n\nHar du hørt om Cucumber? Cucumber (https://cucumber.io/) er et testverktøy som eksekverer en spesifikasjon skrevet i et naturlig (f.eks norsk) språk, f.eks slik som over. Cucumber kan hjelpe deg i å etablere et felles språk mellom utviklere, domeneeksperter og testere, og få alle til å skrive spesifikasjoner som du som utvikler kan kjøre for å teste om systemet ditt oppfyller kravene.\n\nSom i alle tester er det noen forutsetninger som må være på plass før testene kan kjøre. Vanligvis løser vi disse forutsetningene enten med mocking eller med testdata. Felles for begge er at det gir oss kontroll på omgivelsene i testen, men erfaringsmessig mister vi fort kontroll på både testdata og mock'er. Testdata ligger i verste fall i sql-filer eller i flate filer, mocker er jo bare \"testkode\" og mangler både planlegging og struktur.\n\nI dette foredraget vil jeg foreslå en måte hvor Cucumber kan brukes ikke bare til å skrive testene dine, men også hvordan du kan få hjelp til å håndtere testdata vha. Cucumber. Og husk, testdata er ikke bare data for de automatiske testene dine, manuelle tester fortjener minst like god håndtering og kontroll av testdata.","published":"true","title":"Hva har agurk og testdata til felles?","slug":"hva_har_agurk_og_testdata_til_fe"},{"intendedAudience":"Du kan med fordel ha erfaring fra å lese og kommentere på andres kode, men ledere som tenker at kodegransking er for dyrt oppfordres spesielt til å komme! Det blir vist veldig enkle kodeeksempler.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anders Båtstrand","bio":"Anders er utvikler og med-eier i Kantega AS, og har 7 års erfaring fra mange forskjellige kodebaser og team. Han liker å lese all kode som teamet hans produserer, og har de siste årene erfart at dette er vel anvendt tid.","sessionId":"2a7e3303b0db42059d6783b8e7b482f8"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"2a7e3303b0db42059d6783b8e7b482f8","abstract":"Å granske hverandres kode kan avsløre feil, men jeg vil argumentere for at det er mange flere fordeler. Kunnskapsdeling og felles eierskap er vel så viktig. På 20 minutter vil jeg fortelle hvorfor alle i teamet bør lese alles kode, og hva som skal til for at dette er verdt tidsbruken. Jeg vil ta for meg viktigheten av verktøystøtte, konvensjoner i koden, så vel som kulturelle faktorer for at granskingen blir en konstruktiv dialog.","published":"true","title":"Tips for knallbra kodegransk","slug":"tips_for_knallbra_kodegransk"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som ønsker å oppdage bugs så tidlig som mulig. De som brenner for kodekvalitet og ønsker bedre oversikt over kodebasen.\n\nCode in slides.","keywords":["codequality","softwarequality"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Hans Joachim Desserud","bio":"Java-utvikler og arkitekt hos Sopra Steria.","sessionId":"1092b62726784d68b145449e21f4b103"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"1092b62726784d68b145449e21f4b103","abstract":"Til tross for at vi utviklere gjør det beste vi kan når vi skriver kode, sniker det seg inn bugs fra tid til annen. I verste fall kan disse skape problemer i produksjon, så vi ønsker å oppdage og luke dem ut så fort som mulig. Ved bruk av statisk kodeanalyse kan vi gå gjennom kodebasen og finne ting som ser rart, misvisende eller tilogmed riv ruskende feil ut.\n\nSonarQube er et av de mest utbredte verktøyene for statisk kodeanalyse i Java-økosystemet og kan hjelpe oss identifisere en rekke problemer i koden vi har skrevet. Vi tar en titt på noen av disse problemene og hvordan vi raskt kan oppdage og adressere dem.\n\nVi ser også hvordan du kan definere egne regelsett og få varsel når det blir oppdaget nye problemer i kodebasen.","published":"true","title":"Finn bugs automatisk med SonarQube","slug":"finn_bugs_automatisk_med_sonarqu"},{"intendedAudience":"Grunnleggende forståelse av REST API-er. Code in slides.","keywords":["graphql","restapi"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Henrik Glasø Skifjeld","bio":"Utvikler i Iterate. Veldig interessert i tech. Liker å holde meg oppdatert, særlig på frontend og JavaScript.","sessionId":"06004be11b7c4855802cd495ca705383"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"06004be11b7c4855802cd495ca705383","abstract":"I starten av 2015 viste Facebook fram hvordan de har løst noen av problemene med REST API-er - blant annet mange kall mellom klient og server for kompliserte datastrukturer og henting av datafelter man kanskje ikke trenger. De har utviklet en ny måte å utveksle data mellom klient og server - nemlig med noe som kalles GraphQL. Hva er det? Hvordan fungerer det? Hvilke problemer løser det?","published":"true","title":"GraphQL > REST API?","slug":"graphql_gt_rest_api"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som vil lære seg TypeScript eller Angular2. \n\"Live coding\"","keywords":["angular2","typescript","livecoding"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Simo Martomaa","bio":"Simo er en erfaren arkitekt og utvikler i Kantega. Han har gått hele runden fra statisk typet back-end til dynamisk typet front-end, og tilbake.","sessionId":"fe4b2532834e4c1fb007e4def08f9aad"},{"name":"Johannes Harestad","bio":"Johannes jobber som iOS- og frontend-utvikler i Kantega. Han er blitt en ivrig pådriver av TypeScript og Angular etter gode erfaringer i prosjekter.","sessionId":"fe4b2532834e4c1fb007e4def08f9aad"}],"format":"workshop","language":"no","sessionId":"fe4b2532834e4c1fb007e4def08f9aad","abstract":"Har du noen gang tenkt at feilmeldingen kunne vært bedre enn \"Undefined is not a function\"? Har du savnet god IDE-støtte for frontend-utvikling? Da er denne workshoppen midt i blinken for deg! Kom og se hvordan man lager en komponent-basert Angular 2 applikasjon og hvor bra utvikler-opplevelesen kan bli når du har ordentlig type-system fra TypeScript som IDEen støtter. Vi deler våre egne erfaringer fra prosjekter med TypeScript og Angular 2, viser hvor enkelt det er å komme i gang, og hvordan man unngår de vanligste fellene når kodebasen din vokser.\nVeien fra Java til TypeScript er kortere enn du tror!","published":"true","title":"Angular2 med TypeScript","slug":"angular2_med_typescript"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere og tech leads som har litt for enkel tilgang til Elasticsearch og dermed gjerne fikler litt for mye med innholdet slik at de litt fortere enn de aner får bruk for å kjøre restore fra den backupen de burde ha satt opp.","keywords":["elasticsearch"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jan Fredrik Wedén","bio":"Jan Fredrik jobber som utvikler i BEKK og har over 15 års erfaring innen systemutvikling. Han jobber til daglig med prosjekter som samler inn og behandler store datamengder og benytter Elasticsearch til lagring og analyse av informasjonen.\n\nPå fritiden har han stor interesse for bratt friluftsliv og er gjerne å finne på et fjell med ski under bena, klatrende i en fjellvegg eller syklende der motoriserte kjøretøy sjelden kommer frem.","sessionId":"fd1aa3d1e461435699403e02120dc680"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"fd1aa3d1e461435699403e02120dc680","abstract":"Backup av data i Elasticsearch gjøres via snapshot/restore API-et som lover deg inkrementelle backups av dine data. Men hva foregår egentlig i bakgrunnen og hvordan kan du faktisk hente data tilbake igjen fra dine snapshots? Har du noen gang prøvd? Vi ser på Elasticsearchs API for snapshot/restore og viser strategier for å faktisk hente data tilbake igjen når du trenger det - ehh, da vi trengte det - og uten at noen merker noe.","published":"true","title":"Kan du få data tilbake igjen fra dine Elasticsearch snapshots?","slug":"kan_du_f_data_tilbake_igjen_fra_"},{"intendedAudience":"This lightning talk is for developers and architects alike. Too often in the field we over complicate our solutions. Simple problems are solved in the most extreme ways that hinder maintenance in the long run. Unnecessary complexity is added to simple domains which creates steep learning curves for new developers and maintainers of code. This lightning talk, in a sarcastic approach, attempts to demonstrate how damaging and destructive overengineering actually is.","keywords":["overengineering","programminglanguages","architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sirar Salih","bio":"Sirar Salih is a technical lead working at If P&C Insurance, the largest insurance company in Scandinavia. He is a board member of the Norwegian .NET User Group and the Oslo chapter. He is also co-founder of the AngularJS Oslo user group and organizer of the annual Arctic IoT Challenge in Oslo. Sirar loves holding presentations and has experience from speaking at international conferences such as the Norwegian Developers Conference, JavaZone, Trondheim Developer Conference and HTML5 Developer Conference in San Francisco. He actively contributes to the open source community through his blog; https://sirarsalih.com/ and GitHub; https://github.com/sirarsalih.","sessionId":"efca2e0f7bbc477394d2790e4b7ebab6"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"efca2e0f7bbc477394d2790e4b7ebab6","abstract":"Let's use the hottest and greatest technologies. Let's solve a simple problem in the most complex way. Let's add more and more layers to our architecture. Let's call all code which is 3 months or older, legacy. Got domain specific problems? No problem, just throw new tech at it!\n\nBecause hey, why not?","published":"true","title":"Let's overengineer the hell out of this","slug":"lets_overengineer_the_hell_out_o"},{"intendedAudience":"Software developers that works in teams","keywords":["teamwork","get s*%t done","happiness"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sven Peters","bio":"Sven is a software geek working as an Evangelist for Atlassian. He started with Java development in 1998 and has been programming for longer that he'd like to admit. Besides coding his passion is getting the right tools into the hands of those who need it to help build fast moving, agile, autonomous teams and getting them to kick-ass. Sven has extensive speaking experience in 25+ countries on myriad topics.","sessionId":"c90c8e0081804523a6daa8757afef463"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"c90c8e0081804523a6daa8757afef463","abstract":"Every software team writes code, but some teams produce fewer bugs than others. Every software team creates new features, but some teams develop them faster than others. What do high performance teams do differently, and why are team members more focused, satisfied and relaxed? They truly work together. No 10x rockstar programmer can achieve what a well rounded, enthusiastic team can.\nSven Peters examines how the best software teams set and follow goals, integrate new members fast, ensure diversity, monitor and continually improve team health, embrace transparency, create new processes, use a playbook to guide them through every phase of development and even develop creative & flexible work spaces for multidisciplinary projects. He shares techniques including: sparring, OKRs, feature buddies, open demos, focus weeks and many more that help teams and team members to work more effectively together, and produce awesome results.","published":"true","title":"The Secret Sauce of Successful Teams","slug":"the_secret_sauce_of_successful_t"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers and Devops.  This is heavy code.  Docker and internet access is required.","keywords":["docker","orchestration"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ken Sipe","bio":"Ken Sipe is a Cloud Solution Architect at Mesosphere, focused on helping companies simplify the development and operation of large scale infrastructure and distributed systems with Apache Mesos and the new Datacenter OS.   As a JavaOne Rockstar, Ken is an author and award winning international speaker on the practices of software architecture and engineering, continuous delivery and agile practices.   Ken is also an Apache Mesos contributor and an Apache committer on the Myriad, HDFS, Cassandra and Kafka Apache Mesos framework projects.","sessionId":"a6b8b1ea07244d03b70e08e5ee383139"}],"format":"workshop","language":"en","sessionId":"a6b8b1ea07244d03b70e08e5ee383139","abstract":"The popularity of Docker as a micro-services tool has many organizations looking to put docker into production. With years of experience working with leading edge organizations, this workshop will not only teach Docker, but will provide real-world advice on how to work with Docker for production.\n\nThis session is a workshop and as such you will need to come with a laptop with Docker 1.10+ installed. The training and labs will include:\n\nDocker basics\nContainer lifecycles\nBuild files\nWorking with the Registry\nWorking with the docker machine\nDocker compose \nThis will include the dos and don'ts for a production environment.\nThe session will end with standing up a Mesos / Marathon environment for scaling out a docker instance. Time allowing the bonus lab is standing up Kubernetes to run Docker instances.","published":"true","title":"Advanced Docker Workshop","slug":"advanced_docker_workshop"},{"intendedAudience":"The exercises material will be available in both Scala and Java.  The attendees should be able to code in either Scala or Java at an intermediate level.","keywords":["cassandra","spark streaming","kafka"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"James Ward","bio":"James Ward (www.jamesward.com) is a Principal Platform Evangelist at Salesforce.com. James frequently presents at conferences around the world such as JavaOne, Devoxx, and many other Java get-togethers. Along with Bruce Eckel, James co-authored First Steps in Flex. He has also published numerous screencasts, blogs, and technical articles. Starting with Pascal and Assembly in the 80’s, James found his passion for writing code. Beginning in the 90’s he began doing web development with HTML, Perl/CGI, then Java. After building a Flex and Java based customer service portal in 2004 for Pillar Data Systems he became a Technical Evangelist for Flex at Adobe. In 2011 James became a Principal Developer Evangelist at Salesforce.com where he taught developers how to deploy apps on the cloud with Heroku. From Fall 2012 to Spring 2014 James was a Developer Advocate at Typesafe where he created Typesafe Activator and led the Reactive Software vision. James tweets as @_JamesWard and posts code at github.com/jamesward.","sessionId":"430f4752ff4b41f2bd9717f903cfea70"},{"name":"Ryan Knight","bio":"Ryan Knight has 15 years of experience with building distributed systems and large-scale data centric applications with Cassandra, Spark, Java, Scala and Akka. He frequently does training and presentations at conferences around the world, such as JavaOne, Devoxx, Cassandra Summit and many other meetups and has traveled to over 15 countries. He first started Java Consulting in 1999 at the Sun Java Center and has since worked at a wide variety of companies such as Typesafe, Oracle, IBM, Intel, Tomax, Family Search and Riot Games.  He now works as an Enterprise Solution Engineer for DataStax.","sessionId":"430f4752ff4b41f2bd9717f903cfea70"}],"format":"workshop","language":"en","sessionId":"430f4752ff4b41f2bd9717f903cfea70","abstract":"Building mission critical data pipelines provides business with the unique advantage of providing real time analytics of all of the data flowing through the enterprise.  This gives them the ability to get hands on with the data to make more intelligent decisions.\n\nThere are several core principles for building data pipelines for mission critical applications.  The first is to to ensure the integrity of the data ingested so that no data is loss.  This ensures that accurate and high quality analytics of that data.    Another core principle is to make the data pipeline resilient to failures and able to adapt to differing volumes of data and user load.  This requires each component of the pipeline be highly available, scalable to changing demands and able to apply back-pressure during peak data loads.\n\nIn this workshop we will walk through building this type of large scale, mission critical data pipeline using Kafka, Spark Streaming and Cassandra.   The workshop will start by looking at the individual technologies that make up the data pipeline.  Then we will discuss the overall architecture of the data pipeline and how to address these core principles.  Attendees will get hands on with exercises that walk through each of the pieces of the architecture.   \n\nIn the end all attendees will have the good times flowing - with a complete end to end data pipeline!","published":"true","title":"Let the good times flow!  Building a large scale data pipeline with, Kafka, Spark Streaming and Cassandra","slug":"let_the_good_times_flow__buildin"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers working with RDBMS, such as Oracle, and care about performance, should attend this presentation. The only requirement for benefiting from the presentation is that audience believe that performance is a feature, and does not happen by accident. The audience will be introduced to a method showing how to work with performance both in development, test and production.\nAmount of code: \"Code in slides\"","keywords":["performance","rdbms","instrumentation"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lasse Jenssen","bio":"I'm an developer and database expert, focusing on performance and scalability. I have worked with database technologies for over 20 years, and I strongly believe in using the right technology for the right purpose. This could be anything from NoSQL databases such as MongoDB, Cassandra and ElasticSearch, or RDBM Systems such as MS SQL Server, PostgresSQL, MySQL, DB2 or Oracle. The last year I've also started to look into BigData technologies evolving around the Hadoop framework. \n\nI strongly believe that performance is a feature, and that programmers and system owners get the systems they deserve.\n\nIn 2015 I  became an Oracle ACE Associate, for my knowledge and contributions towards the Oracle communities.","sessionId":"7f707e7fcc604fe9910033616bce4493"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"7f707e7fcc604fe9910033616bce4493","abstract":"Performance is not an attribute of a system, but rather an attribute of an individual user experience. Performance is all about response time, which then again is given by its code path. But how can we possibly follow the code path into the RDBMS database. The JDBC 4.1 specification together with the Oracle end-to-end metrics gives you a method to follow the code path, and to work with performance, down to a single push on a button.","published":"true","title":"\"Performance is a feature: Instrument your code using JDBC features\"","slug":"performance_is_a_feature_instrum"},{"intendedAudience":"Anyone interested in the tradeoffs to consider when writing applications with some degree of concurrency.  There will be code in slides and live coding.","keywords":["concurrency","asynchronous","nonblocking"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Christin Gorman","bio":"Christin has been working as a software developer for 15 years, mostly backend and mostly java.  This year she has joined the gang at KODEMAKER.  Since 2011 she has been a regular speaker at JavaZone, where her enthusiasm and strong (at times controversial) opinions have landed three of her presentations in the top 20 most viewed list.","sessionId":"46125475be964164bd920c2bb4b1db27"},{"name":"Eivind Barstad Waaler","bio":"Eivind has been developing Java- and JVM-based applications for over 15 years. He loves programming and is always looking for new ways to solve problems. Eivind is working as a consultant at Kodemaker and has been speaking at most JavaZone-conferences since 2003.","sessionId":"46125475be964164bd920c2bb4b1db27"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"46125475be964164bd920c2bb4b1db27","abstract":"All hipsters know that asynchronous non-blocking code is the only way. But what does that really mean? There are many ways of writing concurrent applications. All with different tradeoffs. We wanted to find out what the best approach or approaches were, so we tried the all, so you won't have to.  We will compact our years of toil into an hour of live coding examples for you to enjoy.  Come learn from our mistakes and triumphs.  We will present you with a common problem, and several different ways to solve it.  We'll show you the benefits, the disadvantages and explanations of what is actually going on at a lower level.","published":"true","title":"5 approaches to concurrency in Java - which one is the best?","slug":"5_approaches_to_concurrency_in_j"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is an experience report focusing on architecture and system design, so there will be no actual code. Attendees should understand the basics of web services, threads, and databases.","keywords":["cloud","bigdata","architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lars Marius Garshol","bio":"Lars Marius is a Staff Software Engineer at Schibsted. He was responsible for building parts of the data collection pipeline and parts of the data analytics platform. Earlier he worked as a public sector consultant at Bouvet, and on developing an enterprise data integration and search platform at Sesam. He's also been an open source developer for many, many years, and for about a decade was editor for a number of ISO standards.","sessionId":"a446a704b6354629abbc6988db5cc20d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"a446a704b6354629abbc6988db5cc20d","abstract":"Schibsted is a global media and classified ads conglomerate with about\n200 million unique users per month. The company is currently being\ntransformed away from traditional paper media and siloed sites toward\na unified global media giant. To do this, Schibsted needs to collect\ndata about user behaviour, and process this with machine learning.\n\nThis presentation is about we built Schibsted's infrastructure for\nreceiving and processing this behaviour data, which at the moment\ncomes to 700 million events per day, or 2 terabytes per day. The\npresentation covers the architecture, design of individual services,\nmonitoring, and challenges in scaling and reliability. It also goes\ninto the interaction between legal privacy requirements and overall\narchitecture.\n\nKey technologies used are Amazon Web Services, auto-scaling, Scala,\nDatadog, Kinesis/S3, Docker, Mesos, Luigi, and Spark.","published":"true","title":"Collecting 700 million events a day","slug":"collecting_700_million_events_a_"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers, architects","keywords":["architecture","agility","evolution"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Neal Ford","bio":"Neal Ford is Director, Software Architect, and Meme Wrangler at ThoughtWorks, a global IT consultancy with an exclusive focus on end-to-end software development and delivery. He is also the designer and developer of applications, magazine articles, video/DVD presentations, and author and/or editor of eight books spanning a variety of subjects and technologies, including the most recent Presentation Patterns and Functional Thinking. He focuses on designing and building of large-scale enterprise applications. He is also an internationally acclaimed speaker, speaking at over 300 developer conferences worldwide, delivering more than 2000 presentations. Check out his web site at nealford.com. He welcomes feedback and can be reached at nford@thoughtworks.com.","sessionId":"2ed7cbc4c500467fa08c35e271a44b38"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"2ed7cbc4c500467fa08c35e271a44b38","abstract":"For many years, software architecture was described as the “parts that are hard to change later”. But software architecture is the balancing of capabilities versus constraints. If build changeability one of your prime capabilities, evolutionary change becomes easier. The microservice architectural style is quite popular, but it is only one in a family of evolutionary architectures. This session defines the characteristics this family of architectural styles, along with engineering and DevOps practices necessary for implementation. I cover the principles behind evolutionary architectures, the practices needed for success, how organization and team structure affects these architectures, and specific engineer practices that facilitate evolutionary architectures. I also discuss migration strategies from common existing architectural types towards move evolutionary architectures.","published":"true","title":"Evolutionary Architectures","slug":"evolutionary_architectures"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is suitable for developers curious about machine learning and for anyone considering using machine learning in a production system (including QA people and operations people). Slides will contain some Scala code, but Scala knowledge is not necessary.","keywords":["machinelearning","bigdata","recommendersystems"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Øyvind Holmstad","bio":"Øyvind Holmstad is a backend developer at the Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation with a background as an IT consultant. His passion for programming comes from a desire to create great and exciting products, and at NRK he has got his wish fulfilled by working on their award-winning on-demand streaming solutions. For the last year he has been immensely enjoying working with Scala and machine learning on NRKs new recommendation system.","sessionId":"a244fe3de31b4c4a9272632622fd3f22"},{"name":"Thomas Oldervoll","bio":"Thomas Oldervoll is a partner and senior consultant in Zenior, currently working for NRK as developer, data engineer and machine wrangler on their recommender system. After 7 years of being a Java developer for various customers in the Oslo region he moved to San Francisco to work for Google, where he worked on large machine learning systems for detecting blog spam and fraud. Back in Oslo he continues to learn more about ML and how to apply it to customer problems.","sessionId":"a244fe3de31b4c4a9272632622fd3f22"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"a244fe3de31b4c4a9272632622fd3f22","abstract":"Taking a machine learning system from prototype to production requires a lot more than what is typically covered in an introduction to machine learning. In this talk we show how NRK built a recommender system for on-demand video streaming, taking it from an internal prototype to a service running in production. TV viewing habits are changing, and NRK needs a recommender system to stay relevant and get better use out of NRK’s content catalog. In addition to explaining the algorithms we use, we will discuss challenges around data collection, infrastructure, model management and testing.\n\nOn to the buzzwords: The system is implemented in Scala using Apache Spark. Training runs in Google Cloud Dataproc with extensive use of Google BigQuery. Recommendations are served through a Play Framework API, deployed as Docker containers running on Mesos in both a public cloud (Microsoft Azure) and a private cloud. \n\nTune in to learn how you can make your system smarter by making better use of data you already have.","published":"true","title":"Machine learning at NRK: From prototype to production","slug":"machine_learning_at_nrk_from_pro"},{"intendedAudience":"Backend developers  that are exposed to relational and non-relational persistence technologies. Live coding.","keywords":["spring","spring-data","nosql"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Oliver Gierke","bio":"Oliver Gierke is the lead of the Spring Data project at Pivotal, formerly known as SpringSource, and member of the JPA expert group. He has been into developing enterprise applications and open source projects for over 10 years now. His working focus is centered around software architecture, DDD, REST, and persistence technologies. He is regularly speaking at German and international conferences and the author of technology articles as well as the first book on Spring Data.","sessionId":"28c91be669794e3194c5e383bbf90f2c"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"28c91be669794e3194c5e383bbf90f2c","abstract":"This talk will give a broad overview of the new features introduced in the latest Spring Data release trains. We will cover recent additions and improvements in Spring Data Commons - the module that's shared amongst the store specific ones. We'll then delve into the latest and greatest features of individual store modules, like JPA, MongoDB, Neo4j, Solr and the community ones as well.","published":"true","title":"What's new in Spring Data?","slug":"whats_new_in_spring_data"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for anyone doing Web front-end development that is curious about alternatives to JavaScript. A basic understanding of and curiosity towards Functional Programming will probably be helpful.\n\nPlenty of Live coding is to be expected.","keywords":["frontend","functionalprogramming","programminglanguages"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Magnus Rundberget","bio":"Magnus is a consultant working for Kodemaker. He has a background from Java, Groovy and JavaScript development. A few years ago he started to develop a keen interest for functional programming and in particular Clojure/ClojureScript. Last year he made a decision to learn more about statically typed functional languages and Elm popped up as the most interesting and approachable candidate to get started with. To get a flying start with Elm, Magnus created an Elm plugin for his favourite editor -  Light Table.  During daytime he is still developing in Groovy, Clojure and JavaScript. Evenings and nights are often spent deep diving into functional programming, blogging and developing on his Oper Source projects.","sessionId":"5080ed85f55b4378b3ae9b5fda2e1769"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"5080ed85f55b4378b3ae9b5fda2e1769","abstract":"Programming a web front-end is getting increasingly more complex. Some people are boldly suggesting that JavaScript is not the ideal language to handle this complexity. A compile step is already part of the workflow for most front-end development projects, so choosing a compile to JS language shouldn't be such a big leap.\n\nOne of the many alternative languages available for the front-end that is well worth a look is Elm. Elm is a relatively young compile to JS language that has started to get quite a bit of attention in the front-end community. It is a statically typed functional language that is carefully crafted to be fun, easily approachable yet very powerful. \n\nIn this talk you will get a quick introduction to the Elm language before diving in, to create a small sample application using Functional Reactive Programming principles. By the end of the talk you should have a better understanding of what Elm is  about and why it might be worth considering for your future web front-end projects.","published":"true","title":"Elm - Awesomesauce or just yet another language for the Front-end ?","slug":"elm__awesomesauce_or_just_yet_an"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for developers and architect who are deploying or looking to deploy their applications on the cloud. In this talk you'll learn about immutable infrastructure and how to solve the challenges associated your transition to get there. No code.","keywords":["immutable infrastructure","cloud","continuousdelivery"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Axel Fontaine","bio":"Axel Fontaine is the founder and CEO of Boxfuse (boxfuse.com), the easiest way to deploy JVM and Node.js applications to AWS.\n\nAxel is also the creator and project lead of Flyway (flywaydb.org), the open-source tool that makes database migration easy.\n\nHe is a Continuous Delivery and Immutable Infrastructure expert, a Java Champion, a JavaOne Rockstar and a regular speaker at many large international conferences including JavaOne, Devoxx, Jfokus, JavaZone, QCon, JAX, ...\n\nYou can find him online at axelfontaine.com and on Twitter as @axelfontaine","sessionId":"c248d6fb60824c029cfba27ed1336e3e"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"c248d6fb60824c029cfba27ed1336e3e","abstract":"The cloud is the new normal and it is time to rethink how we see machines and deployments. We have been piling layer upon layer of complexity for too long. But why should it be this way? It is time to radically simplify all this.\n\nIn this talk, we'll throw general-purpose operating systems, snowflake servers and runtime provisioning out the door. Instead you'll see how servers become disposable, how machine images are generated from scratch in seconds and how to achieve perfect environment parity from dev to prod.\n\nThis is Immutable Infrastructure. It is a profoundly important change as to how we view and treat our systems. We'll go deep. We'll look at how this affects scaling, logging, sessions, configuration, service discovery and more. We'll also look at how containers and machine images compare and why some things you took for granted may not be necessary anymore.\n\nBut beware, neither sacred cows nor kittens will be spared!","published":"true","title":"Immutable Infrastructure: Rise of the Machine Images","slug":"immutable_infrastructure_rise_of"},{"intendedAudience":"The session is targeting enterprise application developers and architects. There will be a lot of live coding using and comparing different technologies.","keywords":["javaee","productivity","enterprise"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sebastian Daschner","bio":"Sebastian Daschner is a Java freelancer working as a Consultant / Software Developer / Architect and is enthusiastic about programming and Java (EE).\nHe is an JCP member, participating in the JSR processes and hacking on various open source projects on Github. He has been working with Java for more than 6 years. Besides Java, Sebastian is also a heavy user of Linux and container technologies like Docker. He evangelizes computer science practices on https://blog.sebastian-daschner.com and on Twitter via @DaschnerS.","sessionId":"079888bfac5942ebb1915a37a139aacd"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"079888bfac5942ebb1915a37a139aacd","abstract":"A long time ago J2EE and especially application servers were considered to be too bloated and \"heavyweight\". It could be quite tedious and discouraging for developers to use that technology for developing applications. But since the name change to Java EE that assumption is not true anymore. This session shows the benefits developing against a well-established standard has, what makes a framework \"lightweight\" and how a lightweight yet comprehensive solution for enterprise application could look like. Most of the time will be spent live-coding and comparing different approaches.","published":"true","title":"Java EE - the most lightweight enterprise framework","slug":"java_ee__the_most_lightweight_en"},{"intendedAudience":"Denne talken er for dem som er nysgjerrige på maskinlæring og deep learning. Kanskje har man hatt grunnleggende om nevrale nettverk på skolen, evt. bare lest litt om temaet. Kanskje vet man ingenting om dem, men lurer litt på hva som foregår. Ingen kode, men masse bilder og kule eksempler.","keywords":["machinelearning","ai","deeplearning"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ole Kristian Braut Grashei","bio":"Ole har en mastergrad i Intelligente Systemer fra NTNU. Til daglig jobber han for Knowit med Java og Android. Det er derimot på kveldene den virkelige magien hender. Da henger han på r/machinelearning mens han trener siste skrik innen maskinlæringsmodeller. Målet er å alltid få litt bedre score i en eller annen maskinlæringskonkurranse på Kaggle.","sessionId":"147947f09a5a4314938bb36b254f3774"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"147947f09a5a4314938bb36b254f3774","abstract":"Etter nylige innovasjoner har interessen og forskning rundt biologisk inspirerte modeller kjent som nevrale nettverk økt kraftig. Teknikkene kalles gjerne deep learning. Gjennombruddet har gitt oss state-of-the-art modeller for tale- og bildeanalyse, med språkforståelse like bak. Gigantene Google, Facebook, Baidu mfl. har hentet inn de mest kjente forskerne innen feltet. nVidia har gått all-inn, og jobber hardt for å levere teknologien som skal drive selvkjørende biler. Google sin AlphaGo har beseiret verdens beste Go-spiller. Problemer som bare mennesker kunne løse blir stadig enklere for maskinene. Jeg skal gi bittelitt historie, vise litt om hvordan disse modellene virker, vise noen kule eksempler og fortelle litt om hva som skjer ved fronten av AI.","published":"true","title":"Hjælp! Maskiner slår oss nå i brettspillet Go og snart kjører de bilene våre. Hvordan greier de det?","slug":"hjlp_maskiner_slr_oss_n_i_bretts"},{"intendedAudience":"Beginner.  Significantly code and example driven.  All code downloadable and runnable for deeper further study.","keywords":["javaee"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"David Blevins","bio":"David has cofounded OpenEJB (1999), Geronimo (2003), and TomEE (2011). He is a member of the EJB 3.0, EJB 3.1, EJB 3.2, Java EE 6, Java EE 7, Java EE 8 Expert Groups and a member of the Apache Software Foundation. He is CEO and founder of Tomitribe and a veteran of open source Java EE and has been both implementing and defining Java EE specifications for more than 10 years with a strong drive to see Java EE simple, testable, and as light as Java SE. A contributing author to 'Component-Based Software Engineering: Putting the Pieces Together' (Addison Wesley), Blevins is a regular speaker at JavaOne, Devoxx, ApacheCon, OSCon, JAX and other Java-focused conferences.","sessionId":"4800ec7cef1b4098b24a3941f716a71c"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"4800ec7cef1b4098b24a3941f716a71c","abstract":"Java EE 7 holds two critical gems many developers never employ: CDI Scopes and Java EE Connectors. Do you have any code storing objects in hashmaps? You can kill that code with custom scopes. Need to interact with a system that doesn’t speak HTTP? Stop writing endless wrapping endpoints and just support that protocol natively with Java EE Connectors. We’ll explore both in detail through concrete and runnable code examples that will have you ready to code.\n\n​We'll also explore the role of Functional programming in Java EE. With a mix of usable Java EE 7 and potential Java EE 8 features, we’ll take concepts like @Schedule annotations and Bean Validation and see how they might be fundamentally changed with Java 8 language enhancements like lambdas and method references.","published":"true","title":"Java EE, Extendable to Functional","slug":"java_ee_extendable_to_functional"},{"intendedAudience":"Audience is expected to be pro efficient in Java and have basic knowledge of Maven.  There will be code in slides and some Live coding/demos.","keywords":["reactive","polyglot","distributed"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Paulo Lopes","bio":"I'm Paulo and I've used my 10+ years of software development experience writing, rewriting, banging my head against the wall, editing and re-editing high-performance web application to make Vert.x an even more awesome framework. I am also the author of \"yoke\" and other small open source projects. I jump out of bed with a big smile on my face each morning because I know reactive applications are real and will finally put monoliths and big balls of mud to an end.\n\nThis is more than a job; I'm on a mission to build fast and faster applications!","sessionId":"c804c2f7558e4acc99345a4b033e5ec6"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"c804c2f7558e4acc99345a4b033e5ec6","abstract":"Async programming is here to stay, it has proven that it can handle the load modern applications demand. Starting with async programming can be a total mind shift, once you add scaling to the equation it can get really complex! But why does it need to be so complicated?\n\nReactive systems are one answer, however, today we're looking for web-scale, and for this we should consider Vert.x! Vert.x is a toolkit to create distributed reactive applications on the Java Virtual Machine. It lets you build scalable applications transparently distributed in Java, JavaScript, Ruby and Groovy. You don’t have to choose a single language, just mix them!\n\nThis session explains how the simple model promoted by Vert.x enables the construction of concurrent, scalable and efficient reactive based applications.","published":"true","title":"Let's build a scalable async Vert.x app in < 60 min","slug":"lets_build_a_scalable_async_vert"},{"intendedAudience":"For deg som har laget et superdupert API men har fått kjeft av kollegaen din fordi han ikke vet hvordan han skal bruke API-et ditt. Code in slides.","keywords":["rest","json","documentation"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Kenneth Stigen","bio":"Kenneth er seniorkonsulent i Knowit Objectnet og har jobbet som programmerer siden 2004. Han trives aller best når han får lage nye ting. Programmerer stort sett i Java, men har de siste par årene også jobbet med Scala og Python.","sessionId":"10ada35f55ed4133a19ca968cbc585bc"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"10ada35f55ed4133a19ca968cbc585bc","abstract":"Det snakkes mye om API First og at API-er er løsningen på alle dine problemer, men har du noen gang forsøkt å benytte et API som ikke er dokumentert? \nI dette foredraget introduseres du til Swagger og hvordan det kan brukes til å presentere API-ene dine på en god måte. \nVi tar en titt på Swagger UI, som hjelper deg med å utforske og teste API-ene dine. \nAvslutningsvis kommer du til å se hvordan vi har samlet all dokumentasjon fra alle våre mikrotjenester i én fin innpakning.","published":"true","title":"Swagger - Vis frem API-ene dine!","slug":"swagger__vis_frem_apiene_dine"},{"intendedAudience":"This presentation is targeted towards those who are in charge of maintaining a system in need of some modernisation but are not sure where to start, as well as those who are starting a new project and are interested in learning what to consider when building the project in a flexible and maintainable manner.\n\nThe concepts are programing-language agnostic, however my own experiences are based primarily in the wonderful world of Java (surprise!). There will be some code in slides.","keywords":["methodology","experiencereports","languageagnostic"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Gareth Western","bio":"Gareth is a developer with over 12 years of experience designing and implementing \"enterprise\" web applications for companies around the world. He currently lives in Norway, and earns his bread and butter working as a consultant for Bouvet.","sessionId":"d3d6715beb654398b1d218b773480453"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"d3d6715beb654398b1d218b773480453","abstract":"Just getting started with building \"cloud native\" applications and looking for an outline for doing it in a well structured and scalable way? Or perhaps you've inherited a more mature Web-based system that needs a kick up the bum to get it organised? If you answered yes to any of the above then the 12 Factor app methodology may be for you!\n\nThe 12 Factor methodology is a set of best practices first published by one of the founders of Heroku (the popular Platform-as-a-Service platform) covering 12 different aspects of application development that apply throughout the entire life of an application, from initial development to runtime in production. By following these guidelines you will give your application a better chance at the long and happy future that it deserves.\n\nIn this talk I will introduce each of these factors and how I have interpreted them in my own experiences developing software throughout the years.\n\nWhile primarily targeted at applications that will be deployed in a cloud environment, the points covered here can be applied to any software applications which run as a service (regardless of the programming language used).","published":"true","title":"Give your apps the X(II) factor!","slug":"give_your_apps_the_xii_factor"},{"intendedAudience":"Anyone interested in using Ceylon to write microservices, or Android apps. Some prior knowledge of the language would be beneficial, but is not essential.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Tom Bentley","bio":"Tom has been working on Ceylon since 2011. He focuses mainly on code generation for the JVM, but he's also had a hand in some of the other tools in the distribution and several of the modules in the Ceylon SDK. His interests include programming languages, the JVM and beekeeping.\n\nTom lives in the UK.","sessionId":"057cde72a9b647c38b8f7109c47df195"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"057cde72a9b647c38b8f7109c47df195","abstract":"Ceylon (http://ceylon-lang.org) is a great language with awesome features and great tooling that lets you focus on getting things done. So we wrote this Android application in Ceylon: You won't believe what happened next... But you'll have to come to the talk to find out. You'll also learn 8 ways Ceylon can help you write great microservices that the government doesn't want you to know about.","published":"true","title":"The most incredible Ceylon presentation you'll ever see","slug":"the_most_incredible_ceylon_prese"},{"intendedAudience":"Everyone","keywords":["devops","fucking","dead"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Andreas Heim","bio":"Andreas Heim er VP of Engineering hos Unacast. Der har han ansvar (sammen med resten av utviklerne) for å utvikle og drifte Unacasts dataplatform. Andreas digger data.","sessionId":"882c2f6e11114ffaa84ae0c762174d44"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"882c2f6e11114ffaa84ae0c762174d44","abstract":"With the rise of managed services, Containers As A Service, Immutable Infrastructure etc., DevOps as we know it are dying. But it is a slow grinding death. DevOps is still being looked at as the \"cool new thing\" in many circles, when in fact, DevOps is just another dead end.\n\nJoin me for this lightning talk, and let's give a big fat middle finger to provisioning frameworks and server management, and succumb to our new Managed Service and Public Cloud overlords!","published":"true","title":"DevOps. You're fucking dead to me.","slug":"devops_youre_fucking_dead_to_me"},{"intendedAudience":"This session if for Git users who want to improve their productivity and knowledge of the tool.","keywords":["git"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nicola Paolucci","bio":"Nicola is an all-round hacker who loves exploring and teaching bleeding\nedge technologies. He writes and teaches about Docker, Git, development workflows and code collaboration. \n\nPrior to his current role as Developer Instigator at Atlassian he lead software teams, built crowd sourcing applications for geo-spacial data, worked on huge e-commerce deployments.\n\nLittle known facts about Nicola: he gesticulates a lot while speaking (being Italian), lives in Amsterdam and rides a Ducati.","sessionId":"7e14ede8dbbc44cb802bec9569a3128f"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"7e14ede8dbbc44cb802bec9569a3128f","abstract":"Many use Git at the most basic level: push, pull, and maybe branch off to isolate feature and bug fix work. But put together a few new and old effective Git commands and one can really increase productivity. Don't resort to XKCD #1597 when facing problems. Efficient, transformative personal Git workflows are not only possible, they are easy to learn. This talk will teach you exactly those.\nDo you want spoilers? Think of the new \"git worktree\" command, think of \"--autosquash\", think of \"subtree\", and of few more interesting surprises in the Git toolchain.","published":"true","title":"Transformative Git practices: new techniques for hyper-productivity","slug":"transformative_git_practices_new"},{"intendedAudience":"Er du utvikler eller sysadmin med interesse for sikring av websider ved bruk av SSL, så er Let's Encrypt en nyhet og revolusjon som du bør kjenne til.\nAv forkunnskaper er det greit å vite hva et SSL-sertifikat er og hva det brukes til. Du vil også få større utbytte av lyntalen dersom du kjenner deg igjen på en kommandolinje.","keywords":["sikkerhet","ssl","let's encrypt"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jostein Tveit","bio":"Jostein har jobbet med programvareutvikling i over 12 år og har en genuin interesse for sikkerhet i programvare. Han mener at all kommunikasjon på nettet bør krypteres og ved å tilby gratis SSL-sertifikater er Let's Encrypt et stort steg i riktig retning. Jostein ønsker derfor å spre kunnskap om og vise hvordan Let's Encrypt kan tas i bruk. Han er styremedlem i OWASP Norway Chapter og jobber til daglig hos Arkitektum i Bø i Telemark.","sessionId":"384cb7ef82514a2f86f2a069a122a8de"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"384cb7ef82514a2f86f2a069a122a8de","abstract":"Skulle du ønske at SSL-sertifikater var enkelt, gratis og at de fornyet seg selv?\nNå finnes Let's Encrypt! Let's Encrypt gir deg gratis SSL-sertifikater og fornyer disse automatisk når de er i ferd med å utløpe.\n\nDette er en kort introduksjon til Let's Encrypt, med en demonstrasjon av hvor enkelt det nå er å skaffe seg et SSL-sertifikat og hvordan dette fornyer seg selv.\n\nLet's Encrypt er en åpen sertifikatutsteder, som utvikles og driftes av Internet Security Research Group (ISRG), hvis formål er å redusere de finansielle, teknologiske og kunnskapsmessige barrierene mot sikring av kommunikasjon på Internett.","published":"true","title":"Let's Encrypt! Endelig er SSL-sertifikater enkelt og gratis!","slug":"lets_encrypt_endelig_er_sslserti"},{"intendedAudience":"Du er interessert i å følge koden din ut i produksjon.  Du trenger innspill og gode ideer til hva og hvordan dette kan overvåkes.\n\"Code in slides\"","keywords":["devops","monitoring"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Fredrik Rødland","bio":"Fredrik har over 15 års erfaring med softwareutvikling hvorav 10 med søk. Han var med å starte opp aksjehandelstjenesten Stocknet, jobbet i FAST med implementering hos kunder. Han har tilsammen jobbet med søk i FINN i 7 år, hvor han blant annet brenner for å ha høy oppetid på alle deler av søketjenesten.\n\nNår han ikke jobber med søk liker han å fotografere og bygge (og fly/kondemnere) quadcopters.","sessionId":"043820e5a053494b899fbb897422ca7b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"043820e5a053494b899fbb897422ca7b","abstract":"I FINN.no har vi de siste årene konvertert en gammel monolitisk applikasjon til over 300 kjørende mikrotjenester.  Denne endringen har store utfordringer rundt feilsøking og oppetid, og krever gode overvåkningsløsninger som tidlig oppdager og varsler om feil.\n\nSøketeamet i FINN har laget en applikasjon som kontinuerlig overvåker ca 200 metrikker og varsler både med GUI, mail, SMS når noe er feil.  Jeg vil gå gjennom tankene bak applikasjonen, vise kodeeksempler på tester vi gjør mot eksterne systemer og vise applikasjonen live.","published":"true","title":"Øyeblikkelig oversikt over 150 ting som kan gå galt (og gjør det)","slug":"yeblikkelig_oversikt_over_150_ti"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for anyone who wants to learn more about performance tuning their Java code. It's my intention to make my talks as accessible as possible without requiring expert knowledge. I will explain the JIT subsystem and optimisations for beginners but will continue to more advanced topics which will unavoidably be quite pretty complicated!\nI will present code in slides showing Java, bytecode, and assembly.","keywords":["jitwatch","hotspot","performance"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Chris Newland","bio":"Chris Newland, author of JITWatch. JVM tinkerer, financial software developer (trading systems, market data systems), performance tuning geek.","sessionId":"940c2799b8d34f3ca422e8064edafc4a"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"940c2799b8d34f3ca422e8064edafc4a","abstract":"Learn about the Just In Time (JIT) optimisations made by the HotSpot JVM to dynamically optimise the performance of your code at runtime.\nLearn about using the free and open-source JITWatch tool to analyse the JIT compiler decisions made by the JVM during the execution of your program.\nDiscover which of your methods were inlined, which allocations were eliminated through escape analysis, and identify safepoint poll points in your code.","published":"true","title":"Understanding HotSpot JVM Performance with JITWatch","slug":"understanding_hotspot_jvm_perfor"},{"intendedAudience":"No prior knowledge is expected or assumed.  This talk will be interesting for anyone who has tried to integrate with physical devices, whether they are an IoT Hipster or a Raspberry PI Hacker.\n\nWe'll be focusing on comparing the protocols, so there will be no code.","keywords":["internet of things","integration","protocols"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mark West","bio":"Mark is an Englishman living in Oslo where he works at Bouvet, a Norwegian IT Consultancy.  After some years in the management wilderness Mark has recently rediscovered the joy of coding and now spends his evenings experimenting with JavaScript, Robotics and the Internet of Things. \n\nIn his spare time Mark is involved in javaBin (the Norwegian JUG) and helps organise community events such as JavaZone and JavaZone Kids. In the past year Mark has spoken about IoT matters at JavaOne in San Francisco and the IoT Tech Day in Utrecht.","sessionId":"fbc157a3cfb04f858ba789edf490dbeb"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"fbc157a3cfb04f858ba789edf490dbeb","abstract":"After HTTP, MQTT and CoAP are perhaps the most commonly used communication protocols for connecting devices to the Internet of Things.  But what are MQTT and CoAP, and what benefits do they provide over plain old HTTP?\n\nIn this session we’ll start by looking at the limitations to using HTTP in the IoT world.  We will then introduce MQTT and CoAP, and explain why these can be compelling replacements for HTTP.  By examining the strengths and weaknesses for HTTP, MQTT and CoAP we’ll identify IoT use cases for all three.","published":"true","title":"MQTT and CoAP for the Java Developer","slug":"mqtt_and_coap_for_the_java_devel"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere, arkitekter og prosjektledere.\n\nDeltakerne vil få dypere forståelse for hva en bør tenke gjennom ved innføring og bruk av Enterprise programvare.\n\nIngen kode.","keywords":["arkitektur","erfaringsrapport"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Vidar Moe","bio":"Arkitekt og utvikler med mange års erfaring fra noen av de største programvareprosjektene i Norge. Brenner for lean og smidige prinsipper, og liker å utfordre både tekniske monolitter og organisatoriske siloer for å kunne levere stadig bedre og raskere.","sessionId":"831674ed258745cea99c26c88a2da90e"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"831674ed258745cea99c26c88a2da90e","abstract":"Mange av oss fryser på ryggen og får piggene ut bare vi hører ordene Enterprise programvare. - Hvorfor gjør vi det?\n\nVi har prøvd å innføre noen kommersielle programvarekomponenter  i nettbankarkitekturen vår, som fra før er bygget på open source standardapplikasjoner og biblioteker. Innføringen har gitt oss nye erfaringer.\n\nKom og hør når vi forteller om utfordringene vi har hatt og hva vi har lært av dette. - Kan det være at det er noe annet enn selve programvaren som er hovedutfordringene til Enterprise programvare?","published":"true","title":"- Enterprise programvare! Vart du skræmt no?","slug":"_enterprise_programvare_vart_du_"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere med interesse for frontend og store javascriptkodebaser\n\nCode in slides","keywords":["javascript"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Erik Wendel","bio":"Erik driver med javascriptutvikling i BEKK Consulting her i Oslo, og elsker funksjonell programmering og å holde foredrag og workshops. Han jobber som fagleder for området frontendarkitektur i BEKK, men jobber til daglig med nettbank- og mobilbankutvikling hos SpareBank1.\n\nHer har han jobbet med storskala javascriptapplikasjoner siden 2012. Det siste året har han jobbet med å koordinere et arbeid for å migrere frontendarkitekturen fra Backbone til React og Redux. Dette arbeidet involverer over femten applikasjoner, femten team og nesten hundre utviklere.\n\nErik er en erfaren taler, og har holdt foredrag og workshops i både inn- og utland, sist på ForwardJS-konferansen i San Francisco.","sessionId":"e321b76a6e1c470fa1674aa0e3491e63"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"e321b76a6e1c470fa1674aa0e3491e63","abstract":"Synes du det er vanskelig å holde deg oppdatert på hva som skjer i frontendlandskapet? Er du lei av at det stadig snakkes om nye rammeverk du knapt har hørt om? Lurer du på hva man bør velge for å lage store og komplekse webapplikasjoner i 2016?\n\nMange mener React og Redux, de siste skuddene på en lang stamme av frontendbuzzwords, er kjempebra greier. Men er det egentlig det? Er det ikke bare... nytt? Hvordan kan vi vite at det ikke bare er nok et blaff i vinden? Kommer det ikke bare noe nytt og enda bedre neste år?\n\nI dette foredraget får du en grundig gjennomgang av React og Redux-arkitekturen. Du vil se hvordan disse kan bidra til å holde store frontendkodebaser ryddige i tiden fremover, uten at vi trenger å være redd for å måtte skrive om alt neste år.","published":"true","title":"\"React og Redux, sier du? Neste år kommer det vel bare enda et rammeverk”","slug":"react_og_redux_sier_du_neste_r_k"},{"intendedAudience":"People that are interested in JVM internals, optimizing native code compilers and who is just curious about alternative JVM implementations may benefit from this talk.  On the other hand, the common knowledge (university level) about JVM and compilers is enough to get the most of the presentation. There is some code in slides but not so much.","keywords":["jvm","aot","jit"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nikita Lipsky","bio":"Nikita Lipsky is an initiator and a team lead of Excelsior JET project – certified Java SE implementation with AOT compiler developed by Excelsior LLC. Working on the project since 1997 he took part in almost every activity of the project from the JVM core to product management and support. Last couple of years, he is experimenting (in a spare time) with open source projects exploring approaches and a concept of the next web.","sessionId":"00f58bdd62994e3a833c01689ab36ec8"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"00f58bdd62994e3a833c01689ab36ec8","abstract":"Ahead-of-time (AOT) native compilation has been available for .NET for quite some time, whereas Java SE, while being older than .NET, still does not have a standard AOT compiler. Some people ask why, some people think that it could only work for certain limited types of Java applications, some people think that it is not needed.\n\nThe truth, however, is that a Java AOT compiler has been available for over a decade, as part of a compliant Java SE implementation called Excelsior JET, and it proved to be useful for many organizations around the world. In this session, I would like to dispel the common myths about Java AOT compilation and show where it has advantages over JIT compilation from the technical point of view.","published":"true","title":"Java AOT Compilation","slug":"java_aot_compilation"},{"intendedAudience":"All audiences. No code. All practical application.\nPerfect if you've watched the show “Mr. Robot”.\n\nYou will hopefully learn to, as they say, “get your shit together” when it comes to personal security.","keywords":["personal security","getting hacked","password management"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Michael Johansen","bio":"A software consultant during the day and a startup founder during the night. At NTNU I studied entrepreneurship, computer science and psychology. During my studies I also took a year off to be a board member at NTNU's Board of Directors. As part of my startup venture I've gotten first-hand experience with the startup scene in both Boston and in Silicon Valley. Humans and machines are the two things that interest me the most. I'm a bit systematic.\n\nI care more than most people about personal security, and it's a topic on which I'd like to share my insights.\n\nCV: michaeljohansen.no -- linkedin.com/in/johansenmichael","sessionId":"e13ec0bd5fb04f9f9d6db7b9dbb9b3bf"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"e13ec0bd5fb04f9f9d6db7b9dbb9b3bf","abstract":"You are one of the most significant security threats to your company. We all know we are going to fix better passwords / encryption / firewalls / etc. one day. Getting properly hacked is one of those things that is a lot more comfortable to prevent beforehand than to gather the shattered pieces afterwards. In this talk, we will take a practical approach to good personal digital security. We will start with the easy parts before drilling through the layers of security, down to the parts that are unpredictable and dangerous. Bring your laptop and a tin foil hat.\n\nTopics include: What it's like to get properly hacked. Using password managers. Operating system security. Browser security. Encryption, firewalls, factors, and other means of protection.","published":"true","title":"Personal security","slug":"personal_security"},{"intendedAudience":"Little code, However deep details on Cgroups and container configurations.","keywords":["java","docker","cgroups"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ken Sipe","bio":"Ken Sipe is a Cloud Solution Architect at Mesosphere, focused on helping companies simplify the development and operation of large scale infrastructure and distributed systems with Apache Mesos and the new Datacenter OS.   As a JavaOne Rockstar, Ken is an author and award winning international speaker on the practices of software architecture and engineering, continuous delivery and agile practices.   Ken is also an Apache Mesos contributor and an Apache committer on the Myriad, HDFS, Cassandra and Kafka Apache Mesos framework projects.","sessionId":"261d8c2d5ab94b3b8212f66f2cbe7096"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"261d8c2d5ab94b3b8212f66f2cbe7096","abstract":"Whether it is Docker or the Mesos Container running with Apache Mesos means running in a container, but do you really understand cgroups and how they work? Do you understand the difference between CPU Sets and CPU Shares? Many organizations use Java for their application development, but do you understand the consequence of what impact the cgroup constraints have on the JRE? \n\nThis talk starts with a look at the anatomy of a container including control groups (cgroups) and namespaces. Then we will take a deep understand of Java's memory management and GC characteristics and how JRE characteristics change based on core count. The session will detail specifically the difference between CPU sets and CPU shares and memory management. The session will close with a deep understanding of the consequences of running the JRE in a CPU share environment and the potential for pseudo-random behavior of running in a heterogeneous datacenter.","published":"true","title":"Nobody puts Java in the container","slug":"nobody_puts_java_in_the_containe"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is for people in DevOps teams that are involved in how their systems perform in production. It will go into detail about how easy it is to do Chaos Engineering when using the public cloud, with some examples for AWS and Azure, but will also show how you can get started when stuck with a more traditional hosting provider. Code in slides!","keywords":["devops","cloud","testing"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nikolai Norman Andersen","bio":"Nikolai is a senior consultant and lead developer at BEKK. He is currently working with the The Norwegian Directorate for Education and Training on their systems for digital exams and tests. Nikolai has previously worked as a freelancer, for a small startup and for an advertising agency. His focus is on .NET and DevOps, spending time improving applications and the way they are continuously delivered. He is also a co-organiser of the Oslo F# Meetup and the upcoming DevOpsDays Oslo.","sessionId":"215e79c051ca4b1caf4c47c38a162892"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"215e79c051ca4b1caf4c47c38a162892","abstract":"Our software systems are becoming more complex and more distributed. How do we have confidence in the resilience and redundancy of the systems we put in production? Chaos Engineering is the practice of introducing failures into your system in controlled experiments to learn how your system reacts. In this talk we will look into how to establish the steady state behavior of a system and how to start experimenting to discover if the system can handle spikes in traffic, failures and timeouts.","published":"true","title":"Lord of Chaos - Becoming a Chaos Engineer","slug":"lord_of_chaos__becoming_a_chaos_"},{"intendedAudience":"Everyone. No Code.","keywords":["#qualityoflife","#healthycoding","#brainware"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Irwan Syahrir","bio":"A java programmer. I like learning about almost anything. Fascinated lately about the idea of biohacking and flow state, especially in the context increasing creativity and quality of life.","sessionId":"ef137f1cffae4afb8b22b555f5e08cef"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"ef137f1cffae4afb8b22b555f5e08cef","abstract":"In his book The Rise of Superman, Steven Kotler mentioned computer programming specifically as one of the Flow triggers. Flow is the mental state of operation in which a person performing an activity is fully immersed in a feeling of energized focus, full involvement, and enjoyment in the process of the activity. In essence, flow is characterized by complete absorption in what one does.  Flow is currently studied by, among others, the Flow Genome Project, which is a interdisciplinary, global organization committed to mapping the genome of Flow by 2020 and open sourcing it to everyone. They are a collection of world-class academics, athletes and artists dedicated to taking Flow from the extreme to the mainstream. They advance Flow science and train individuals and organizations to harness Flow in their lives and work.\n\nFlow triggering activities have been used to recover from illnesses. Arguably it is also beneficial to our health and quality of life (happiness?). A healthy and happy coder is most likely to produce a better and sustainable work, both individually as well as a team. \n\nIn this talk I would like to examine the benefits/pitfalls of flow state in a development context. I would also like to present some practical techniques/tools that Flow Genome Project has come up and put them in the software development context.","published":"true","title":"Code with the Flow - Healthy coding","slug":"code_with_the_flow__healthy_codi"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som har vært med i et utviklingsprosjekt. Ingen kode, masse humor!","keywords":["architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Trond Pedersen","bio":"Trond er en engasjert og løsningsorientert utvikler og arkitekt fra Sopra Steria. Han er en ivrig deltager i Oslos utvikler-miljø, og var blant annet med på å etablere  Smidig-Konferansen og XP-meetup. Han har vært en forkjemper for smidig systemutvikling siden 2001 og setter stor pris på gode diskusjoner om alle aspekter ved systemutvikling.","sessionId":"e6ab3f387f824b5fa0422424b64b9eae"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"e6ab3f387f824b5fa0422424b64b9eae","abstract":"Jeg liker endring. Jeg liker å programmere, og jeg liker å se de store linjene. Det har medført at jeg programmerer på ca annet hvert prosjekt jeg er med på, og er “rådgiver”, arkitekt eller lignende i de resterende. I dette foredraget drar jeg denne to-sidigheten ut i det absurde. Jeg beskriver min indre dialog som en boksekamp mellom Arkitekten med stor A, og programmerer-Trond.  Forhåpentligvis ligger det noen lærdommer og litt forståelse i denne beskrivelsen av min indre dialog, også for deg.","published":"true","title":"Arkitekt-meg og Progge-meg i bokseringen","slug":"arkitektmeg_og_proggemeg_i_bokse"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers and architects on any level. There's code in slides.","keywords":["experiencereports","codequality","craftsmanship"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Stian Grenborgen","bio":"Stian Grenborgen is an experienced Java programmer and software architect working for Sopra Steria. He has worked on large and critical systems in the Norwegian government and with infrastructurally crucial systems for the financial sector. He takes a special interest in computer interface design both in his professional capacity and in his spare time.","sessionId":"09379f1314884068a5493a51227f9405"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"09379f1314884068a5493a51227f9405","abstract":"I have some scary examples for you, gathered throughout many years on maintenance and on large modernization projects. Examples of code so indescribably bad that it's difficult to understand how it came to ever exist. These (anonymized) examples have been analyzed in order to determine how they came to be. Participate in this presentation so that you can avoid making the same mistakes in your next development project. ...or live with the misconception that only bad developers make bad code.","published":"true","title":"The Uncomfortable Truth of Bad Code","slug":"the_uncomfortable_truth_of_bad_c"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som har noe erfaring med Git. Ingen kode.","keywords":["craftsmanship","git","version control"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Fredrik Mørken Valdmanis","bio":"Fredrik har 4 års erfaring som utvikler i BEKK, og har brukt git til stort og smått i 7 år. Han er selverklært git-nerd, og prøver stadig å finne nye og bedre måter å bruke verktøyet på.","sessionId":"c6edf67ba6af41f8bda54bad44646ba8"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"c6edf67ba6af41f8bda54bad44646ba8","abstract":"I forlengelsen av clean code bør vi også etterstrebe clean Git-historikk. For å oppnå det bruker mange av oss Git rebase, blant annet til å rydde i rotete historikk, redigere tidligere commitmeldinger eller fjerne flaue commits.\n\nMulighetene er endeløse når man først har lært seg å bruke rebase, men med stor makt følger stort ansvar. Hvor lurt er det egentlig å skrive om historikken i Git? Når bør du gjøre det, og når bør du la være?\n\nHistorieforfalskning forsøker vi vanligvis å unngå, men i den digitale verden må det vel være greit? Eller er det andre farer som lurer?","published":"true","title":"Det er greit å lyve litt, eller?","slug":"det_er_greit__lyve_litt_eller"},{"intendedAudience":"Frontend devlopers, designers and UX","keywords":["ux","frontend","flexbox"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Magnus Dæhlen","bio":"I am Magnús Dæhlen. I work as a solutions engineer at Iterate AS. My main job is working as an IT consultant and I am currently working with Cisco on some really cool stuff.\nI am passionate about web technology and I have held several talks around different web technology, like React, React Native, Flexbox etc. \nOn a more personal note, I am very fond of music and I play in a band with several other developers from Finn.no, Start and Iterate.","sessionId":"7557022b2fdd4196a28872204f435b39"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"7557022b2fdd4196a28872204f435b39","abstract":"De siste årene har responsivitet blitt en viktigere del av nettsideutvikling.\n\nW3C har i løpet av den siste tiden jobbet med en ny måte å style layouten på en nettside. Det de har kommet frem til går under navnet Flexbox.\n\nFlexbox er en layout som skal gjøre det lettere å jobbe med responsivitet og dynamiske elementer. Flere har allerede begynt å ta i bruk dette, som for eksempel React Native.\n\nI denne lyntalen skal jeg ta for meg litt av bakgrunnen til Flexbox og hvordan man effektivt kan ta det i bruk i dag.","published":"true","title":"Flex med bokser","slug":"flex_med_bokser"},{"intendedAudience":"Kom og hør på denne lyntalen dersom du er skallet fordi du har revet av deg alt håret i frustrasjon over at Javascript koden din ikke fungerer.  Og for deg som er ny i Javascript-verden , og ennå ikke har falt i noen feller, men som helst sikkert kommer til å gjøre det når du innser hvor mye som faktisk er lov å gjøre med Javascript.","keywords":["javascript","typesjekker","flow"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Carl Joachim Rørvik","bio":"Full-stack utvikler hos Bekk Consulting. Jobbet mye med React og Redux det siste året. Var tidligere i år med å lage og holde kurs i funksjonell frontendprogrammering for studenter ved UiO og NTNU.","sessionId":"91f96afb32474353b3d1028f7fb493f0"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"91f96afb32474353b3d1028f7fb493f0","abstract":"Har du noen gang tenkt på at du skulle ønske Javascript var et sterkt typet språk? Hvor mange ganger trenger man egentlig å bli fortalt at undefined ikke er en funksjon? Dette var også noe av det de ansatte hos Facebook irriterte seg over. Så de satte seg like godt ned og laget Flow - En statisk typesjekker for Javascript.  Etter denne lyntalen trenger du aldri mer å lure på hvorfor Javascript-koden din feiler. Fra nå er Flow din venn. Flow er power!","published":"true","title":"Flow er power!","slug":"flow_er_power"},{"intendedAudience":"Folk som bruker React og gjerne også Flux (helst i form av Redux) som ønsker å få kontroll på og få testet kompliserte flyter i sine apps. God kjennskap til JavaScript og helst nyeste ES6. Kjennskap til generatorfunksjoner er ikke nødvendig, da det blir gjennomgått. En grunnleggende forståelse for Flux-arkitekturen er nødvendig. Nivået er viderekommende til avansert.","keywords":["react","javascript","redux"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Øystein Strand","bio":"Konsulent i BEKK med interesse for moderne og testbare JavaScript-apps.","sessionId":"3f307de70b4b464d8d4e4a04de97a3c9"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"3f307de70b4b464d8d4e4a04de97a3c9","abstract":"Ajaxkall er et eksempel på operasjoner som er kjipe å teste. Spesielt hvis du skal reagere på responsen og kanskje gjøre nye kall, håndtere feil eller sette i gang nye operasjoner. Koden blir gjerne spagetti med mange callbacks og bruk av mocking for testing. Redux har blitt det definitive biblioteket for å håndtere oppdatering av data i React-apps, men det mangler en måte å orkestrere kompliserte og asynkrone operasjoner. Redux-saga er en mellomvare til Redux som lar deg samle komplekse flyter og sideeffekter i enkle og testbare generatorfunksjoner - helt uten bruk av mocking og callbacks. Det blir vist kodeeksempler, med full testdekning, på hvordan redux-saga løser praktiske utfordringer vi har hatt på Skatteetaten, bl.a. ajaxkall, feilhåndtering, sekvensielle og parallelle flyter, analytics, throttling og innlogging/oppstart.","published":"true","title":"100% testdekning i React-apps","slug":"100_testdekning_i_reactapps"},{"intendedAudience":"Ingen kode. Passer både for utviklere og mindre tekniske.","keywords":["beginner","experiencereports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Frank Jensen","bio":"Frank har jobbed med Java-basert webutvikling i 10 år, og vært utviklingssjef i ett. Fokus har vært på nettavisene til NHST Media Group, hvor Dagens Næringsliv er den mest kjente. På fritiden prøves gjerne andre språk i andre kontekster.","sessionId":"a510936865fb4a7db74fc3756c18e316"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"a510936865fb4a7db74fc3756c18e316","abstract":"Hackaton er ikke bare en metode for å få utviklere og andre til å jobbe sene kvelder, betalt kun med mat drikke, og muligheten for å vinne heder og kule gadgets. Aller viktigst er det et forum der utviklere og andre kan møtes for idemyldring og samarbeid som er verdifull og gøy for alle som er involvert.\n\nDagens Næringsliv har begynt å arrangere Hackaton årlig, og her vil jeg si litt om hvor nyttig og gøy dette er. Vi har opplevd originiale idéer fra uventet hold, og får implementert funksjonelle prototyper. Vi så også at utviklere, forretningsutviklere, redaksjon, designere og andre kunne samarbeide akkurat så godt som optimistene hevdet på forhånd.\n\nEtter lyntalen håper jeg du har gode nok argumenter for å overbevise din bedrift om å arrangere dette, så du kan oppleve det selv.","published":"true","title":"Hacakton i Dagens Næringsliv","slug":"hacakton_i_dagens_nringsliv"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle nivåer. Vil være noe kode på slidene.","keywords":["api","diffy","backend"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anders Ullnæss","bio":"Fagleder for mobilitet i Mesan. Jobber både med mobil backend, Android og iOS.\nLager for tiden apper og API-er for å se på TV, lese nyheter og sjekke været hos NRK.","sessionId":"f2d0c56a2f474d1f9516121043015f4e"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"f2d0c56a2f474d1f9516121043015f4e","abstract":"Har du noen gang refaktorert backendkoden din eller latt være selv om du egentlig har lyst?\nHar du noen gang krasjet klientene fordi du ikke sjekket nøye nok at outputen fra endepunktene var lik som før endringen?\nDa er denne talken for deg! \n\nLær hvordan du kan sammenligne outputen fra før og etter endringene dine for å oppdage utilsiktede bieffekter ved hjelp av verktøyet Diffy fra Twitter.","published":"true","title":"Diff deg til trygghet!","slug":"diff_deg_til_trygghet"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers. Code in slides","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Haakon G. Eriksen","bio":"Utvikler hos FINN.no, som gjerne blander seg i alt fra apps-utvikling\ntil konfigurasjon av lastbalanserere.","sessionId":"3acd7825b3424e79818c507f782dfa11"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"3acd7825b3424e79818c507f782dfa11","abstract":"Mange moderne IT-organisasjoner har som mål at utviklerne skal ta\nansvar for koden sin helt ut i produksjon. Likevel bruker de\ndriftsverktøy som er laget for den tradisjonelle modellen hvor\nutviklerne leverer koden sin til driftsavdelingen, og de to miljøene\ndeler relativt lite av både kode og kunnskap.\n\nIstedenfor at utviklerne skriver integrasjonstester som sjekker at\nsoftwaren oppfører seg som den skal før deployment og drift konfigurerer\nmonitoreringsverktøy som også sjekker at softwaren oppfører seg som\nden skal i produksjon, kan vi tenke oss at vi kan gjenbruke denne logikken?\nDenne talken vil undersøke fordeler og ulemper ved å bruke tradisjonelle\ncompile-time tester som en del av runtime-helsesjekker av en applikasjon.","published":"true","title":"Gjenbruk av software-tester for systemovervåkning","slug":"gjenbruk_av_softwaretester_for_s"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere, Devops'ere  og andre som ønsker å konfigurere sine kjøremiljøer på en enklere måte... Det blir ikke så mye kode men litt konfigurasjonsfiler.","keywords":["devops","scripting","cloud"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Rune Storløpa","bio":"Rune jobber i Knowit, og har jobbet 15 år i bransjen som utvikler, arkitekt og teknisk prosjektleder (og av og til noen andre roller også). De siste 6 årene har han jobbet i forskjellige prosjekter som praktiserer DevOps-prinsipper og senest i et prosjekt hvor kjøremiljøet ligger på Amazon AWS.","sessionId":"fa7b6d41d06248cfbd437d4560e12ea5"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"fa7b6d41d06248cfbd437d4560e12ea5","abstract":"\"Alle\" vil i skyen, og \"alle\" vil kjøre Devops. Det ville vi også i mitt siste prosjekt. Men et skymiljø i f.eks. Amazon AWS inneholder mange bevegelige deler. Så å sette det opp riktig er ikke nødvendigvis trivielt. Og selv når man har fått et miljø som fungerer, er det ikke helt enkelt å duplisere det, slik at testmiljøer og produksjon blir like.\n\nJeg går igjennom den reisen vi gjorde fra manuell konfigurasjon gjennom flere iterasjoner til dagens løsning. Jeg viser hva som skal til for å sette opp et miljø i AWS, og hvordan dette kan gjøres enklere og mer reproduserbart ved å bruke skripting og Terraform. Og i tillegg deles noen erfaringer på veien.","published":"true","title":"Hvordan bruke Terraform for å konfigurere Amazon AWS","slug":"hvordan_bruke_terraform_for__kon"},{"intendedAudience":"For those interested in video, image stream or audio programming, image or audio composition or just something quite different from other presentations.","keywords":["distributedsystems","architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Stig Lau","bio":"10 yrs exp in Kringsjå Skolemusikk. DSLR in attic. Have eaten more with javaBin than at home. Made an app for converting XML into music videos.","sessionId":"c21817b4fc77464c9f67245f7ecd944e"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"c21817b4fc77464c9f67245f7ecd944e","abstract":"Are you a rock star dev? What if the next tech revolution has nerds coding video algorithms and data structures like web apps of the early 2000’s? \n\nProgrammatically editing video is not that difficult. The presentation focuses on the architecture of a server-side app for video-editing - algorithms and data structures for handling image streams.","published":"true","title":"If coding music videos was easy as algdat and cloud","slug":"if_coding_music_videos_was_easy_"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers, code in slides","keywords":["testing","tools"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Cecilie Haugstvedt","bio":"Test lead in Computas with a technical background. Has been working with test in public sector for the last couple of years and is currently spending her time improving testing of legacy and not-so-legacy systems. Believes the quality of the system is the responsibility of the entire team and not something you leave to testers alone. Likes to play with gadgets on her free time.","sessionId":"525d4f2680cd4c229ac51824415f57c1"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"525d4f2680cd4c229ac51824415f57c1","abstract":"TDD is all good but testing is more than checking that the code does what the requirements says it should do. OK, it might happen that we forget a requirement or two. However, the majority of bugs arrives in situations that are not mentioned in the specfication. How do we discover these situations? Luck? Going back to waterfall and spending months on getting the requirements perfect before we start coding? Performing rigerous manual testing after the development is done?\n\nExploratory testing is a powerful approach to testing that has been used by the testing community for more than 25 years. It is especially useful when working with complex solutions, incomplete requirements and specifications, and/or time-pressure. Does the situation sounds familiar? \n\nIn this talk we'll look at how to apply the ideas behind exploratory testing and use them to find potential error situations and write more robust code. You might not learn to win the lottery but you'll learn how to find more of the nasty bugs before you commit your code to the repository.","published":"true","title":"Learn to be Lucky","slug":"learn_to_be_lucky"},{"intendedAudience":"Lyntalen er en introduksjon for alle som er nysgjerrige på IoT, iBeacons og Googles fysiske web.","keywords":["iot","beacon"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anders Hefre","bio":"Jobber til daglig som systemutvikler og fagleder for Java i Bekk. Mine interesser er programmeringsspråk, mobil utvikling og alt av nye teknologier.","sessionId":"3aa13597174641b99304d78971dd05c9"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"3aa13597174641b99304d78971dd05c9","abstract":"Det har gått over to år siden iBeacon ble nevnt på Apples World Wide Developers Conference. Google sitt prosjekt \"Physical Web\" ble lansert først i september i fjor. Hva skiller disse to? Hva finnes av applikasjoner og bruksområder? Kom for å høre en introduksjon til teknologiene og en sammenlingning av disse to.","published":"true","title":"IoT – Googles fysiske web og Apples iBeacon","slug":"iot__googles_fysiske_web_og_appl"},{"intendedAudience":"Looking into the main Java conferences around the world, you cannot find any Maven related sessions that guide you through the fundamentals. Maybe the community assumes that you should already know them, like the Java language itself. Still, recycling this knowledge could be a win-win situation for everyone. How much time developers waste with not knowing how to deal with Maven particularities?\n\nI wrote a blog post about this: http://www.radcortez.com/maven-common-problems-and-pitfalls/ and the session is going to include most of the post information, plus additional problems and practices that can help developers to be more effective when working with Maven.","keywords":["maven"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Roberto Cortez","bio":"My name is Roberto Cortez and I am a professional Java Developer working in the software development industry, with more than 10 years of experience in business areas like Finance, Insurance and Government.\n\nAs a Freelancer / Independent Contractor I travelled around the world to customers, but also to attend Java conferences. The direct contact with the Java community made me want to become an active member in the community itself. For that reason, I have created the Coimbra JUG, started to contribute to Open Source on Github and launched my own blog.\n\nCurrently, I’m working with Tomitribe. I’m very excited to work with all the amazing tribers working hard to make TomEE a compelling Java EE server.","sessionId":"fa08690e3d2c4ceb9e33f33f1715fd22"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"fa08690e3d2c4ceb9e33f33f1715fd22","abstract":"Love it or hate it (and a lot of people seem to hate it), Maven is a widely used tool. We can consider that Maven has been the de-facto standard build tool for Java over the last 10 years. Most experienced developers already got their share of Maven headaches. Unfortunately, new developers are going through the same hard learning process, because they don't know how to deal with Maven particularities. \"Why is this jar in my build?\", \"I can’t see my changes!\", \"The jar is not included in the distribution!\", \"The artifact was not found!\" are common problems. Learn to tame the Maven Beast and be in complete control of your build to save you countless hours of pain and frustration.","published":"true","title":"Maven - Taming the Beast","slug":"maven__taming_the_beast"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is for you if you are developing Hibernate/JPA applications and would like to add full-text search functionality. You will learn how easy that task is made via Hibernate Search. You should have an average knowledge of JPA, knowledge of Elasticsearch is not required. There will be code in slides and a small amount of live coding.","keywords":["hibernate","elasticsearch"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Gunnar Morling","bio":"Gunnar Morling works as software engineer in the Hibernate team at Red Hat, focusing on Hibernate OGM, Validator, and Search. He is also is serving in the expert group for Bean Validation. In his spare time Gunnar is leading the MapStruct project. Prior to joining Red Hat, Gunnar worked on a wide range of Java EE projects in the logistics and retail industries. He is based in Hamburg, Germany.","sessionId":"3cd6c2e1c4294a1e8b79c5ebf8208e56"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"3cd6c2e1c4294a1e8b79c5ebf8208e56","abstract":"A great search experience is a must-have for enterprise applications these days. As full-text search in databases often is limited, Elasticsearch steps in and offers powerful search services through a REST API.\n\nKeeping your domain model and Elasticsearch in sync may seem easy first, but the devil is in the details. What about type conversions, handling of nested entities and associations or the processing of query results?\n\nBut no worries, Hibernate Search has got you covered. In this talk you will learn how to index your entity model with the help of a few annotations, let Hibernate Search take care of the database/Elasticsearch synchronization and get back managed objects from full-text queries.\n\nBased on common use cases, you will find out how to prepare your model for indexing, synchronous and asynchronous index updates, different approaches for running searches and more. Be prepared to see code and the great combo of Hibernate Search and Elasticsearch in action.","published":"true","title":"From Hibernate to Elasticsearch in no time","slug":"from_hibernate_to_elasticsearch_"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som savner en kreativ outlet. Det blir enklere å følge med hvis du har erfaring med JavaScript, men det er ikke noe must. Ingen forhåndskunnskap om musikkteori er påkrevd. Det blir kode i slides.","keywords":["creative","web","music"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Stian Veum Møllersen","bio":"Utvikler basert i Oslo. Under gjennomsnittlig god på piano, røver på finger-trommer og skikkelig glad i musikk. Tror alle har en musiker i seg, de har bare ikke funnet rett instrument enda. Fagleder for Webgrensesnitt i BEKK.","sessionId":"6230a419068a46cb9f61296632c49a45"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"6230a419068a46cb9f61296632c49a45","abstract":"Nettleseren som musikkinstrument? JavaScript som tangenter i et piano? WebAudio og WebMIDI gjør nettleseren din til det mest portable elektroniske instrumentet til nå, med et par linjer kode har du ditt eget instrument. Kun kreativiteten setter grenser for hva du kan høre av din egen kode!","published":"true","title":"Nettleseren som musikkinstrument","slug":"nettleseren_som_musikkinstrument"},{"intendedAudience":"This workshop is for developers comfortable with JavaScript. Experience with React and Redux is preferable, but not required.\n\nYou'll need to bring your own laptop (Windows/OSX/Linux), ready for React Native development. We'll email you setup instructions a week or two before the conference.","keywords":["react-native","react","javascript"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Aleksander Hindenes","bio":"Aleksander is a web developer with an entrepreneurial mind. He has two years experience working for Bekk Consulting AS, building Single Page Apps for a public sector client. As of this fall, he'll be an independent Oslo-based consultant, taking on new and exciting projects.","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"},{"name":"Markus Nilssen","bio":"Markus is a developer working as a consultant for BEKK in Oslo. Although he deals with every level of the stack, he reserves some extra love for javascript and Single Page Apps. When he is not cranking out code, he enjoys rock climbing and other outdoor activities.","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"},{"name":"Anum Qudsia","bio":"Developer with experience in various technologies such as Swift, Java, .Net, Xamarin, Javascript, MBaaS (Parse) etc. Anum is very passionate for mobile apps and has spent the last few years developing apps for numerous clients. She has worked on several app projects and released these to the App Store. She has contributed in holding workshops at BEKK and Mobile Meetup in Oslo. In her spare time she enjoys creating novice apps, play music, skydive and travel.","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"},{"name":"Simen Lomås Johannessen","bio":"Simen is an iOS enthusiast with 4 years’ experience. During the day, he spends his time at SpareBank1 developing Norway’s best mobile bank solution. He spends a lot of his free time investigating the JavaScript world and in particular looking into React ecosystem.","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"},{"name":"Anders Kristiansen","bio":"Anders is a full-stack developer at BEKK with an extra interest in frontend and mobile apps. He works with cross plattform app development for Android and iOS at a daily basis at his current project. When he is not building software he likes building stuff in and around his house.","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"},{"name":"Nicklas Utgaard","bio":"-","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938"}],"format":"workshop","language":"en","sessionId":"81408fcbcee94d2aa123920b9e25f938","abstract":"Hands-on introduction to React Native – Facebook's open source library for building cross-platform native mobile apps.  \n\nYou'll make a messaging client for a simple chat API. You can choose if you want to develop for Android or iOS (or both!). \n\nIn this workshop you'll gain insight in how you can use your web development skills to create native mobile apps with React Native. You'll see how you can leverage popular JavaScript libraries like React, Redux, fetch, etc., without sacrificing the native look and feel. You'll create the layout using Flexbox, which React Native \"borrows\" from CSS.","published":"true","title":"Introduction to React Native","slug":"introduction_to_react_native"},{"intendedAudience":"Programmers that know Java and maven, and need to create a windows service.\n\nCode level: basic","keywords":["maven","windows service"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Steinar Bang","bio":"Senior solutions architect at Sopra Steria.\n\nWhat makes me happy is putting things together from open source and free software out there, and create stuff for others to use.\n\n30 years of experience in programming and electronics.","sessionId":"e4fd602aa8654480b168fc1c974d83f8"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"e4fd602aa8654480b168fc1c974d83f8","abstract":"A task often needed is to make your Java program a Windows Service. This is may be a bump in your project, particularily if you don't know anything about windows services.\n\nThis 10 minute demo explains how to overcome this bump by implementing a single interface and adding a little maven magic to create an izpack installer that installs your program as a windows service.","published":"true","title":"A Java windows service in 10 minutes","slug":"a_java_windows_service_in_10_min"},{"intendedAudience":"Lyntalen er for alle som er nysgjerrige på opne data, og ønskjer ei kjapp innføring og overblikk. Ingen kode, med unntak av eit par små eksempel på data i JSON-format.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Livar Bergheim","bio":"Livar har jobba med opne data og informasjonsforvaltning i Difi sidan juni 2015, og med opne data nokre år før det. Utdanninga er informatikk/programvareutvikling. Han jobbar som rådgjevar, men finn stadig anledningar til å få programmert litt i jobben og på fritida. I jobben held han mange foredrag om opne data, og brenn for mulegheitene meir deling av data gir.","sessionId":"30aa8a371f324761b387dd8a61502c05"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"30aa8a371f324761b387dd8a61502c05","abstract":"I denne lyntalen får du ein introduksjon til kva opne offentlege data er, og eit overblikk over området.\n\nFor eksempel kva opne offentlege data er, kvar du finn data, korleis du går fram for å få tak i data som endå ikkje er publisert, eit par eksempel på korleis opne offentlege data er brukt og siste nytt om opne offentlege data i Norge.\n\nDifi har ansvaret for det nasjonale registeret over opne offentlege data - http://data.norge.no/\nDer finn du oversikt over datasett frå offentleg sektor, informasjon og rettleiing, samt døme på bruk av opne offentlege data.","published":"true","title":"Gratis maskinlesbare data frå offentleg sektor, ja takk!","slug":"gratis_maskinlesbare_data_fr_off"},{"intendedAudience":"Utvecklare och testare. No code.","keywords":["docker","experiencereports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jonas Nordstrand","bio":"Svensk utvecklare som tillbringat snart tio år i den norska förskingringen med att utveckla nettbank i olika sammanhang. Jobbar idag för SpareBank 1 med att utveckla spännande ting för 750.000 bankkunder - och med att se till tingen kommer på luften snabbare än någonsin. \n\nBrinner för förenkling, testautomatisering och vikten av att lösa de rätta problemen.","sessionId":"ffa92929206a49f7960f9f17627cd3e9"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"ffa92929206a49f7960f9f17627cd3e9","abstract":"Med Dockers nätverksstöd är det smärtfritt att ta full kontroll över baksystemerna och ersätta länkarna till dessa med mock-containers. Detta gör det möjligt att köra stabila och isolerade end-2-end tester direkt på byggservern!\n\nI talken ser vi nærmare på olika möjligheter för att mocka flera typer baksystemer.","published":"true","title":"End-2-End testning med Docker: mock it all - or die trying!","slug":"end2end_testning_med_docker_mock"},{"intendedAudience":"Lyntalen er for alle de som er interessert i testautomatisering, både utviklere som har lyst å se noen eksempler på testautomatisering i praksis og de som ønsker en mer overordnet intro til testautomatisering og hva man bør tenke på før man setter i gang med utvikling av slike tester. Presentasjonen har med noen få kodeeksempler.","keywords":["testautomatisering"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Hege Hansbakk Huuse","bio":"Hege jobber som konsulent i Bouvet. Her har hun vært systemutvikler i både små og store smidige prosjekter innenfor Java-miljøet. De siste årene har Hege imidlertid gått fra å være ren utvikler til å spisse sin kompetanse som funksjonell arkitekt og innen fagområdet automatiserte funksjonelle tester.\n\nTidligere har Hege flere års erfaring som utvikler og drifter på CERN i Sveits. Hun har bakgrunn som sivilingeniør fra NTNU og har nå 13 års erfaring innen IT-bransjen.","sessionId":"2e695984a31445be84843607c87e9096"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"2e695984a31445be84843607c87e9096","abstract":"Denne presentasjonen er en intro til testautomatisering. Hva er det? Når bør vi automatisere våre tester? Hvilke fordeler gir testautomatisering og hvilke utfordringer støter man på ved utvikling av slike tester?\n\nHvis du i tillegg ønsker å få noen tips i forhold til når det er hensiktsmessig å automatisere en test og hvordan man kan lykkes med testautomatisering, er dette presentasjonen for deg.\n\nTil slutt vil jeg også vise noen eksempler på hvordan testautomatisering kan gjøres i praksis. Her vil jeg vise eksempler fra to ulike prosjekter og med verktøy som Java, Selenium WebDriver, egendefinerte DSL´er, ExtentReports, RSpec, Ruby og Capybara.","published":"true","title":"Testautomatisering: Hva, når, hvordan?","slug":"testautomatisering_hva_nr_hvorda"},{"intendedAudience":"> Who should attend this session?\nEveryone involved with Software\n\n> How will the participants benefit from attending? \nReceive insight into the business of Open Source from someone living off Open Source\n\n> Explicitly state what your audience needs to know in order to get the most out of your presentation.\nNo prerequisites, No code","keywords":["opensource","business"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lukas Eder","bio":"Lukas Eder is the founder and CEO of Data Geekery GmbH, located in Zurich, Switzerland. With his company he has been selling database products and services around Java and SQL since 2013. Ever since his Master’s studies at EPFL in 2006, he has been fascinated by the interaction of Java and SQL. Most of this experience he has obtained in the Swiss E-Banking field through various variants (JDBC, Hibernate, mostly with Oracle). As a Java Champion, he is happy to share this knowledge at various conferences, JUGs, in-house presentations and on his blog. Here’s his conference and JUG talk schedule for the most recent time: http://www.jooq.org/news.","sessionId":"0189c2e53f2a46c3a72001b07c43f2e1"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"0189c2e53f2a46c3a72001b07c43f2e1","abstract":"Open Source is ubiquitous. Open Source is inevitable. But why would anyone even engage in Open Source? Does making money with it even work?\n\nModern Open Source is not Richard Stallman's Open Source anymore. Now that even Microsoft is open sourcing .NET (and possibly: Windows?), we'll need to review our opinions about Open Source.\n\nLarge corporations have engaged in commoditising their infrastructure software via Open Source in order to increase demand for their primary offerings: PaaS, SaaS, and IaaS.\n\nAnd with this new model in mind, we'll have a short look into whether it still makes sense for ISVs to engage in Open Source development, or if we should just enjoy the massive free ride.","published":"true","title":"This isn't Richard Stallman's Open Source Anymore","slug":"this_isnt_richard_stallmans_open"},{"intendedAudience":"Denne talken passer for alle som har litt kodeerfaring, men man trenger på ingen måte å være ekspert. Talken vil være på et grunnleggende nivå, men kjennskap til algoritmer og kunstig intelligens vil være en fordel.","keywords":["ai","swarm intelligence","np-hard problems"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Hanne Gunby","bio":"Utvikler i BEKK Consulting. I mai 2015 leverte jeg en master på NTNU der jeg brukte en Swarm Intelligence-algoritme til å optimalisere bussrute-planlegging.","sessionId":"15d8e609d2e54ab391c76f7b53d6d7ba"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"15d8e609d2e54ab391c76f7b53d6d7ba","abstract":"Matematikere og programmerere har lenge prøvd å finne optimale løsninger på problemer som ikke lar seg løse direkte ved å bruke algoritmer eller formler. Et eksempel på et slikt problem er The Travelling Salesman Problem. \n\nI noen tilfeller har man godtatt at det kan være svært vanskelig å finne den aller beste løsningen, og man har i stedet funnet strategier for å komme fram til nesten optimale løsninger. Disse kan i mange tilfeller være svært verdifulle selv om de ikke er helt helt optimale.\n\nI naturen har insekter som maur og bier vist seg ekstremt dyktige til å finne korteste vei mellom to punkter. Dette gjør de ved å dele informasjon og dermed bygge en slags kollektiv intelligens. Basert på denne framgangsmåten har det blitt utformet en modell for kunstig intelligens som kalles \"swarm intelligence\". Ideen er at man lager systemer som hermer etter hvordan disse insektene kommuniserer med hverandre, for på denne måten å kunne finne tilnærmet korteste vei på en rask måte.\n\nVi skal se kort på hva swarm intelligence er ved hjelp av praktiske eksempler, og vi skal diskutere hvordan sverminspirerte algoritmer kan brukes på andre problemer - og hvordan dette kan bli mer relevant i fremtiden.","published":"true","title":"Swarm Intelligence - løsningen på uløselige problemer?","slug":"swarm_intelligence__lsningen_p_u"},{"intendedAudience":"Intermediate - All Code.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Hadi Hariri","bio":"Developer and creator of many things OSS, his passions includes Web Development and Software Architecture. Has authored a couple of books, a few courses and has been speaking at industry events for nearly 15 years. Currently at JetBrains leading the Developer Advocacy team. Spends as much time as he can writing code.","sessionId":"b7f5dd796ae140bcb58a018dd91d6c20"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"b7f5dd796ae140bcb58a018dd91d6c20","abstract":"Kotlin, a language developed by JetBrains for nearly 5 years is very close to its first release. However, did you know that it's being used in production for over a few years now already? Both inside and outside of JetBrains there are people deploying Kotlin applications for Android platform, for Web Applications and just about any other type of application.\n \nWhy are people using it instead of Java or some of the other languages out there? Primarily because it provides significant benefits in terms of conciseness, readability and safety, without some of the drawbacks that adopting a new language has such as a higher learning curve or interoperability with existing code and ecosystems. \n \nIn this talk we'll cover some aspects of Kotlin that can really help you in your daily development, focusing on solving issues versus highlighting language features.","published":"true","title":"Kotlin - Ready for Production","slug":"kotlin__ready_for_production"},{"intendedAudience":"Coding will be done. Experts and beginners may attend, we have tasks ranging from easy to difficult, so there is something for everyone.\n\nYou will need to bring your own laptop with:\n          * Git \n          * Node.js (4.x.x)\n          * Your favorite JavaScript editor\n        We know it can be very frustrating if something unexpected happens (during the install or the workshop) so we will bring some macbooks with the software preinstalled and tested.","keywords":["iot","javascript","gadgets"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Alexander Svendsen","bio":"Alexander is a full-stack developer at BEKK by day and a crime fighting vigilante by night. When he is not fighting super villains he enjoys learning new things and hacking on different hobby projects in domains like machine-learning, functional programming and IOT.","sessionId":"50587664ebb34d5286f252946c9375f5"},{"name":"Snorre Lothar von Gohren Edwin","bio":"Snorre is currently a full stack developer at BEKK and generally is curious about new technology. When IoT entered the tech world, Snorre decided that a workshop would suite perfectly for a platform for all the curious techies. Blockchain is another technology that is on Snorre´s radar now. He loves to discuss these subjects with interested people!","sessionId":"50587664ebb34d5286f252946c9375f5"},{"name":"Birgitte Haavardsholm","bio":"Birgitte is a fullstack developer at BEKK. She works mostly with java and javascript. At her spare time she enjoys playing with iot and machine learning.","sessionId":"50587664ebb34d5286f252946c9375f5"},{"name":"Vegard Veiset","bio":"Vegard is a senior full-stack developer at BEKK and has a passion for internet of things, gadgets and hacks. He enjoys meeting like-minded people and is one of the founders of Pils & Programming Oslo, a meetup which is simply about hacking together on hobby projects while enjoying a few beers.","sessionId":"50587664ebb34d5286f252946c9375f5"}],"format":"workshop","language":"no","sessionId":"50587664ebb34d5286f252946c9375f5","abstract":"Have you ever been curious to what IoT is, but never really taken the step to try it out? Then this is the perfect workshop for you!\n\nWe will be working together in groups of 2-3 people and explore gadgets, sensors, and connect with the all loving cloud. You will be controlling cool gadgets, reading values from the physical world and cooporate with groups in the room to create exciting integrations.\n\nThis is a hands-on workshop and the programming language used is Javascript. The targeted platforms are arduino and photons. The devices will be communicating through Firebase.","published":"true","title":"Internet of Things for Everyone!","slug":"internet_of_things_for_everyone"},{"intendedAudience":"This session is suitable for anyone who wants to have fun programming art.  It is also relevant for anyone who wants to teach others how to code.\n\nThis presentation will mostly consist of live coding, with only a minimal amount of Powerpoint.","keywords":["processing","games","live coding"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ragnar Aas","bio":"Amateur photographer, java professional, globetrotter, music lover, stargazer. In my professional life, I work as a consultant at Bouvet.","sessionId":"83ff19b60e4e44958470345db238ff8c"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"83ff19b60e4e44958470345db238ff8c","abstract":"To some, programming is an art form. To others, programming can be used to create Art.\n\nWhen your daily routine consists of hacking boilerplate code and wading through tons of code to fix incomprehensible bugs, relaxing with some simple creative fun programming is just the ticket to start believing in the good things in life again. \n\nProcessing (https://processing.org) may be just that ticket. Attend this session for a practical introduction to the Processing language","published":"true","title":"The Art of Processing","slug":"the_art_of_processing"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som er påvirket av arkitektur i store bedrifter.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Trond Pedersen","bio":"Trond er en engasjert og løsningsorientert utvikler og arkitekt fra Sopra Steria. Han er en ivrig deltager i Oslos utvikler-miljø, og var blant annet med på å etablere  Smidig-Konferansen og XP-meetup. Han har vært en forkjemper for smidig systemutvikling siden 2001 og setter stor pris på gode diskusjoner om alle aspekter ved systemutvikling.","sessionId":"802e47365c674fa5a5dfa7ded3a13649"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"802e47365c674fa5a5dfa7ded3a13649","abstract":"Vi lager systemer for store bedrifter. Men som stor bedrift har man et helt økosystem av systemer. Noen systemer er kjøpt fordi man fant en god leverandør. Noen er laget fra grunnen av i for eksempel java, og noen (service busser) er der for å lage arkitekturtegningene vakrere!\n\nSå vi kommer ikke unna at Store Bedrifter trenger Arkitektur. Men trenger vi Arkitekter? Og hvordan kan vi utvikle arkitekturen i en bedrift i riktig retning? I dette foredraget ser vi på hvordan vi som mennesker bygger organisasjoner, som bygger systemer. Det betyr at det ikke nødvendigvis blir slik som Sjefarkitekten vil !.","published":"true","title":"På tur med Arkitektur i STORE Bedrifter","slug":"p_tur_med_arkitektur_i_store_bed"},{"intendedAudience":"Ansvarlige utviklere. Ingen spesifikk forkunnskap kreves.\n\nCode in slides.","keywords":["devops","monitoring","craftsmanship"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Truls Jørgensen","bio":"Blir ofte kalt arkitekt, men kaller seg selv utvikler. 10 års erfaring. Fersk ansatt i NAV. Elsker kode, kaffe og Pearl Jam.","sessionId":"7705d12819104920bf0860bc7765c96b"},{"name":"Johnny Horvi","bio":"Engasjert fullstack utviklerfyr med 6 års erfaring. Drikker kulturmelk på daglig basis.","sessionId":"7705d12819104920bf0860bc7765c96b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"7705d12819104920bf0860bc7765c96b","abstract":"Kjære ansvarlige utvikler. Du bryr deg om applikasjonen din. Du bryr deg om hvor mange som bruker den, og hvordan hendelser påvirker den. Har responstiden utviklet seg i positiv eller negativ retning i det siste? Den ytelsesforbedringen du gjorde - halverte du virkelig minnebruken slik du trodde, eller økte den i stedet med 10%? Vi mener at de valgene du tar for applikasjonen bør være basert på fakta, og at disse skal være lett tilgjengelig for deg hele veien fra utvikling til produksjon. Denne informasjonen består også av mer enn disk-, minne- og cpu-bruk. Standardmetrikker er vel og bra, men det er først når du kobler disse dataene med informasjon og hendelser som er unike for akkurat din applikasjon at monitoreringsløsningen blir uunnværlig.\n\nVi vil i løpet av dette fordraget gi deg kunnskapen og verktøyene for å sette opp en skalerbar, robust og åpen monitoreringsløsning med bruk av InfluxDB, Grafana og Sensu, og grave dypere i de tekniske og filosofiske detaljene rundt monitorering. Vi vil også vise hvordan vi har satt opp denne løsningen for over 3000 servere, som til sammen genererer ~1 millard datapunkter per døgn.","published":"true","title":"Continious Monitoring","slug":"continious_monitoring"},{"intendedAudience":"No code. \n\nFor alle som er interessert i å levere store systemer","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Jørn Ola Birkeland","bio":"Prosjektleder, arkitekt og utvikler i 20 år, siste 5 år i Skatteetaten i MAG/EDAG og SOFUS.","sessionId":"c9876a89fc084b858b0c3c2d5f689ca4"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"c9876a89fc084b858b0c3c2d5f689ca4","abstract":"... produksjonssatte ett år tidligere enn planlagt.\n\nSOFUS-prosjektet hos Skatteetaten lanserte ny plattform for forskuddsberegning ett år før opprinnelig plan. Det inkluderte ny infrastruktur, ny sluttbrukerflate, ny saksbehandlingsløsning og ny beregningsplattform.\n\nHvordan er det mulig? Svaret får du her.","published":"true","title":"Offentlig IT-prosjekt bommet på tiden ...","slug":"offentlig_itprosjekt_bommet_p_ti"},{"intendedAudience":"People looking to use Kubernetes in production. Experience with Kubernetes is not requried, but being familiar with containers is assumed.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Paul Bakker","bio":"Paul is working as a software architect for Luminis Technologies, where he's currently leading the team that develops the CloudRTI; a Kubernetes/Docker based service that takes care of DevOps tasks like blue/green deployment, failover, centralised logging and monitoring. He is the author of “Building Modular Cloud Apps With OSGi” published by O'Reilly and an advocate for modularity in software. He is currently writing his second book for O'Reilly \"Java 9 Modularity\" which is expected early 2017.\n\nHe's also deeply involved in Amdatu, an open source library for highly modular OSGi components, and several other open source projects. He's a regular speaker on conferences speaking both about modularity/OSGi related topics, and topics related to Kubernetes and cloud architecture in general.","sessionId":"4cc304ba0bea4eeba4b50a1ed3f9ec3d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"4cc304ba0bea4eeba4b50a1ed3f9ec3d","abstract":"Kubernetes is a great tool to run (Docker) containers in a clustered production environment. When deploying often to production we need fully automated blue-green deployments, which makes it possible to deploy without any downtime. We also need to handle external HTTP requests and SSL offloading. This requires integration with a load balancer like Ha-Proxy. Another concern is (semi) auto scaling of the Kubernetes cluster itself when running in a cloud environment. E.g.  partially scale down the cluster at night.\n\nIn this technical deep dive you will learn how to setup Kubernetes together with other open source components to achieve  a production ready environment that takes code from git commit to production without downtime.","published":"true","title":"Kubernetes automation in production","slug":"kubernetes_automation_in_product"},{"intendedAudience":"Java-utviklere som har begynte å bevege seg inn i verdenen med Java 8 og funksjonell programmering. Kode i slides.","keywords":["functionalprogramming","javase","java8"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Fredrik Vraalsen","bio":"Fredrik works as a software developer and consultant at Iterate. His main interest the past couple of years has been functional programming and in particluar how to apply this in his daily job as a Java developer. Recently he has started writing Scala for a living and is trying his best to catch up. He's held training courses in Scala and Java 8 and dabbled in Clojure, and likes to speak at conferences.","sessionId":"f5c105670c0c410486642780306ae8c3"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"f5c105670c0c410486642780306ae8c3","abstract":"Java 8 åpnet slusene for funksjonell programmering (FP) i Java, men verktøykassen som følger med JDKen er ganske mangelfull. Man har ingen støtte for immutable objekter og datastrukturer, som er helt essensielt innen FP og hjelper deg å fjerne en rekke typer kodefeil. I tillegg mangler for eksempel mer høynivå mekanismer for parallellisering av oppgaver.\n\nI dette foredraget vil vi gå igjennom et utvalg av tredjepartsbiblioteker som du kan ta i bruk for å bøte på disse problemene og gjøre Java-koden din ennå mer sikker og funksjonell!","published":"true","title":"Hjelp, vi skal kode funksjonelt i Java!","slug":"hjelp_vi_skal_kode_funksjonelt_i"},{"intendedAudience":"Code in slides, major benefits for Developers and DevOps guys.","keywords":["jenkins","continuous delivery","devops"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Alex Soto","bio":"Alex is a software engineer at Red Hat. He is a passionate of Java world, software automation and he believes in the open source software model.\n\nAlex is the creator of NoSQLUnit project and team member of Arquillian, Asciidoctor and Apache TomEE projects. He is a member of JSR374 (Java API for JSON Processing) Expert Group and coordinator at Barcelona JUG. Currently Alex is co-writing Arquillian in Action book for Manning and he is an international speaker presenting his talks at software conferences like Devoxx, JavaOne, JavaZone or JavaLand.","sessionId":"b27a333e962549b98d8fc1f4b4688a27"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"b27a333e962549b98d8fc1f4b4688a27","abstract":"Jenkins Pipeline is a game changing way to write automation jobs with Jenkins. Pipeline supports from simple one-step hello-world type jobs to the most complex parallel pipelines or Docker operations like creation or publication of images. Best of all, they support manual/automated intervention and also an extension mechanism to avoid the DRY effect on your build pipeline. Combining Jenkins Pipeline with Docker can seriously reduce friction in your DevOps efforts. \n\nBut Jenkins Pipeline is not the only new thing that are in Jenkins 2.0, there is also UX improvements better out-of-the-box experience and a new website.\n\nCome to this session to learn what’s new in Jenkins 2.0 and how you can improve your Continuous Delivery Pipeline with Jenkins Pipeline as well as see what is coming after Jenkins 2.0.","published":"true","title":"Jenkins Pipeline, Jenkins 2.0 and Beyond","slug":"jenkins_pipeline_jenkins_20_and_"},{"intendedAudience":"People that are fed up with the BS of our industry!","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Hadi Hariri","bio":"Developer and creator of many things OSS, his passions includes Web Development and Software Architecture. Has authored a couple of books, a few courses and has been speaking at industry events for nearly 15 years. Currently at JetBrains leading the Developer Advocacy team. Spends as much time as he can writing code.","sessionId":"0a0eb45c75a24d54b7ba98fff04aa68b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"0a0eb45c75a24d54b7ba98fff04aa68b","abstract":"We love our silver bullets don’t we? Constantly chasing the dream that the next big thing will solve all our past problems. It doesn’t matter if it’s a language, framework, platform or library, we’re out there chasing it. Why? Well because it’s going to solve our needs, it’s going to solve the business needs. Well supposedly it will. And how much is it going to cost? Not that much, especially if we’re not the ones paying the bills. \n\nIt’s about time we look at the hard facts and ask those difficult questions. Are we really looking for a silver bullet?  Why are we constantly riding the technology bandwagon? Where is the churn going to take us? And at what cost?","published":"true","title":"The Silver Bullet Syndrome","slug":"the_silver_bullet_syndrome"},{"intendedAudience":"No code","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anne Landro","bio":"Anne Landro har jobbet med systemutvikling i mange år. Den siste tiden har hun hatt mest fokus på det funksjonelle aspektet av det å lage gode systemer. Hun liker godt å prøve forskjellige roller, og trives best når hun kan få en god forståelse av helheten og behovene bak et system.","sessionId":"dfb78ca736e04bd988900c41ad53536d"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"dfb78ca736e04bd988900c41ad53536d","abstract":"I det siste har brukersentrert design og UX blitt det hotteste hotte som er på alles lepper.  Men hvis vi bare gjør som kunden sier, glemmer vi at en viktig del av rollen vår som eksperter, er å stille spørsmål ved ønskene som strømmer på.\n\nI denne lyntalen ser vi på hvorfor det lønner seg å ikke gjøre som kunden sier. Vi ser på noen skrekk-eksempler hvor kunden fikk bestemme litt for mye, og tilfeller av det motsatte - hvor løsningen ble mye bedre av å ignorere brukernes ønsker.","published":"true","title":"Ikke gjør som kunden din sier!","slug":"ikke_gjr_som_kunden_din_sier"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som vil ha kode sikkert og raskt ut i produksjon. Live koding med eksempler i Java og Groovy.","keywords":["continuous integration","continuous deployment","testing"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Per Jørgen Walstrøm","bio":"Per Jørgen Walstrøm er Team Lead på FINN Reise. Han har  jobbet som utvikler siden dot.com-bølgen på slutten av 90-tallet og finner fortsatt motivasjon og indre glede i en test som lyser grønt.","sessionId":"481781e8292749cfae6b8689879262d2"},{"name":"Stig Kleppe-Jørgensen","bio":"Stig Kleppe-Jørgensen er Lead Developer på FINN Reise. Han har jobbet som utvikler fra midten av 90-åra og levd med for lav testdekning og tilhørende smerte, da det til slutt ble ny jobb og grønne bygg hos FINN. Han er stadig på utkikk etter nye bibliotek/verktøy som kan gjøre hverdagen lettere for utviklerne i teamet. Ikke minst for at veien for å få kode ut i produksjon blir så sikker og rask som mulig.","sessionId":"481781e8292749cfae6b8689879262d2"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"481781e8292749cfae6b8689879262d2","abstract":"Da FINN Reise lagde sin nye plattform i 2013, var det en forutsetning at kode skulle rulles ut kontinuerlig. For å få til dette, var vi avhengige av at ny kode som traff produksjon oppførte seg som den skulle og ikke klusset det til for allerede eksisterende funksjonalitet. \n\nDette er historien om hvordan Continous Integration og Continous Delivery er en naturlig del av en utviklers hverdag i FINN Reise.  Vi viser hvordan tester hjelper oss på vei, hvordan utviklernes rolle har forandret seg og tar et dykk inn i FINNs interne infrastruktur.","published":"true","title":"Hvordan FINN Reise ruller ut kode i produksjon 42 ganger om dagen","slug":"hvordan_finn_reise_ruller_ut_kod"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is aimed at programmers interested in advanced concurrency who want to develop algorithms with predictable response times at all levels of throughput which push our modern CPUs to the limit.","keywords":["java","concurrency","performance"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Martin Thompson","bio":"Martin is a Java Champion with over 2 decades of experience building complex and high-performance computing systems. He is most recently known for his work on Aeron and SBE. Previously at LMAX he was the co-founder and CTO when he created the Disruptor. Prior to LMAX Martin worked for Betfair, three different content companies wrestling with the world largest product catalogues, and was a lead on some of the most significant C++ and Java systems of the 1990s in the automotive and finance domains.\n\nHe blogs at mechanical-sympathy.blogspot.com, and can be found giving training courses on performance and concurrency when he is not cutting code to make systems better.","sessionId":"3c02e2942c1b4a579e05450b4e5e829d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"3c02e2942c1b4a579e05450b4e5e829d","abstract":"Concurrent programming with locks is hard. Concurrent programming without using locks can be really hard. Concurrent programming with relaxed memory ordering and predictable latency semantics is said to be only for wizards. This talk focuses on a decade long quest to discover algorithms and data structures that provide very high throughput while keeping latency low and predictable. Additionally, data structures need to provide real-time telemetry on how a system is performing via non-blocking operations.\n\nWe will cover some fundamental theory of concurrency and then compare various approaches to the same problem so that we can measure the impact on latency. We'll also show how some of these algorithm implementations get more interesting given the new features in Java 8.","published":"true","title":"A quest for predictable latency with Java concurrency","slug":"a_quest_for_predictable_latency_"},{"intendedAudience":"Anybody who needs to make a choice on a database","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Philipp Krenn","bio":"Philipp is a Developer Advocate at Elastic, spreading the love and knowledge of full-text search, analytics, and real-time data. He is a frequent speaker at conferences and meetups about all things search & analytics, databases, cloud computing, and devops. Philipp lives in Vienna where he enjoys experimenting with software, organizing meetups, and sports.","sessionId":"7b495f0cc2a344e29737f9e6832e7f4f"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"7b495f0cc2a344e29737f9e6832e7f4f","abstract":"In hardly any other area we’ve had as much change and improvement as in the field of databases. Just a few years ago everyone had “their” database that was used for each project. Today you are confronted with a variety of approaches and implementations.\n\nWe start off with a brief look at the theoretical background of distributed systems and databases in particular. After that, we discuss possible scenarios as well as the advantages and disadvantages of several databases:\n\n* Why SQL is in fashion (again). \n* Why MongoDB’s document structure fits object-oriented programming so well. \n* How you can capture visitor hits with Redis efficiently. \n* Why Cassandra is so scalable and fail-safe. \n* How full-text search works with Elasticsearch.\n\nThe right choice of database(s) hasn’t become easier through the wide range of possibilities, but all the more interesting!","published":"true","title":"Databases — the choice is yours","slug":"databases__the_choice_is_yours"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk will switch between presenting the functional aspects of the prototype as well as showing how the functionality materializes by showing code in slides and code in an IDE.","keywords":["semantic java","apache jena","codeanalysis"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Magnus Stuhr","bio":"I am senior developer working for Computas, and have been in the industry for five years. I have been involved in several projects, both for the industry and academia, and for the private and public sectors.\n\nI am passionate about Java, best-practices and testing of code, and semantic web technologies. My main focus has always been on how semantic web technologies can be incorporated with Java, where I have also conducted a bit of research, resulting in two journal publications.","sessionId":"e0e6713dc6ee435b9e4a3ea10aefa8e3"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"e0e6713dc6ee435b9e4a3ea10aefa8e3","abstract":"\"Hendelsesregistrering\" (Event Registration) is a prototype developed for the police in Norway, focusing on assisting crime investigations and analysis by being able to detect phenomena and patterns in crime. The aim is to give the police the information they need at the right time to make better decisions, support crime investigations, see connections between events, and identify phenomena and patterns in crime. \n\nThe prototype is based on semantic web technologies, and adopts the Apache Jena framework for semantic web programming with Java. This presentation will go through the functional aspect of the solution, with a closer look at how the Apache Jena framework for Java supports the entire back-end stack.","published":"true","title":"Disclosing patterns and phenomena in crime with semantic Java","slug":"disclosing_patterns_and_phenomen"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette foredraget er for alle de som er litt nysgjerrige på funksjonell programmering og om java8 er veien å gå fremover. Utviklere, prosjektledere, arkitekter, alle er velkomne. Det vil være kodeeksempler i både Java og Scala, men ikke veldig avanserte.","keywords":["functionalprogramming","experiencereports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Kaare Nilsen","bio":"En lidenskapelig programmerer med mer enn 15 års erfaring fra prosjekter i forskjellige bransjer hos både private og offentlige kunder.  Kaare er ikke redd for å heve stemmen og snakker ofte om tema relatert til programmering og open source på meetups og konferanser.","sessionId":"80aa41b568bc44928f3250bcd445efad"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"80aa41b568bc44928f3250bcd445efad","abstract":"Mange har forsøkt reisen fra javaland til Scalaland, noen har fått oppholdstilatelse mens andre fikk sin søknad avslått og måtte returnere til Javaland. Dette er en annen historie. Hvordan er det for en fastboende i Scalaland i mange år å returnere til javaland etter java8-regimet har åpnet for retur av funksjonelle programmerere?\n\nDette er et erfaringsforedrag om hvordan dette, nå et år senere, har gått. \nHvordan fungerer java til funksjonell programmering nå? \nHva er det beste med å komme tilbake, og hva er det verste?\nHar oppholdet i Scalaland endret hvordan jeg skriver Javakode?","published":"true","title":"En Scalaflyktning i Javaland","slug":"en_scalaflyktning_i_javaland"},{"intendedAudience":"You need a basic understanding of test automation and performance testing to make the most out of this session. The talk will be a combination of slides and live coding.","keywords":["gatling","performance","testing"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Bert Jan Schrijver","bio":"Bert Jan is a Software craftsman at JPoint in the Netherlands and Java User Group leader for NLJUG, the Dutch Java User Group. His focus is on Java, Continuous Delivery and DevOps. He loves to share his experience by speaking at conferences, writing for the Dutch Java magazine and helping out Devoxx4Kids with teaching kids how to code.","sessionId":"65cc5fa8a63f48fd869f24ebc9248a4b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"65cc5fa8a63f48fd869f24ebc9248a4b","abstract":"Performance testing is traditionally a task for specialists that takes place at the very end of the software delivery life cycle. But how does this fit in with a DevOps way of working, where continuous feedback is one of the key points? It doesn't. In a world where scalability and performance are just as important as delivering new features, you need to embed performance testing in your daily development workflow: it needs to become a natural part of development. And this is where Gatling comes in: an open source load testing framework based on Scala, Akka and Netty. In this session, you will learn how to use Gatling to incorporate performance testing in development and how to provide your team with continuous feedback on your application's performance.\nSubjects include an introduction to Gatling, automated recording and processing of performance tests with the Gatling Scala DSL and integration with Jenkins for automated execution, bench marking and reporting of load tests.","published":"true","title":"Continuous performance: load testing for developers with Gatling","slug":"continuous_performance_load_test"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som bruker en smarttelefon og ikke blir vippet av pinnen når de hører om bluetoothteknologi. Presentasjonen kan inneholde spor av kode.","keywords":["mobile","beacons","java"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Arne Jervell","bio":"Arne Jervell har vært CTO i Giant Leap Technologies i 5 år. Han gikk ut fra Datateknikk på NTNU i 2002, etter å ha spesialisert seg på grafikk og algoritmer. Han brenner for mobilutvikling, personvern, pizzabaking og alt som er kult.","sessionId":"8a60f3bc274842cfa1408f6d10c84f60"},{"name":"Kari Bergh Schjønsby","bio":"Kari kommer fra BEKK Consulting, og er nå et av de nyeste tilskuddene til Giant Leap. Hun var klassekamerat med Arne på NTNU, og har også mer enn 14 år i IT-bransjen. Kari kan gire seg opp over det meste som er gjennomtenkt, lekkert og går fort.","sessionId":"8a60f3bc274842cfa1408f6d10c84f60"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"8a60f3bc274842cfa1408f6d10c84f60","abstract":"I Giant Leap er vi i gang med to spennende beaconprosjekter. Det ene er et pilotprosjekt for en stor norsk matvarekjede, og i det andre bruker vi beacons til betaling.  Matvarekjeden vil bruke beacons for å gi kunder en bedre handleopplevelse. I det prosjektet er vi i ferd med å utvikle en app som skal gi kunder riktig tilbud til riktig tid. I utvikling av betalingsløsningen er vi helt nede på jernet. Bruk av beacons er nybrottsarbeid, og i kjølvannet det følger det er en rekke spennende utfordringer. I matvareprosjektet må vi ta stilling til en rekke motsetninger; vi må ta hensyn til personvern, og samtidig gi en personlig tilpasset kjøpsopplevelse. Vi vil gi god informasjon, uten å irritere kundene. \nI betalingsprosjektet er en av de største utfordringene hvordan vi utnytter IP6-protokoll maksimalt.\n\nI dette foredraget vil vi gjerne fortelle hva vi har lært om bruk av beacons, så langt; Mobil- og Javautvikling kan vi, men beacons er litt nytt for oss ennå. Vi vil fortelle om hvilke utfordringer vi har møtt på og hvordan vi har gått frem for å løse dem, både konseptuelt og teknisk, med vår beacons - mobil - Java- stack. \nVi har snublet litt underveis, men kom vi i mål? Kom, så skal du få høre.\n\n\nGiant Leap Technologies er Norges fremste kompetansemiljø innen mobil tjenesteutvikling. http://www.giantleap.no/","published":"true","title":"En suksesshistorie om Java, mobil og beacons (og litt om hva som gikk galt)","slug":"en_suksesshistorie_om_java_mobil"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for everyone who generate data, and has an interest in open data. There will be some RDF code in slides, but no knowledge of the W3C standards is needed. Although, some general knowledge of RDF is a bonus.","keywords":["semantic web","linked open data"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Veronika Heimsbakk","bio":"I work as a Java developer at Acando in Oslo. I recently ended my studies in the wonders of programming and problem solving at the University of Oslo, where I fell in love with the Semantic Web and logic. For the past year I've been working with semantic technologies in several in-house and external projects. I've been a part of the \"semantic revolution\" at Acando, by writing blog posts and throwing several talks on the subject.\n\nOther than worshiping Linked Open Data, I enjoy Turing machines, circuit electronics, brewing beer and hunting.","sessionId":"8d3d1a120858447b862b47d3d5dde52b"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"8d3d1a120858447b862b47d3d5dde52b","abstract":"On a web where huge amount of data is available at all time, everywhere, there is a growing need for data consistency and data integrity. When we talk about data, we talk about all things that we may say something about. By following some simple rules about naming things you may achieve consistency and integrity by providing context to your open data. In the Semantic Web we call this data 5-starred data. \n\nI will explain what 5-starred data is, why it is important, and how you may make your data 5-starred. We will dip into the Linked Open Data Cloud and look at how the data are structured using W3C standards and find out what makes data in the web, rather than just on the web.","published":"true","title":"Is your data 5-starred?","slug":"is_your_data_5starred"},{"intendedAudience":"Lyntalen er for alle utviklere som frontend.  Lyntalen tar for seg hvordan man kan behandle statisk data  i en single page application.  Det vil være kode-eksempler i slides. Krever ingen forkunnskaper om React eller relativitetsteorien.","keywords":["react","frontend"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Emil Staurset","bio":"Emil har jobbet som utvikler i BEKK siden 2015. Har en mastergrad i datateknikk fra NTNU, og han er mer enn gjennomsnittlig interessert i funksjonell programmering og statisk data","sessionId":"217f33647bc54acbb4660b7e71c387d8"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"217f33647bc54acbb4660b7e71c387d8","abstract":"I denne lyntalen skal vi se på hvordan vi brukte fossefall, parallelitet og relativitet til å håndtere statiske data i vår applikasjon. I tillegg skal vi forsøke å besvare de store spørsmålene her i livet: Kan statisk data aldri endre seg? Hvor skal den statiske dataen leve?","published":"true","title":"Hva er egentlig statisk data?","slug":"hva_er_egentlig_statisk_data"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklarar. Prosjektledarar. Arkitektar. IT-ledarar. Null kode.","keywords":["devops","continuousdelivery"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sveinung Dalatun","bio":"Aktiv i Kodesmia i javaBin. Fagledar for Kontinuerlige leveransar og DevOps i BEKK.","sessionId":"49687cf3e9e64b0e94da7a08cfbbd772"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"49687cf3e9e64b0e94da7a08cfbbd772","abstract":"... for til og med me i smidige vesle javaBin sliter.\n\nSidan DevOps byrja å bli hot for ein 4-5 år sidan har bransjen sett ein bråte med DevOps-initiativ rundt omkring, men meir enn ein gong har ein starta forbetringane i feil ende. Når du høyrer på folk prata om DevOps og Kontinuerlige leveransar får du fort inntrykk av at alt har ei teknisk løysning. I så fall har du bomma ... kraftig. Gløym teknologien. Start med det mjuke.\n\nKom og høyr ein desillusjonert utviklar prata om kva Kodesmia i javaBin har til felles med store offentlige IT-prosjekt, korleis me automatiserte alt og samstundes gjorde alle redde for å ta på ting og kvifor eg endte opp som ein seig driftar.","published":"true","title":"DevOps e' grisevanskelig","slug":"devops_e_grisevanskelig"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers that want to level up from TDD and static code analysis","keywords":["mutation testing","unit testing","code quality"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Filip van Laenen","bio":"Filip van Laenen is a Chief Architect at the Norwegian software company Computas AS, which supplies IT solutions to the public and the private sector in Norway. He has almost twenty years of experience in the software industry, from being a developer in both small and large teams to being the lead developer and competency leader for security and software engineering for the whole company. During the last years, he has spent some time using mutation testing, which has given him a number of aha! moments he would like to share with other developers.","sessionId":"4b9d6012a28d44c2becd3fb436eae369"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"4b9d6012a28d44c2becd3fb436eae369","abstract":"Mutation testing is the true test for whether or not your source code does the right thing, and whether it's properly tested by your unit tests. But while we're on a killing spree against the mutants of our source code, let's reflect a bit on what these mutants really represent, and why we want to include the unit tests that kill them in our test suite.\n\nWhat's the real point of boundary testing? Do we really need every statement in the source code? Have we tested all calculations? How do we know that we got all the access modifiers on our methods right? These are some of the questions that we would like to reflect on for a moment.\n\nWe'll start this talk with a short introduction to mutation testing, but only to set the stage. The core of this talk consists of a walk-through of Java code and unit tests, and a reflection on TDD and the quality of our unit tests. At the end of this talk you should be more suspicious about both your source code and your unit tests.","published":"true","title":"Dial M for Mutation","slug":"dial_m_for_mutation"},{"intendedAudience":"No experience with machine learning needed.","keywords":["machine learning"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anders Breivik","bio":"Anders is a fallen mathematician with over 10 years of experience from his backup plan as a software developer. As a consultant with the Nordic consultancy Knowit, Anders enjoys working with both large critical enterprise systems and small scale mobile solutions. Currently Anders is passionate about IoT, iBeacons and mini drones.","sessionId":"ebd7f5fd6f184f9498c4d8f2db4069ec"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"ebd7f5fd6f184f9498c4d8f2db4069ec","abstract":"What is Machine Learning as a Service? Which do I choose? How can I use it in my application?\n\nMachine learning has long been a somewhat academic discipline, its practitioners highly specialized. But with the advent of a new class of commoditized machine learning platforms, MLaaS, Machine Learning as a Service, is now available to all developers.\n\nMLaaS can be treated as a black box, giving developers the opportunity to dive into machine learning head first. Supply your own data, build a model using tools supported by your chosen MLaaS platform and train it using the well tested algorithms offered. When ready to dig deeper into the world of machine learning, most MLaaS platforms enables us to develop our own algorithms even better tailored to our data and models.\n\nThis talk will show you the state of the art of MLaaS, what the different vendors offer, and where you best can put it to use in your applications.","published":"true","title":"MLaaS - Machine Learning for the rest of us","slug":"mlaas__machine_learning_for_the_"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is suitable for everyone with reasonable experience in software development. Since this session is more about people and process than about code, there'll be (almost) no code in this talk.","keywords":["devops"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Bert Jan Schrijver","bio":"Bert Jan is a Software craftsman at JPoint in the Netherlands and Java User Group leader for NLJUG, the Dutch Java User Group. His focus is on Java, Continuous Delivery and DevOps. He loves to share his experience by speaking at conferences, writing for the Dutch Java magazine and helping out Devoxx4Kids with teaching kids how to code.","sessionId":"a764f8905e39414dbde2d1fb27a8c500"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"a764f8905e39414dbde2d1fb27a8c500","abstract":"DevOps is the new black. You need DevOps. Right now.   \nWhat? You're not doing DevOps yet? Hurry! You're going to miss the boat!  \n\nSounds familiar? The same thing happened with Agile a while ago. Coined as a solution for all your problems, companies rushed to implement this 'next big thing', only to realize a few years later that they got most of it wrong by failing to understand the concepts behind it well enough in the first place.  \n\nDon't make the same mistake again. Getting DevOps right isn't easy. It's downright hard. In this talk, I'm not going to explain how to 'do' DevOps in your organisation, since there is not just one 'right' way to do it. What I can show you however, is how NOT to do DevOps.  \nThis session shares 15 common misconceptions, call them anti-patterns, of DevOps. I'll talk from my own experiences in getting things wrong, explain why they are wrong and prevent you from making the same mistakes. You'll leave this session with a basic understanding of how (not) to fail at DevOps and hopefully, a smile on your face ;-)","published":"true","title":"The DevOps disaster: 15 ways to fail at DevOps","slug":"the_devops_disaster_15_ways_to_f"},{"intendedAudience":"Some code is shown for both android phone(java/xml) and server(golang). The talk is intended for people who are aware of or should be aware of the possible security flaw of bluetooth enabled wearables.","keywords":["wearables","privacy","mobile"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nils Larsgård","bio":"Senior developer with experience from backend, frontend and app development. Love to learn new stuff and have tons of side-projects. Currently working as a consultant for my own company, bytecode.no .","sessionId":"ef377f3136fb4a9398c44458b0076c1a"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"ef377f3136fb4a9398c44458b0076c1a","abstract":"You want push messages every time your neighbour comes home? How about location of every time your neighbour is in the nearabouts of a phone with your app on it?  All kinds of wearable devices are enabled with bluetooth and emits signals that everyone can read. Listening for these signals with a simple smartphone and logging it to a server makes a possible illegal but very effective surveillance system network.  This talk is a demonstration of how easy it is to build a full fledged surveillance system with just an app and a server.","published":"true","title":"Tracking location of your neighbours wearable with Android","slug":"tracking_location_of_your_neighb"},{"intendedAudience":"Primarily intended for the seasoned developer who want to write secure code, but who also has realised that the day-to-day development work does not leave room for thinking “security” all the time. You probably carry roles as system architect or lead developer, or have informal roles as goto-guy/gal.\nThere will be code in slides and the discussion will be about principles for how to write code.","keywords":["application security","domain-driven design","coding principles"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Dan Bergh Johnsson","bio":"Agile aficionado; Domain Driven Design enthusiast; code quality craftsman, with a long time interest in security. The combination made Dan use quality practices from DDD to address application security issues - thus coining \"Domain Driven Security\" together with John Wilander around 2009. Has spoken on similar topics at numerous renown conferences including JavaZone, Devoxx, Jfokus, QCon etc","sessionId":"26188ac268804a8c85c2fad6ae1afcef"},{"name":"Daniel Deogun","bio":"Coder and Quality defender; brings order to a chaotic world of bits and bytes through good design and clean code; fights security trolls on a daily basis using magic spells from DDD and an overall security mindset. Daniel's extensive experience ranges from patient critical pacemaker systems to web applications to high performant software in the gaming industry. Combining this with his passion for agile and tech has made him a frequent speaker at international conferences.","sessionId":"26188ac268804a8c85c2fad6ae1afcef"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"26188ac268804a8c85c2fad6ae1afcef","abstract":"We all know we have Anonymous, LulzSec, and NSA around. With this in mind, isn’t it time to think about the security of our systems? Well, of course. In this talk, we’ll show how Domain Driven Design is used to counteract security weaknesses without one thinking “security” all the time. So, if you’re interested in learning how to design secure software, then this session is for you.\nBusiness and technical attacks are two kinds of attacks, where the latter is most famous, e g SQL Injection & XSS. But it doesn’t mean business attacks are less harmful. On the contrary, they tend to be extremely sophisticated and powerful as they often leave infrastructure intact without firing alarms. Domain Driven Security is the field that counteracts both categories by using tools and mindsets from DDD.","published":"true","title":"Your Business is under Attack; Arm yourself with Domain Driven Security","slug":"your_business_is_under_attack_ar"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som er nysgjerrige på hvordan man kan bruke mikrotjenester også til frontend.","keywords":["microservices","node.js","esi"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sindre Ilebekk Johansen","bio":"Utvikler og Devopser som er nysgjerrig av natur.","sessionId":"15144d4045334f41ae34be5c998a5520"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"15144d4045334f41ae34be5c998a5520","abstract":"Amedia har i vår skrevet om hele arkitekturen for å rendre forsiden for nettavisene fra å være en Java-Monolitt til en mikrotjenestearkitektur med små node.js-applikasjoner som kjører i docker.\n\nJeg vil gå igjennom hvorfor vi gjorde dette, hvilke valg vi gjorde, og hvordan dette har gitt en mer robust arkitektur, en bedre hverdag for utviklerne og avisene mer spillerom til hvordan de vil ha sin egen forside.","published":"true","title":"Bruk av node og esi i en mikrotjenestearkitektur for å rendre forsiden til halvparten av norske lokalaviser","slug":"bruk_av_node_og_esi_i_en_mikrotj"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som ønsker å utvikle noe utenom sin \"day job\". No code.","keywords":["metodikk","apps","hobbyprosjekt"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Christian Aamodt","bio":"Christian er en erfaren utvikler, og har jobbet som konsulent med javabaserte webprosjekter siden 1998. Han har utviklet apper siden 2010, blant annet den prisbelønte appen \"Kubbe lager skyggeteater\" fra 2013 og appen \"Oslo i gamle dager\". Christian jobber nå som konsulent for Bouvet Norge.","sessionId":"633d76d5e15e45b9b8d8cfd0e5c6c68d"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"633d76d5e15e45b9b8d8cfd0e5c6c68d","abstract":"Har du fått en ide til noe du vil lage? Et produkt du har lyst til å utvikle, men ikke nok til at du vil si opp jobben eller sette igang en startup? Christian utviklet på fritiden gjennom flere år appen \"Oslo i gamle dager\", som blant annet ble omtalt i Aftenposten (http://www.osloby.no/nyheter/Her-er-appen-som-tar-deg-tilbake-til-det-gamle-Oslo-8169441.html). Appen er  en ios-app som benytter en javabasert server i Googles cloud. Basert på sine erfaringer fra denne prosessen, vil han motivere til hobbyprosjekter og gi nyttige råd og tips til hvordan slike prosjekter kan gjennomføres.","published":"true","title":"Not ready to quit your day job? Hvordan lykkes med hobbyprosjekter?","slug":"not_ready_to_quit_your_day_job_h"},{"intendedAudience":"The talk is intended for intermediate or advanced developers familiar with either Java or Scala. The audience is expected to previously have seen basic functional constructs, such as lambdas. We will present working code examples in Java and Scala. We will perform little live coding, but use IntelliJ as our presentation medium and primarily show code on screen. I.e. “Code in slides”.","keywords":["scala","functionalprogramming","reactive"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lars Albertsson","bio":"Lars Albertsson has worked with data-intensive and scalable applications throughout his corporate career - at Google, natural language processing startup Recorded Future, and with stock exchange systems. He rolled out the current data processing infrastructure at Spotify, and moved on to be architect for data processing infrastructure and user modelling for the new central technology organisation at Schibsted Media Group. He is now an independent consultant, helping companies build scalable data processing solutions.","sessionId":"3485e67c10bd4972a031d70e400a6743"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"3485e67c10bd4972a031d70e400a6743","abstract":"Functional programming constructs have risen in popularity in recent years, driven by the Big Data hype.  The object-oriented paradigm is likely to remain dominant, but there is opportunity to enrich our toolboxes by picking up some instruments from the functional world. We will present a set of functional constructs applicable for asynchronous programming, error handling, and data processing. We will skip past basic and now well-known functional constructs, such as lambdas, streams, map, and reduce, and focus on techniques that are not yet part of most object-oriented programmers’ toolboxes: reactive patterns, currying, disjunctions, lenses, and more. The constructs presented will be applicable in familiar, object-oriented contexts, and not require a functional mindset.","published":"true","title":"Functional patterns for object-oriented minds","slug":"functional_patterns_for_objector"},{"intendedAudience":"De fleste som er involvert i en systemutviklingsprosess kan ha nytte av denne lyntalen. Spesielt utviklere, arkitekter, testere og prosjektledere eller produkteiere. De fleste vil kjenne igjen problemstillingene vi ser på, og få en aha-opplevelse om hva slags avhengigheter og bindinger som kan spille inn i en systemutviklingsprosess og hvilken konsekvens de kan ha. Lite kode i slidene.","keywords":["architecture","continuousdelivery","testing"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Torstein Gjengedal","bio":"Torstein har jobbet i 15 år med utvikling, arkitektur og rådgivning. Han er vant til sammensatte systemporteføljer, har erfaring med både tekniske perspektiver, kvalitetssikring og leveranseprosesser og søker alltid etter enkle løsninger.","sessionId":"39d18326ded84e02aa8dea7a34fe3e9b"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"39d18326ded84e02aa8dea7a34fe3e9b","abstract":"Ved utvikling av IT-systemer oppstår mange typer avhengigheter og bindinger. De kan vise seg på ulike nivåer og i ulike faser i løpet av en utviklingsprosess, men  har til felles at de medfører kostnader. Og noen koster mer enn andre.\n\nHvilke avhengigheter har vi, hva koster de, og kan de unngås? Og hvilke bryr vi oss egentlig mest om? La oss gå igjennom noen typiske avhengigheter både av teknisk, testmessig og leveransemessig art og se litt nærmere på hva de medfører!","published":"true","title":"Avhengighetens pris","slug":"avhengighetens_pris"},{"intendedAudience":"For de som tror de driver med DevOps, synes DevOps høres kult ut, eller bare har lyst på en kjapp innføring i DevOps. Ingen kode!","keywords":["devops","rant"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"David Kai Christen Kristensen","bio":"Til daglig jobber David som systemkonsulent i Mesan AS hvor han også er leder for faggruppen for Cloud & DevOps. Han er lidenskapelig opptatt av distribuerte systemer, fra skytjenester til mesh-nettverk. Han hater idiotiske administrative hindringer i utviklingsprosessen, og er ikke redd for å fortelle deg hvor han mener skapet burde stå!","sessionId":"8f27169519f749b4a5277ff0d9cc728a"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"8f27169519f749b4a5277ff0d9cc728a","abstract":"Du driver ikke med DevOps selv om du har en byggserver som bygger på push til master! Du driver ikke med DevOps selv om du har tatt i bruk PaaS tjenester i skyen! Du driver ikke med DevOps selv om du deployer Docker containere med Mesos! Du driver ikke med DevOps før du har tatt inn over deg hva DevOps faktisk er. Så la meg forklare deg DevOps!","published":"true","title":"Du tror du driver med DevOps du..","slug":"du_tror_du_driver_med_devops_du"},{"intendedAudience":"Anyone interested in continuous learning and improvement. Anyone who believes developers should take responsibility for how their code behaves in production.","keywords":["experience reports"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Andreas Jacobsen","bio":"Andreas Jacobsen is tech lead for Web Solutions at Posten. He enjoys programming and self-referential jokes. He does not enjoy writing about himself in the third person.","sessionId":"93d6e7b57d9f4758b2c3f8957e6bd220"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"en","sessionId":"93d6e7b57d9f4758b2c3f8957e6bd220","abstract":"All systems fail. In the aftermath it can be easy to point fingers and assign blame, but this can obscure important lessons and opportunities to learn. In this talk, I'll explain what a blameless post mortem is and share some experience about how our team applies them to learn from downtime and bugs. I'll also cover why it's an important activity for both developers and operators.\n\nAfter this talk you will have the tools to immediately get started with blameless post mortems and a list of resources gaining a deeper understanding of how and why they work.","published":"true","title":"The road to nines is paved with war stories","slug":"the_road_to_nines_is_paved_with_"},{"intendedAudience":"Er en ny måte å gjøre innlogging på interessant eller synes det er gøy med nye teknologier er dette noe for deg. Passer for alle og det blir ingen kode.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Liv Kolås","bio":"Liv Kolås jobber som konsulent(i EVRY) og utvikler fordi hun liker å lage ting og kunne se resultatet av det hun gjør på slutten av dagen. I tillegg setter hun pris på en utfordring og det å tenke ut gode løsninger. På fritiden driver Liv med håndarbeid (mye strikking). I tillegg er hun interessert i sikkerhet og prøver og holde seg litt oppdatert på dette området.","sessionId":"d2c5fbb67b114162aeeeb053142b4e77"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"d2c5fbb67b114162aeeeb053142b4e77","abstract":"Brukernavn og passord er en ut datert og usikker måte å gjøre logg-inn på. Vi bør begynne å se på alternativer som er sikrere og kanskje enklere. \n\nEt av alternativene er SQRL det eliminerer mange problemer som finnes ved tradisjonell innlogging. \nJeg snakket om det samme i fjor, men nå er det endelig ferdig spesifisert og det burde være mulig å se hvordan det kan gjøres.","published":"true","title":"Så enkelt kan innlogging være","slug":"s_enkelt_kan_innlogging_vre"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere med kjennskap til Javascript. Alle som vurderer å lage eller få utviklet en løsning med offline støtte.","keywords":["javascript","frontend"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Anders Skar","bio":"Anders har mange års erfaring med utvikling av komplekse web- og native applikasjoner, deriblant forretningskritiske applikasjoner med krav offline lagring. Alltid nysgjerrig på å teste ut det siste innen teknologi og dingser.","sessionId":"0c0605d3ea8a49d8a6f5bae1bbb36ba7"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"0c0605d3ea8a49d8a6f5bae1bbb36ba7","abstract":"For å støtte offline datahåndtering med bakgrunnssynkronisering måtte man før utvikle native-applikasjoner. Nå har dette blitt mulig i nettleseren!\n\nI denne lyntalen vil vi se nærmere på teknologier som blant annet LocalStorage, IndexedDB, NetworkInformation og Service Workers background sync API som gjør det mulig å lagre data offline som synkroniseres automatisk når brukeren er på nett selv om brukeren har lukket nettsiden. Og dette er mulig helt uten å bruke en spesialtilpasset nettleser eller andre rammeverk som Cordova.\n\nBasert på praktisk erfaringer vil du få en oversikt over hvilke muligheter og begrensninger som finnes per i dag.","published":"true","title":"Offline webapps med bakgrunnsynkronisering","slug":"offline_webapps_med_bakgrunnsynk"},{"intendedAudience":"Ingen forkunnskap om maskinlæring er nødvendig. Kode vil bli vist i slidene.","keywords":["machinelearning","cloud"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Simen Skogen","bio":"Simen er utdannet sivilingeniør i datateknikk fra NTNU, med en fordypning innen kunstig intelligens og maskinlæring. Han har jobbet i 2 år hos Capgemini, og jobber for tiden med både backend og frontend til utvikling av nettbank. Simen har en spesiell interesse for 'smarte' algoritmer, visualisering og fine brukergrensesnitt.","sessionId":"12c577faa8e14cb0bf3a1df770bd2dc6"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"12c577faa8e14cb0bf3a1df770bd2dc6","abstract":"Maskinlæring er godt på vei fra hype til mainstream og kommersialiseres allerede gjennom tjenester fra Azure, Amazon og Google. Det som før måtte programmeres med biblioteker og krevde domenekunnskap, kan nå settes sammen som legoklosser med svært få, eller ingen linjer med kode.\n\nFå en intro til maskinlæring og hva sky-tjenestene for maskinlæring har å tilby. Kodeekspempler vil vise hvordan du kan bruke disse tjenestene eller skape et eget API basert på åpne biblioteker.","published":"true","title":"Kom i gang med maskinlæring i skyen!","slug":"kom_i_gang_med_maskinlring_i_sky"},{"intendedAudience":"Participants will learn:\n\n* how to quickly and effectively build edge services\n* how to integrate edge services with existing services\n* how to optimize for mobile devices\n* how to leverage edge services securely\n\nKnowledge of microservices and/or Java is helpful, but not required.\n\n(Live coding)","keywords":["microservices","edge services","api gateway"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mark Heckler","bio":"Mark Heckler is a Pivotal Principal Technologist & Developer Advocate, conference speaker, and published author focusing upon software development for the Internet of Things and the Cloud. He has worked with key players in the manufacturing, retail, medical, scientific, telecom, and financial industries and various public sector organizations to develop and deliver critical capabilities on time and on budget. Mark is an open source contributor and author/curator of a developer-focused blog (http://www.thehecklers.org) and an occasionally interesting Twitter account (@MkHeck).\n\nMark lives with his very understanding wife in St. Louis, MO USA.","sessionId":"d03a1f1a43934b0ab198b6cbfb4d0f9d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"d03a1f1a43934b0ab198b6cbfb4d0f9d","abstract":"Devices (phones, tablets, etc.) already consume most services/data, but they have to get those services somewhere! In this session, learn how to use proven patterns & open source software to quickly and effectively build edge services - API gateways - that marshal & streamline communication between your key services and end-users with devices in hand. This session addresses vital points such as:\n\n* Leveraging OAuth2 for service security\n* Configuration services\n* Microservice registration and discovery\n* Circuit breakers for graceful degradation\n\nAdditional topics discussed include logging & tracing, testing approaches, and migration patterns.\n\nThe presenter will demonstrate how to develop & manage microservices & expose them via an edge service, securely, using OSS tools employed by Netflix to keep movies streaming globally 24x7.","published":"true","title":"Living on the Edge (Service): Bundling Microservices to Optimize for Devices","slug":"living_on_the_edge_service_bundl"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers, testers and anyone else working on solutions that users are interacting with. \n\nThere will be plenty of code in slides, but the talk should be possible to follow for anyone. We will start off on a basic level, and we will work our way up to a more advanced level together.","keywords":["universal design","frontend"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Vegard Haugstvedt","bio":"Vegard is a color-blind, full-stack developer (alternating between Java and frontend-code) and has been trained in Universal Design. He worked on one of the first major projects going live after the law of Universal Design went into effect, and draws a lot of experience from that. \n\nThere are few better ways of getting him riled up than arguing that Universal Design is not neccessary, and he dreams about the day Universal Design is as much of a given as writing unit tests.","sessionId":"ed9f3fa9d4a74e019f8128cfd8f6e229"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"ed9f3fa9d4a74e019f8128cfd8f6e229","abstract":"Since July 1st 2014, all IT solutions in Norway are bound by law to follow the requirements of WCAG 2.0 including level AA. A lot of people seem to think this is so that blind people can use websites. They are not wrong, but still it is so much more. Implemented correctly, a universally designed solution will benefit all of us, and the target groups include many others, like older-, drunk- and sunbathing users. \n\nIn this talk I will give some insights into what kind of users to think about when designing, implementing and testing IT solutions, as well as what you should think about with regards to the different user groups.\n\nI will also present tips and methods on how to implement a solution conforming to the WCAG 2.0 AA requirements and alert you to some of the normal pitfalls. We will be looking at plenty of code examples, showing both good and bad implementations.\n\nAfter listening to this talk, you will have a much better understanding of why and how to implement a universal design, and hopefully be motivated to go back to work and convince your coworkers to get on bord too!","published":"true","title":"Implement universally designed solutions or your drunk grandma will suffer for it!","slug":"implement_universally_designed_s"},{"intendedAudience":"Live coding. Well, we'll browse through the code rather than write it on the spot. But there are pre-created code snippets we'll use.","keywords":["jvm","programminglanguages"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Oleg Šelajev","bio":"Oleg Šelajev is an engineer, author, speaker, lecturer and advocate at ZeroTurnaround. He spends his time testing, coding, writing, giving conference talks, crafting blogposts and reports. He is pursuing a PhD on Dynamic System updates and code evolution. Oleg is a part-time lecturer at the University of Tartu and enjoys speaking and participating in Java/JVM development conferences such as JavaOne, JavaZone, JFokus and others.","sessionId":"3f81b31c7b584d33bf8b5ed3c13120c2"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"3f81b31c7b584d33bf8b5ed3c13120c2","abstract":"In this session we'll create a new programming language! We'll construct its grammar, semantics, operations and the interpreter for the language. Additionally, we'll learn about parsers and how to perform simple optimizations, both at compile time and otherwise. Most importantly we'll tackle the interoperability problem with the underlying platform, which in our case is the JVM.\n\nThis session will briefly discuss type systems, optimizations, memory management and concurrency issues that programming languages all encounter. Have you ever wanted to create a programming language of your own? After this session you will have seen all the tools you need to do so and will understand more about how are programming languages work including the challenges you’ll face.","published":"true","title":"How to Create a New JVM Language in Under an Hour","slug":"how_to_create_a_new_jvm_language"},{"intendedAudience":"This talk is for people interested in the details of the HotSpot Virtual Machine implementation. The audience should have a general understanding of VM technology or at least be interested in learning about it. We will do some \"Live coding\" during this session up to the native level.","keywords":["hotspot","internals","intrinsics"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Volker Simonis","bio":"Volker Simonis works for SAP in the SAP JVM Technology group. He is an OpenJDK contributor from the very beginning and helped SAP and the SAP JVM team engage in the OpenJDK project. He's the project lead of the OpenJDK PowerPC/AIX porting project, a JDK9 reviewer and a JCP Executive Committee representative for SAP.","sessionId":"bfab430bf9744553a6bb8a15f1a781d8"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"bfab430bf9744553a6bb8a15f1a781d8","abstract":"By definition, intrinsics are functions which are handled specially by the compiler or the VM. The HotSpot virtual machine supports intrinsics for specific API functions in the interpreter as well as in the C1 and C2 JIT compilers. In general, intrinsics are a great possibility for optimization. But they also come at a certain cost. First of all, they are inherently platform and implementation dependent. If available, they can lead to consistency problems if they are implemented differently in the interpreter and the JIT compilers. Finally, they can change the program control (e.g. safepoint behavior) and observability (e.g. profiling, instrumentation) in subtle ways.\n\nThis talk will give you a short deep dive into the HotSpot Virtual Machine using the example of HotSpot intrinsics. It will explain how they are implemented and the implications this has for the Java VM. Finally, it will demonstrate how you can add a new intrinsic for your favourite Java method.","published":"true","title":"HotSpot Intrinsics","slug":"hotspot_intrinsics"},{"intendedAudience":"Utviklere som er nysgjerrig på hvordan parallelle streams faktisk fungerer.\n\n\"Code in slides\"","keywords":["java core","streams"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Henrik Wingerei","bio":"Henrik Wingerei jobber som seniorkonsulent i BEKK hvor han har jobbet som fullstack utvikler i 4 år. Henrik er interessert i teknologi, alternative språk og paradigmer, og alt som rører seg rundt en applikasjon. Henrik har tidligere holdt foredrag på både JavaZone og meetups.","sessionId":"2236362c8ae64f39bce3067447918896"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"2236362c8ae64f39bce3067447918896","abstract":"Java 8 kom med et nytt og spennende streams API, som gir oss Java-utviklere helt nye muligheter for prosessering av data. I tillegg kan man enkelt velge om operasjoner på en stream skal utføres sekvensielt eller i parallell.\n\nDet å kjøre stream-operasjoner i parallell kan ved første øyekast virke enkelt og ufarlig, men er det egentlig så lurt? Vi gjør et kort dypdykk i hvordan parallelle streams faktisk fungerer, når man bør bruke de, og ikke minst om man bør bruke de i det hele tatt.","published":"true","title":"(Når) bør man bruke parallelle streams?","slug":"nr_br_man_bruke_parallelle_strea"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers interested in functional programming\n\nCode demo and in slides","keywords":["functionalprogramming","api","javase"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Erlend Hamnaberg","bio":"Erlend is a consultant working for Arktekk. He is very interested in function programming and spends quite a bit of his free time developing more or less useful libraries. He is a former chairman of javaBin and has been active in the community for a long time. The main language of choice is Scala, but since a lot of clients still use Java, we need to build useful libraries there as well.","sessionId":"2ba516c213b24a428da83667cc213639"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"2ba516c213b24a428da83667cc213639","abstract":"The arrival of Java 8 has made it possible to make better APIs.\nI have made a new JSON library for Java 8, which encodes the RFC\nusing functional programming style.\n\nIn this talk I will walk you through how I did this, using \nconcepts as Algebraic Data Types (ADTs) and other useful functional\nprogramming patterns like Isomorphisms and Functor and CoFunctors.\n\nI will describe a way of using fold as the basic building block for \nexpressing your api, and as the most powerful tool in the ADT.\n\nLastly I will explain how we can use these techniques to \ndo decoding and encoding of JSON without using reflection in Java 8.","published":"true","title":"Functional JSON in Java 8","slug":"functional_json_in_java_8"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle!","keywords":["lær kidsa koding!"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Line Moseng","bio":"Line ble ferdig med mastergrad i informatikk ved Universitetet i Oslo i 2015. Nå jobber hun som utvikler i Ciber. Hun har engasjert seg i Lær Kidsa Koding siden 2013 med ønske om at at barna som nå vokser opp skal få mulighet til å være skapere og ikke bare forbrukere av digital teknologi.","sessionId":"e96580556e35482b9388e5b0ed2fbc65"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"e96580556e35482b9388e5b0ed2fbc65","abstract":"Vi har fått over 76 kodeklubber i Norge, og nesten 50.000 barn var med på kodetimen i 2015. Imidlertid er det lenge til vi har nådd målet om ha undervisning i informatikk i skolen. Jeg vil gi deg litt ammunisjon du kan bruke overfor skolen og skole-eiere, og håper jeg kan gi deg noen råd dersom du vil sette i gang med kodeklubb eller hjelpe den lokale skolen. Om vi lærer kidsa koding sikrer vi Norge i fremtiden!","published":"true","title":"Lær Kidsa Koding! slik kan du bidra","slug":"lr_kidsa_koding_slik_kan_du_bidr"},{"intendedAudience":"This presentation is relevant for any Java developer that has ever worked with JPA and Hibernate. That being said, it's best to have some prior knowledge of JPA and/or JDBC.\n\nThis presentation aims to offer a different perspective to JPA and Hibernate because it's focused on high-performance features.\n\nNo code","keywords":["hibernate","high-performance"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Vlad Mihalcea","bio":"I work as a Developer Advocate for the Hibernate project. I answered more than 1000 Hibernate questions on StackOverflow and wrote over 70 articles about Hibernate.\n\nI'm currently writing a book entitled​ High-Performance Java Persistence ( https://leanpub.com/high-performance-java-persistence ).","sessionId":"a4cdc066845f4907a01cc2ac26fe9b22"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"a4cdc066845f4907a01cc2ac26fe9b22","abstract":"Hibernate is the most popular JPA provider and knowing its inner-workings can make the difference between a high-performance enterprise application and one that barely crawls.  \n\nThis presentation goes through the most common performance bottlenecks issues like exotic mappings, too much flushing, inappropriate queries, JDBC batch updates misuse, and suboptimal result set fetching.\n\nAside from common anti-patterns, I will also present some very useful Hibernate features like the enhanced identifier generators, locking-likelihood reduction, caching strategies and bytecode enhancements.","published":"true","title":"High-Performance Hibernate","slug":"highperformance_hibernate"},{"intendedAudience":"Intermediate Java level knowledge necessary, there will be code in slides and live coding.","keywords":["modularity","javase","architecture"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Paul Bakker","bio":"Paul is working as a software architect for Luminis Technologies, where he's currently leading the team that develops the CloudRTI; a Kubernetes/Docker based service that takes care of DevOps tasks like blue/green deployment, failover, centralised logging and monitoring. He is the author of “Building Modular Cloud Apps With OSGi” published by O'Reilly and an advocate for modularity in software. He is currently writing his second book for O'Reilly \"Java 9 Modularity\" which is expected early 2017.\n\nHe's also deeply involved in Amdatu, an open source library for highly modular OSGi components, and several other open source projects. He's a regular speaker on conferences speaking both about modularity/OSGi related topics, and topics related to Kubernetes and cloud architecture in general.","sessionId":"ed2dcf60ebb844c89901e38a30204a8b"},{"name":"Sander Mak","bio":"Sander crafts scalable software at Luminis Technologies. With almost a decade of experience on the JVM platform, he specializes in modular Java and JavaScript development. Additionally, data analysis and machine learning are part of his ever growing list of interests. Sander loves sharing knowledge, for example through his blog at http://branchandbound.net. He is currently writing 'Java 9 Modularity' for O'Reilly, expected release early 2017. Furthermore he speaks regularly at international developer conferences, sharing his passion for Java, alternative JVM languages and related technologies.","sessionId":"ed2dcf60ebb844c89901e38a30204a8b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"ed2dcf60ebb844c89901e38a30204a8b","abstract":"With Java 9, modularity comes to your doorstep (whether you ordered it or not). This isn't your average language feature: making the most out of it may involve rewiring your brain. In this session we explore the benefits of a modular codebase using Java 9 modules. Because who doesn’t like more reliable and secure applications, meanwhile killing the dreaded classpath?\n\nAfter reviewing the basic concepts of modules, we'll explore modularity patterns that enhance your design and development skills. We all have existing software, so migration of codebases to a modular world is an important topic as well. Automatic modules, the 'unnamed' module and other new concepts are added to your toolbox to this end.\n\nWant examples? We've got plenty in this practical and code-driven talk. Even if you intend to use Java 9 without modules, this talk helps you prevent common issues. You'll be ready for Java 9 before you know it.  \n\nBoth speakers are currently writing “Java 9 Modularity” for O’Reilly, expected early 2017. They have extensive experience under the belt already with the Java 9 Jigsaw early access builds.","published":"true","title":"Java 9 Modularity in Action","slug":"java_9_modularity_in_action"},{"intendedAudience":"For Java-utvikleren som er interessert i å høre om et nytt programmeringsspråk. Det vil være kodeeksempler i presentasjonen.","keywords":["programming languages","concepts / theory"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Erlend Åmdal","bio":"Erlend Åmdal er en master-student på Datateknologilinjen på NTNU. Til tross for begrenset akademisk bakgrunn har han bygd opp mye erfaring innenfor diverse software-utvikling og en brennende lidenskap for programmering. Jack of all trades, med fokus på både klient- og serversiden på web, Java-miljøet og Minecraft-modding.","sessionId":"51b7a940fa684d9a9ac270849feb66a2"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"51b7a940fa684d9a9ac270849feb66a2","abstract":"En introduksjon til Kotlin, et Java-aktig programmeringsspråk som kjører på JVM. Kotlin har verktøyene som trengs for å skrive sikre og robuste applikasjoner med færre kodelinjer takket være en streng kompilator og pragmatisk språkdesign.\n\nLær det du trenger å vite for å komme i gang med Kotlin. Forstå hvilke fordeler Kotlin kan gi innenfor sikkerhet og kortfattethet. Bruk det i ditt neste prosjekt eller introduser det i en eksisterende Java-kodebase.","published":"true","title":"Kotlin: Pragmatisk programmering på JVM","slug":"kotlin_pragmatisk_programmering_"},{"intendedAudience":"If you're interested in software defined infrastructure, IT-automation, cloud or devops, this presentation is for you. Expect lots and lots of live coding.","keywords":["devops","cloud","infrastructure"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Stefan Magnus Landrø","bio":"I currently work with the Oslo-based IT consultancy Bekk Consulting. 15 years industry experience, creating and running business critical applications and services. Open source, cloud and bringing the industry forward, makes me tick. Frequent speaker at conferences.","sessionId":"8ffb66a27010431eb6c4df5bd08c2ab6"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"8ffb66a27010431eb6c4df5bd08c2ab6","abstract":"Terraform is a tool for defining, creating and changing versioned infrastructure in a safe and efficient way. The tool lets you define infrastructure using a simple JSON-like syntax, and services from different cloud providers, both public and private, can be combined to create advanced setups.\n\nTerraform being provider agnostic, all kinds of services ranging from low-level resources like virtual machines and disk storage, to high level services like DNS and email can be managed. \n\nThis presentation is packed with demos, showcasing most of the features found in Terraform.","published":"true","title":"Terraform - colonise the cloud!","slug":"terraform__colonise_the_cloud"},{"intendedAudience":"no code... well... probably not :)","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Ken Sipe","bio":"An American man who has seen more of Norway than most norwegians and is learning the viking ways.","sessionId":"8beea5ac5a244613ae0bca52a60840ec"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"8beea5ac5a244613ae0bca52a60840ec","abstract":"This is a talk on my experience learning Norwegian this year!   \n\nKen is an American man  that loves Norway.  He has traveled their way too often to excuse his ignorance of the language and is making every effort to fix that this year.   The lesson material that he picked up starts with \"An American man meets a Norwegian woman\".  Come see if Ken has any chance of getting lucky :)","published":"true","title":"An American Man moter en norsk kvinne","slug":"an_american_man_moter_en_norsk_k"},{"intendedAudience":"Code examples in slides","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Maria Khalusova","bio":"Maria is a JetBrains’ veteran and has participated in various projects since 2006: IntelliJ IDEA, TeamCity, AppCode. Currently she is a Product Marketing Manager in Upsource team. Maria is passionate about productivity tools, sharing knowledge and improving conversations.","sessionId":"8f1550ff123848568f418df747cab6c6"},{"name":"Trisha Gee","bio":"Trisha has developed Java applications for a range of industries, including finance, manufacturing, software and non-profit, for companies of all sizes. She has expertise in Java high performance systems, is passionate about enabling developer productivity, and dabbles with Open Source development. Trisha is a leader of the Sevilla Java User Group and a Java Champion. She believes we shouldn't all have to make the same mistakes again and again. She’s a Developer Advocate for JetBrains so she can share all the cool stuff she's discovered so far.","sessionId":"8f1550ff123848568f418df747cab6c6"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"8f1550ff123848568f418df747cab6c6","abstract":"A code review is basically a technical discussion which should lead to improvements in the code and/or sharing knowledge in a team. As with any conversation, it should have substance and form. \n\nWhat’s involved in a good code review? What kind of problems do we want to spot and address? Trisha Gee will talk about things a reviewer may consider when looking at changes:  what potential issues to look for; why certain patterns may be harmful; and, of course, what NOT to look at.\n\nBut when it comes to commenting on someone’s work, it may be hard to find the right words to convey a useful message without offending the authors - after all, this is something that they worked hard on. Maria Khalusova will share some observations, thoughts and practical tricks on how to give and receive feedback without turning a code review into a battlefield.","published":"true","title":"Code Review Matters and Manners","slug":"code_review_matters_and_manners"},{"intendedAudience":"Developers. Some code in slides. Maps in slides. Slides in slides. Oh, well, you get the point.","keywords":["maps","gis","android"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Khiem-Kim Ho Xuan","bio":"Khiem-Kim Ho Xuan is an IT consultant working for Computas AS. His interests are developing apps  and .NET applications.\nKhiem-Kim is also a competency network coordinator for .NET at Computas and also a member of the Norwegian Java User Group - javaBin.","sessionId":"43f15a3a777b441ea65ecc8ac3b0fc9d"},{"name":"Rustam Mehmandarov","bio":"Rustam Mehmandarov holds a master's degree in Computer Science from the University of Oslo. He has been working as a developer and lead programmer for 10 years. In addition to being passionate about agile development, web development, architecture and geographical information systems, he is also a guru of both Linux and Windows worlds. On his spare time he enjoys working out, as well as coding in Python and Java [but not simultaneously].\n\nLeader of the Norwegian Java User Group - javaBin, and of a professional network for databases and information management at work.\n\nHe is a frequent speaker at both national and international conferences and events such as JavaOne (USA), JavaZone (Norway), JavaLand (Germany), RigaDevDay (Latvia), NDC - Norwegian Developer Conference (Norway), Booster (Norway), Trondheim Developer Conference (Norway), Open Source Developers' Conference Nordic (Norway), and events at various Norwegian universities.","sessionId":"43f15a3a777b441ea65ecc8ac3b0fc9d"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"43f15a3a777b441ea65ecc8ac3b0fc9d","abstract":"You just zoom into the map until you start to see an indoor floor plan of the building. Then you use the level switcher to move between available floors in the building. Isn't that cool? Well, obviously it is. But it is also really useful.\n\nHave a look at what can be created when a map geek meets an Android geek. Oh, wait, you probably have seen the results already in the app. Well, come and see how we did it, and get a tour behind the scenes.","published":"true","title":"How We Built an Indoor Map For the JavaZone App. You Can Do That Too!","slug":"how_we_built_an_indoor_map_for_t"},{"intendedAudience":"You should be familiar with JavaScript and best-case you already have some React.JS experience, as I won't make a deep-dive into React.\n\nI'll have code in my slides as also some live demos.","keywords":["javascript","javaee","react"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Niko Köbler","bio":"Doing stuff with computers, mostly hacking (functional) on the JVM.\nAlso consulting and training business. Co-Lead of a local Java User Group.\nAuthor and Speaker at international tech conferences.\nTweeting at @dasniko.","sessionId":"be9af2fb0e9e4aeea679e9e23f49070c"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"be9af2fb0e9e4aeea679e9e23f49070c","abstract":"Isomorphic (greek: \"isos\" = equal, \"morph\" = shape) JavaScript apps are applications that can run the same code on both client-side and server-side. Isomorphism describes that if you look at the same entity in two different contexts, you should get the same thing. Here the contexts are server and client. Although the term has been mostly used in mathematics until now, it's an apt term to describe a web programing pattern where the code is shared by the front-end and back-end.\nJust take an MVC-based Java framework, like the new Java EE 8 MVC 1.0, integrate it with Nashorn and use the famous JavaScript templating engine React.JS (developed by Facebook) as the \"V\"iew layer in MVC - that's it. Now you can render templates on the server- as also on the client side - or start rendering serverside, send them to the client and finish there! Nothing is impossible - even Netflix uses it!","published":"true","title":"Isomorphic JavaScript apps with Nashorn, React.JS and Java EE MVC","slug":"isomorphic_javascript_apps_with_"},{"intendedAudience":"Lyntalen er ment for alle som ønsker å høre hvordan det offentlige i kan samarbeide om utvikling av felleskomponenter. Selve lyntalen vil være basert på erfaringer og utfallet av samarbeidet.","keywords":["opensource","collaboration","github.com"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Kennet Vuong","bio":"Kennet fullførte sin mastergrad i Informatikk våren 2015 og startet i Knowit august 2015 som konsulent. Kennet har raskt gått fra DevOps utvikler til en større rolle som utviklingsleder og teamleder i sitt nye prosjekt.\nKennet er en ivrig utvikler som stadig er på jakt etter nye utfordringer og teknologier. Han ser på seg selv som en full-stack utvikler som trives like godt på frontend og backend. Kennet har stor interesse for teknologi og er stadig på jakt etter nye og kule teknologier. I tillegg har Kennet sansen for funksjonell programmering og spesielt Clojure.","sessionId":"3f4aeba4280d4a15b53fc0580a6f099d"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"3f4aeba4280d4a15b53fc0580a6f099d","abstract":"De offentlige har begynt å dele på github! I denne lyntalen skal vi se på hvordan Oslo kommune og Direktoratet for forvaltning of IKT (Difi)  samarbeider om å bygge felleskomponenter gjennom åpen kildekode. Lyntalen beskriver samarbeidet på et teknisk nivå med stikkord som: deling av åpen kildekode, verktøy for samarbeid i utviklingsprosessen, bruk av open source-modeller og litt om hvordan du også kan bidra for å gjøre nasjonale felleskomponenter enda bedre!","published":"true","title":"Hvordan Oslo Kommune og Difi samarbeider om åpen kildekode","slug":"hvordan_oslo_kommune_og_difi_sam"},{"intendedAudience":"G1 GC will be the default collector in JDK 9. Anyone that would like to get more details on the default garbage collector and wants to understand the internals as well as take home some tuning advice is welcome to attend. The slides will have lots of GC logs (using the new logging format introduced in JDK 9). The author will also include GCHisto and JFreeCharts to provide GC information to the attendees.","keywords":["garbage collection, g1 gc, java 9 gc logging"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Monica Beckwith","bio":"Monica Beckwith is an Independent Consultant specializing in optimizing the Java Virtual Machine and the Garbage Collectors for enterprise applications. She is a regular speaker at various conferences and has several published articles on topics including garbage collection, the Java memory model and others. Monica led Oracle's Garbage First Garbage Collector performance team, and was named a JavaOne 2013 Rock Star.","sessionId":"90b83ec5560842c3be236a847a822904"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"90b83ec5560842c3be236a847a822904","abstract":"This is a Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1 GC) readiness session. In this session, attendees will learn more about G1 pause (young and mixed) composition, G1's remembered sets and collection set and G1's concurrent marking phase. The speaker will also cover performance tuning advice for \"taming\" mixed collections and evacuation failures.","published":"true","title":"Java 9: The (G1) GC Awakens!","slug":"java_9_the_g1_gc_awakens"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette er en presentasjon for deg som ønsker å høre om praktiske erfaringer ved bruk av jwt i et bredt systemlandskap, hvor kanal til sluttbrukere er både web og intraweb. Dette involverer hvordan single sign-on løsninger samhandler både med applikasjoner og underliggende integrasjoner.  Code level: \"Code in slides\"","keywords":["sikkerhet","jwt","sso"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Per Otto Bergum Christensen","bio":"Per Otto er fagansvarlig for Java og integrasjon i Eika og har jobbet med utvikling på Java-plattformen i over 16 år. I Eika jobber Per Otto i prosjekter og med behov som går på tvers. Han møter hele tiden utfordringer sammen med team på jakt etter løsninger som lar seg realisere effektivt i en fungerende første versjon, eller hvor det er behov for utvidelser av eksisterende løsninger.","sessionId":"7f83c1b700f848e68f54620e9d41e390"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"7f83c1b700f848e68f54620e9d41e390","abstract":"I kategorien ikke-funksjonelle krav er sikkerhet og sporbarhet blant de viktigste, men ofte prioritert ned eller glemt i jakten på ny funksjonalitet. \n\nNår så sikkerhet kommer i fokus er det lett å bli paralysert av utfordringen. Det naturlige kravet er single sign-on og sporbarhet mellom alle applikasjoner og systemer. Finnes det et produkt som kan kjøpes? Vil et prosjekt kunne implementere det? \n\nDenne lyntalen handler om enkel teknologi og mekanismer for sikkerhet og sporbarhet mellom applikasjoner på web/intraweb og fagsystemer. JSON Web Token (jwt) brukes som underliggende standard, og det blir presentert bruk av både tredjeparts-biblioteker og skreddersydde løsninger for sikkert å spore en brukers handlinger i systemet.","published":"true","title":"Sikkerhet er ikke en one stop shop!","slug":"sikkerhet_er_ikke_en_one_stop_sh"},{"intendedAudience":"This session is for anyone who are curious about other languages on the JVM or about Haskell. No previous knowledge about Haskell or functional programming is assumed. There will be code in slides which will be explained as we go.","keywords":["functionalprogramming","haskell","programminglanguages"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Erlend Hamberg","bio":"Erlend Hamberg started a on computer engineering degree to learn about systems programming and hardware, but veered slightly off course and ended up with a degree in computer science with a specialization in artificial intelligence. He loves functional programming – especially in languages with strong type systems, but still has a weak spot in his heart for C. When not tinkering with programming or programming language theory he can be found kayaking in the Oslo fjord.","sessionId":"95b4378d70514d58a55becd4c388b6ab"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"95b4378d70514d58a55becd4c388b6ab","abstract":"This is your chance of being the ultimate JVM hipster and use a language “before it was cool”.\n\nFrege is an implementation of the Haskell programming language on the JVM and was voted the most popular of the “upcoming languages” at last year's JavaOne conference. With Scala being the elephant in the functional programming room on planet JVM, can Frege be a serious contender? We'll have a look at what makes the language unique by walking through some simple code examples and then look at how Frege code can be called from Java and vice versa.","published":"true","title":"Off the Deep End: Haskell on the JVM","slug":"off_the_deep_end_haskell_on_the_"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette er en presentasjon for JavaScript-utviklere som er nysgjerrige på alternative verktøy for å bli mer produktive.\n\nDet vil vises kode i presentasjonen.","keywords":["clojurescript","web","productivity"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Odin Standal","bio":"Odin er en Kodemaker og sivilingeniør i datateknikk som liker å fylle verktøykassen. Etter å ha jobbet med ClojureScript i flere prosjekter med stor sukess er han nå overbevist om at funksjonell programmering ofte kan lede til mer robuste løsninger på en raskere måte.","sessionId":"8c5e656b971b46a0a7da8e5210505d33"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"8c5e656b971b46a0a7da8e5210505d33","abstract":"Trenden i webutvikling går mot mer og mer avanserte klienter skrevet i JavaScript. Denne økte kompleksiteten forsøker vi å håndtere gjennom ting som ES2016,  bibliotek for funksjonell programmering, immutability, promises og en god dose disiplin. \n\nClojureScript er et pragmatisk språk som hjelper deg til å lage enklere løsninger. \nDenne presentasjonen vil belyse flere grunner til at ClojureScript er verdt \nå vurdere til ditt neste prosjekt.\n\nKom for å se hvordan et språk kan tilby deg store fordeler og glede, hvis du bare er villig til å lære deg noe ganske annerledes enn det du er vant til.","published":"true","title":"3 grunner til at ClojureScript gir deg superkrefter","slug":"3_grunner_til_at_clojurescript_g"},{"intendedAudience":"The attendees should know JUnit and how to write tests with it. After the talk they will know why JUnit 5 was necessary, how to use and how it might improve testing on the JVM for all frameworks.\n\nThere will be code in slides.","keywords":["testing","junit"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Nicolai Parlog","bio":"I'm a thirty year old boy, as the narrator would put it, who has found his passion in software development. I constantly read, think, and write about it, and code for a living as well as for fun.\n\nI work as at Disy, Germany's leading provider for spatial and environmental IT-solutions, where I improve the flagship product. I blog about software development on codefx.org and am a long-tail contributor to several open source projects.\n\nI have supported the crowdfunding campaign and followed the project ever since. Back in 2015, I wrote about the prototype (http://blog.codefx.org/libraries/junit-lambda-prototype/),  after its release in February I started playing around (http://blog.disy.net/aarlaubstag-junit5-rust-graphml/) with the alpha version, and I have visited talks about the topic by members of the team. An article for InfoQ is in the making and an interview with the team is planned.\n\nThat being said, I am just a voracious consumer of publicly available information about the project but am not affiliated with the developer team.","sessionId":"51dcde1576c44e5f84f37316cd5bc5f3"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"51dcde1576c44e5f84f37316cd5bc5f3","abstract":"Java's most ubiquitous library is getting an update!\nAnd this is the time to see what's new and weigh in on its course.\n\nThis talk will...\n\n* show you how to write tests with JUnit 5\n* walk you through the changes compared to JUnit 4\n* present the new architecture\n* discuss compatibility with previous JUnit versions, IDEs, and other testing tools\n\nBe careful, though:\nYou might end up with an urge to start using it right away.","published":"true","title":"JUnit 5: Next Generation Testing on the JVM","slug":"junit_5_next_generation_testing_"},{"intendedAudience":"Coding, Javascript experience necessary.","keywords":["javascript","chrome"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Lars Barlindhaug","bio":"Loves to solve problems. Consultant at Iterate.","sessionId":"36c42e25bb704cdc9991579d6b5807af"}],"format":"workshop","language":"no","sessionId":"36c42e25bb704cdc9991579d6b5807af","abstract":"Chrome Developer Tools er tilgjengelig i alle Chrome installasjoner, men få kjenner til alle mulighetene. Å se på DOM elementer og lese console output er kjent for mange, men den kan også brukes som editor, analysere ytelse og finne minnelekasjer. Etterhvert som Javascript-applikasjoner blir mer komplekse blir avansert bruk av Chrome Developer Tools nødvendig for å skjønne hvordan applikasjonen fungerer.\n\nI løpet av 2 timer skal vi blant annet se på hvordan åpne og endre lokale filer direkte i Chrome med sourcemaps og hvordan bruke CPU profile og flame chart for å finne kilden til ytelsesproblemer.","published":"true","title":"Alt du ikke visste om Chrome Developer Tools","slug":"alt_du_ikke_visste_om_chrome_dev"},{"intendedAudience":"Alle som er interessert i og nysgjerrig på maskinlæring. \"No code\"","keywords":["machinelearning"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Vegard Hartmann","bio":"Vegard fullførte en master i kunstig intelligens i 2005. Etter det har han jobbet som IT-konsulent og er nå leder for IT-rådgivning i BEKK. Etter mange år som konsulent er studiet endelig relevant for jobben. Vegard kombinerer teknisk innsikt om kunstig intelligens og maskinlæring med kunnskap om hvordan det kan tas i bruk i virksomheter og hva det betyr for forretningssiden.","sessionId":"d78e969980e24f23bb6d60386b83530e"}],"format":"lightning-talk","language":"no","sessionId":"d78e969980e24f23bb6d60386b83530e","abstract":"John McCarthy innførte begrepet 'kunstig intelligens' i 1955 som en betegnelse på vitenskapen knyttet til det å lage intelligente maskiner. Fire år senere introduserte Arthur Samuel begrepet 'maskinlæring'.\n\nHvorfor har vi først nå begynt å snakke om disse tingene? Hva er egentlig maskinlæring og hva kan det gjøre for virksomheter? Alt dette, og mye mer, vil du få vite mer om i kontekst av dataanalyse.","published":"true","title":"Maskinlæring - Hva er det og hvorfor snakker vi om det?","slug":"maskinlring__hva_er_det_og_hvorf"},{"intendedAudience":"This is an introductory talk. I require no previous experience with any of the above techniques.\nI will show some Java, Python, and JavaScript code in the slides. However, Java developers will be able to make sense of this code.","keywords":["elasticsearch","big data","visualisation"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Oliver Zeigermann","bio":"Oliver Zeigermann is a developer and consultant from Hamburg, Germany. He has developed software in many different languages and technologies over the past couple of decades, including C, C++, Java, Python, and JavaScript.\n\nFor the past few years he dived into the analysis of larger sizes of data using machine learning and/or data visualisation techniques. Among other things, he contributed to interactive visualisations to Graylog, an Elasticsearch based log management software.","sessionId":"86c205f79e8b466e9ae008a2fc46d52f"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"86c205f79e8b466e9ae008a2fc46d52f","abstract":"Interactive visualizations of large sets of data allow for completely new ways of exploring it. They are no longer static images that can be used to tell a story, but rather allow to inspect the world at a macroscopic level. Putting those visualizations into a zero-install environment like the browser makes the data accessible to anyone who has the domain knowledge but not necessarily a very technical background.\n\nBased on a real project I will lead you through the phases of data visualisation. Preparation using pandas and pyelasticsearch. Storing and providing the data using Elasticsearch. Eventually, displaying data in the most interactive way in the browser using D3.","published":"true","title":"Worlds, not Stories: Data Exploration in the browser using Elasticsearch, Pandas, and D3","slug":"worlds_not_stories_data_explorat"},{"intendedAudience":"Dette er en gøy workshop for alle utviklere, og det spiller ingen trille om du er superarkitekt eller er i din spede begynnelse på karrieren. Workshopen gir et innblikk i hvor enkelt man kan lage en 3D-opplevelse på mobil. Eneste forutsetningen er grunnleggende forståelse for Java. Android-kompetanse er et pluss.\n\nCode in slides","keywords":["android","virtual reality"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Thomas Pettersen","bio":"Tech Lead Mobil i Mesan. Har jobbet siden 2010 med utvikling av mobilapplikasjoner, med hovedvekt på Android og mobile backends. Er lidenskapelig interessert i tekniske duppedingser, molekylær gastronomi og jordbærfisk, og deler mer enn gjerne dette med omverden (om man ser bort fra jordbærfisken..!)","sessionId":"e5760dae310146cc896d3a978db4d7ee"}],"format":"workshop","language":"no","sessionId":"e5760dae310146cc896d3a978db4d7ee","abstract":"Er du klar for en smakebit på fremtidens gaming? Mesan tar deg med på en reise inn i det noe uvanlige, hvor vi skal utforske Virtual Reality og hvordan man kan lage enkle spill i full 3D ved hjelp av enkle virkemidler som papp og en mobil. Her snakker vi workshop i Android-utvikling med Java og OpenGL, Google Cardboards, matematikk og en god dose fantasi. Dette blir gøy! Vi stiller med utstyr og info, du stiller med pågangsmot og kreativitet. Ta gjerne med din egen Android-telefon om du har. Vel møtt!","published":"true","title":"VR for alle!","slug":"vr_for_alle"},{"intendedAudience":"What we expect from you:\n• Not afraid to use a shell, though commands will be served\n• Hands-on\n• Eager to learn a new technology\n• Not afraid to ask questions\n\nYou will need to bring your own laptop with 5GB free disk space. A virtual machine for VirtualBox will be provided to get you started.\n\nFor setup instructions, follow this link:\nhttps://github.com/mbertani/elk-workshop/tree/javazone2016","keywords":["loganalysis","devops","datascience"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Sigmund Hansen","bio":"Sigmund works at Computas and is the manager of test and dev environments, builds and releases of case management software used by Norwegian courts. He is also responsible for analysing error logs from the production environment, and uses ELK for these purposes, creating dashboards to quickly get a view of the state of affairs in production. Sigmund has been a Java hobbyist since 1998. At university he specialized in programming languages, language theory, data structures and algorithms. He has teaching and speaking experience from university, game jams, conferences and the Norwegian Lær Kidsa Koding (Teaching Children Code), and has taught semantic web, data structures and algorithms, ELK and object-oriented, game and microcontroller programming.","sessionId":"2da4d53d67064b7592c1d5f64b5840c3"},{"name":"Marco Bertani-Økland","bio":"Marco is a mathematician and software developer working at Computas. Marco has worked at several projects for Politiets IKT Tjenester (PIT). Among these, has Marco used ELK for data visualization and real-time analytics for Norways Police crime case management system. He has also held workshops for PIT's middelware unit, to help them define their logging architecture with ELK. He has a strong interest in machine learning, data visualization, predictive policing, functional programming and Mathematics.","sessionId":"2da4d53d67064b7592c1d5f64b5840c3"}],"format":"workshop","language":"en","sessionId":"2da4d53d67064b7592c1d5f64b5840c3","abstract":"The LAPD makes crime report data publicly available. In this workshop you will get your hands dirty and learn to use ELK to analyze these data. ELK consist of three open source projects — Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana — designed to take data from any source and search, analyze, and visualize it in real time. The philosophy behind these tools is that getting immediate, actionable insight from data matters.\n\nDuring this workshop we will teach you how to:\n• Get ELK up and running\n• Configure Logstash to process data on LAPD crime reports\n• Configure Logstash to pass the processed data to Elasticsearch\n• Define a mapping template in elasticsearch to shape our data, so that you can both search and aggregate.\n• Visualize the data in Kibana. Create a dashboard with a map, graphcs and tables to get insights from the data.\n \nIf time allows, we will show you examples on how to parse HTTP access logs and/or Java stack trace logs.\n\nFor more information, take a look at https://www.elastic.co/","published":"true","title":"Law and Order in LA - To Process and Search with ELK","slug":"law_and_order_in_la__to_process_"},{"intendedAudience":"Front-end developers with passion to UX. Accessibility evangelists. Responsive and adaptive UIs heroes. Live coding.","keywords":["angular material 2","ui","accessibility"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Maxim Salnikov","bio":"Maxim Salnikov is Oslo-based web UI developer, a Google Developer Expert in Angular with strong passion to mobile. He has 10+ years experience in development front-ends for complex web applications. He knows everything about web front-end: starting from user interfaces prototyping, going through HTML/CSS/JS implementation and finishing with architecting RESTful APIs.\nWorking daily with web front-end technologies he is happy to experiment with the same stack for building hybrid mobile apps using latest hybrid frameworks.\n\nOn evenings he runs Norway’s largest meetups dedicated to web front-end: Framsia, AngularJS Oslo. Also he is leader of Norway's biggest community dedicated to mobile development (Mobile Meetup Oslo) and currently working on organizing conference for mobile developers in 2016.\n\nMaxim likes to travel the world visiting developers events and sharing his experiences and knowledge by speaking at conferences and meetups.","sessionId":"8d92cd46ae584459a66cc83ab6cc6b81"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"8d92cd46ae584459a66cc83ab6cc6b81","abstract":"Our amazing web applications need high-quality UI components. So we have Angular 2 app on one hand and Material Design visual language on another. How to combine these without calling designer and spending days on struggling with CSS cross-platform issues and re-inventing client-side code for common UI scenarios? Right! Angular Material 2, set of reusable, well-tested, and accessible UI components, is going to solve this issue. It's still under active development but we can look behind the scenes and create our cross-platform, UI-rich app just in minutes. Let's go exploring and coding!\n\nBonus: after our app is created we'll check its Accessibility, how it's automagically added by Angular Material 2 to allow users of all abilities to navigate, understand, and use our UI successfully.","published":"true","title":"Angular Material 2: Reward your app with high-quality UI in minutes","slug":"angular_material_2_reward_your_a"},{"intendedAudience":"Experienced Java developers, including Android developers. The presentation will include code in slides.","keywords":["android","opencv","computer vision"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Johannes Brodwall","bio":"Johannes Brodwall works for Sopra Steria Norway. He creates software.\n\nJohannes has been working as a programmer, architect, agile coach and programmer again for 15 years. He has worked as architect in large public sector projects to create nationally strategic infrastructure, in small 1-2 person private sector teams to create internal apps to improve work processes and everything in between.\n\nHe has been a speaker at conferences in Norway, eastern Europe and south Asia and is also active as a conference organizer in Norway.","sessionId":"474f7829e5c3438ea013dcb3a63c2c3b"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"474f7829e5c3438ea013dcb3a63c2c3b","abstract":"What could you do if your phone could understand what it sees?\n\nIn this talk, we go though how to get an Android application to recognize what's on a picture by using OpenCV. Most of the code is not Android specific so the code will be relevant for non-mobile developers as well.\n\nThe talk will cover how to integrate with the camera, how to detect and track objects you are interested and how to classify parts of the image.","published":"true","title":"Computer vision for mobile Java developers","slug":"computer_vision_for_mobile_java_"},{"intendedAudience":"* DevOps who want to know an easy way to monitor Java applications via JMX\n* Anybody using Jolokia 1.0 who wants to know about the forthcoming new features\n* Basic to medium Java skills required (would be good if 'JMX' is not something completely new)\n* Live demos","keywords":["devops","monitoring","jmx"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Roland Huss","bio":"Roland Huss is a software engineer at Red Hat working in the xPaas team on fabric8. He has been developing in Java for nineteen years now but never forgot his roots as system administrator.\n\nRoland is an active open source contributor, lead developer of the JMX-HTTP bridge Jolokia and the popular fabric8io/docker-maven-plugin. And he loves chilli pepper.","sessionId":"69e388ea52b64e9bafbf631414ad7e09"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"69e388ea52b64e9bafbf631414ad7e09","abstract":"Jolokia is a JMX-HTTP bridge which alleviates the pain of accessing JMX remotely. It is an agent based approach with support for many platforms and is integrated into popular software like Spring Boot, ActiveMQ, hawt.io or OpenShift xPaaS Middleware Images.\n\nThe next major version 2.0 brings exciting new features: JMX notification support over HTTP, new backend providers in addition to JMX so that for example Spring beans can exposed over Jolokia directly plus an internal agent modularisation which allows for custom sized Jolokia agents with only the required features. \n\nThis talk starts with an overview over Jolokia and which problems it solves, before the Jolokia 2.0 features will be presented in an extensive live demo.\n\nAt the end you will have a good impression what is possible with JMX nowadays and how Jolokia can help you with your application monitoring and management tasks.","published":"true","title":"Jolokia 2.0","slug":"jolokia_20"},{"intendedAudience":"Attendees should be interested in Java Security, and Java Security Alternatives.  Attendees do not need to know Java Security objects, approaches, or techniques.  Code in slides.","keywords":[],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Scott Kramer","bio":"Scott Kramer currently works as a Lead “Hands-On” Architect for various clients.  Scott Kramer has over two decades of experience with technology leadership, enterprise architecture, application development and consulting having written and sold his first commercial program in high school.  Scott has worked on many different hardware devices, operating systems, languages and technology stacks including Single Board Computers, information gathering devices, multi-cored linked devices, and mainframes through personal computers.  Scott has experience in many languages and operating systems including MVS, Unix, and Microsoft, .NET, Java, C, and more.  Scott has certification in several technologies, and has been published in variety of subjects, written computer based training modules and has spoken on a variety of subjects at ChicagoJUG, IllinoisJUG, Chicago Coder Conference, and JavaOne.  Scott volunteers for many organizations including Chicago Java Users Group, Illinois Java Users Group, Coder Conference, Chicago Police, the Sheriff, and a Society for Global Citizenship (a disabled children’s organization).  Scott graduated from University of Wisconsin, and happily lives in Chicago with his wonderful wife.","sessionId":"59e23ffa261f48f6b7d7b96754161fdf"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"59e23ffa261f48f6b7d7b96754161fdf","abstract":"This presentation covers benefits and drawbacks of various popular Java EE microservices security approaches (Diffie-Hellman, RSA, HMAC) and looks at how to implement them in real-world examples. It explains why hash-based message authentication is best for microservice communication and has remained uncrackable. The presentation also shows that HMAC is fast, efficient, stateless, scalable, and DOS-resistant and can securely use any protocol and framework that supports messaging with headers, with no risk to the transport layer.","published":"true","title":"Securing your Java EE Microservice with HMAC Authentication","slug":"securing_your_java_ee_microservi"},{"intendedAudience":"Intermediate to advanced developers. JavaEE will benefit most.\n\nThere will be code in slides (both \"horror stories\" and best practices), and time permitting I will do live heapdump analyzis using Eclipse Memory Analyzer.","keywords":["memory leak","classloader leak","permgen space / metaspace"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Mattias Jiderhamn","bio":"Mattias Jiderhamn is an architect and development lead at Lexmark Enterprise Software. He has been developing in Java for 15 years, specializing on enterprise cloud solutions. He has declared war against ClassLoader leaks through his blog, where he maintains a long list of offending third party libraries and links to their bug reports, many of which he has submitted. He has released a ClassLoader Leak Prevention library with the hopes of saving the Java world from java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space/Metaspace. Thanks to this library, the Java EE application servers of his cloud solutions don't require any restarts despite continuous deploys.","sessionId":"70998aa524af45f28bee365a1e57e4c7"}],"format":"presentation","language":"en","sessionId":"70998aa524af45f28bee365a1e57e4c7","abstract":"Are you tired of java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space/Metaspace? Then this talk is for you! We'll begin with a crash course in the Java memory model in order to understand what the error message actually means. Then we'll look at different causes of the error and how to avoid them. We'll look at using Eclipse Memory Analyzer to track down memory leaks. We will glance at a few interesting mistakes from the Open Source world. Last but not least you'll learn how you can get rid of java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space / Metaspace once and for all, using the presenters ClassLoader Leak Prevention library.","published":"true","title":"Join my war on ClassLoader leaks","slug":"join_my_war_on_classloader_leaks"},{"intendedAudience":"Presentasjonen er rettet mot utviklere, arkitekter og metodister. Det vil være en del refleksjoner rundt bruk av teknologi, arkitektur og litt kode i slides.","keywords":["devops","mvp","microservices"],"conferenceId":"3baa25d3-9cca-459a-90d7-9fc349209289","speakers":[{"name":"Tor Åge Ballo","bio":"Tor Åge er en utvikler som er oppfostret, opplært og oppdratt i Skatteetaten. Direkte fra barneskolen(NTNU) har han blitt kastet ut i store prosjekter i etaten. Tor Åge har vært med på innføring av Java i Skatteetaten, og vært involvert i overgangen fra silosystemer til mikroarkitektur hvor hendelser er i sentrum. Tor Åge elsker utvikling, teknisk arkitektur og design og føler at dagen ikke er komplett uten å ha blitt skitten på hendene.","sessionId":"d323fee7d54843de95be0ea5bb7ec3ee"},{"name":"Jon Sølvberg","bio":"Currently working in Skatteetaten (Norwegian revenue authorities) since June 2015. Prior to this, long-standing experience in development of complex and critical business systems within the financial sector (Stock Exchange and CSD field) - both as a developer and acting as technical lead (since 2000). \n\nExpertise: Solution architecture,  software development with focus on Open Source technologies and JEE technologies.","sessionId":"d323fee7d54843de95be0ea5bb7ec3ee"}],"format":"presentation","language":"no","sessionId":"d323fee7d54843de95be0ea5bb7ec3ee","abstract":"Ett år før planen lanserer Skatteetaten en løsning for beregning av forskuddsskatt. Løsningen er i høyeste grad ufullstendig, men har per dags dato over en million potensielle brukere.\n\nHvordan er dette mulig? \n\nI Sofus-prosjektet i Skatteetaten har man valgt å levere løsningen bit for bit. Hver dag utvides løsningen og flere brukere kan få glede av ny funksjonalitet i nye applikasjoner.  Devops og kontinuerlige produksjonssettinger har vært sentrale suksessfaktorer for å kunne levere tjenestene gradvis. Det har også vært stort fokus på mikro-tjenester, plugin-arkitektur og generell uavhengighet for å kunne levere forskuddsberegning ett år før tiden.","published":"true","title":"Ufullstendig løsning prodsatt i Skatt!","slug":"ufullstendig_lsning_prodsatt_i_s"}]}